{"title_page": "Botlikh language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Botlikh\n|nativename=\u0411\u0443\u0439\u0445\u0430\u043b\u044a\u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0446I\u0446I\u0438/Bujxa\u0142i mic\u2019c\u2019i\n|states=[[Russia]]\n|region=Southwestern [[Dagestan]]<ref name=\"Ethmap\">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_map.asp?name=RUE&seq=10 Ethnologue language map of European Russia, with Botlikh shown in the inset with reference number 9]</ref>\n|ethnicity= \n|speakers=210\n|date=2010 census\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Caucasian\n|fam1=[[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]]\n|fam2=[[Avar\u2013Andic languages|Avar\u2013Andic]]\n|fam3=[[Andic languages|Andic]]\n|fam4=Akhvakh\u2013Tindi\n|fam5=Karata\u2013Tindi\n|fam6=Botlikh\u2013Tindi\n|iso3=bph\n|glotto=botl1242\n|glottorefname=Botlikh\n}}\n\n'''Botlikh''' (also spelled '''Botlix''') is an [[Andic languages|Andic language]] of the [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian language family]] spoken by the [[Botlikh people|Botlikhs]] in the [[Buikhe]] and [[Ashino]] villages in southwestern [[Dagestan]], [[Russia]] by approximately 210 people, according to the 2010 census.<ref name=\"e18\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eki.ee/books/redbook/botlikhs.shtml The peoples of the Red Book: Botlikhs]\n{{Northeast Caucasian languages}}\n{{Languages of the Caucasus}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Botlikh Language}}\n[[Category:Northeast Caucasian languages]]\n[[Category:Andic languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Russia]]\n[[Category:Endangered Caucasian languages]]\n\n\n{{NEC-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Botlikh\n|nativename=\u0411\u0443\u0439\u0445\u0430\u043b\u044a\u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0446I\u0446I\u0438/Bujxa\u0142i mic\u2019c\u2019i\n|states=[[Russia]]\n|region=Southwestern [[Dagestan]]<ref name=\"Ethmap\">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_map.asp?name=RUE&seq=10 Ethnologue language map of European Russia, with Botlikh shown in the inset with reference number 9]</ref>\n|ethnicity= \n|speakers=210\n|date=2010 census\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Caucasian\n|fam1=[[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]]\n|fam2=[[Avar\u2013Andic languages|Avar\u2013Andic]]\n|fam3=[[Andic languages|Andic]]\n|fam4=Akhvakh\u2013Tindi\n|fam5=Karata\u2013Tindi\n|fam6=Botlikh\u2013Tindi\n|iso3=bph\n|glotto=botl1242\n|glottorefname=Botlikh\n}}\n\n'''Botlikh''' (also spelled '''Botlix''') is an [[Andic languages|Andic language]] of the [[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian language family]] spoken by the [[Botlikh people|Botlikhs]] in the [[Buikhe]] and [[Ashino]] villages in southwestern [[Dagestan]], [[Russia]] by approximately 210 people, according to the 2010 census.<ref name=\"e18\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eki.ee/books/redbook/botlikhs.shtml The peoples of the Red Book: Botlikhs]\n{{Northeast Caucasian languages}}\n{{Languages of the Caucasus}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Botlikh Language}}\n[[Category:Northeast Caucasian languages]]\n[[Category:Andic languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Russia]]\n[[Category:Endangered Caucasian languages]]\n\n\n{{NEC-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Botlikh_language"}
{"title_page": "Bosha language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Bosha\n|nativename=Garo\n|states=[[Ethiopia]]\n|region=[[Kingdom of Garo]]\n|extinct=fl. through 19th century\n|familycolor=Afro-Asiatic\n|fam2=[[Omotic languages|Omotic]]\n|fam3=(see text)\n|iso3=none\n|iso3comment=(included in {{ethnolink|kbr}})\n|glotto=bosh1241\n|glottorefname=Bosha\n}}\n\n'''Bosha''' is an extinct [[Omotic language]] of [[Ethiopia]]. ''[[Ethnologue]]'' lists it as a dialect of the Northern Omotic [[Kafa language]], but notes that it may be a distinct language. Other sources list it as unclassified.<ref>Blench, 2006. [http://rogerblench.info/Language/Afroasiatic/General/AALIST.pdf The Afro-Asiatic Languages: Classification and Reference List]</ref> The Bosha state, the [[Kingdom of Garo]], was a culturally [[Gonga languages|Gonga]] enclave within the southern [[Oromo language|Oromo]] area.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:North Omotic languages]]\n\n\n{{Ethiopia-stub}}\n{{AfroAsiatic-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Bosha\n|nativename=Garo\n|states=[[Ethiopia]]\n|region=[[Kingdom of Garo]]\n|extinct=fl. through 19th century\n|familycolor=Afro-Asiatic\n|fam2=[[Omotic languages|Omotic]]\n|fam3=(see text)\n|iso3=none\n|iso3comment=(included in {{ethnolink|kbr}})\n|glotto=bosh1241\n|glottorefname=Bosha\n}}\n\n'''Bosha''' is an extinct [[Omotic language]] of [[Ethiopia]]. ''[[Ethnologue]]'' lists it as a dialect of the Northern Omotic [[Kafa language]], but notes that it may be a distinct language. Other sources list it as unclassified.<ref>Blench, 2006. [http://rogerblench.info/Language/Afroasiatic/General/AALIST.pdf The Afro-Asiatic Languages: Classification and Reference List]</ref> The Bosha state, the [[Kingdom of Garo]], was a culturally [[Gonga languages|Gonga]] enclave within the southern [[Oromo language|Oromo]] area.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Languages of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:North Omotic languages]]\n\n\n{{Ethiopia-stub}}\n{{AfroAsiatic-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bosha_language"}
{"title_page": "Boselewa language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Boselewa\n|altname=\n|states=[[Papua New Guinea]]\n|region=[[Fergusson Island]], [[Milne Bay Province]]\n|speakers=610\n|date=1999\n|ref=e18\n|ethnicity=spoken by 40% (1999?)<ref name=e15>{{e15|bwf}}</ref><!--both figs 1st appear here, so may be same date.  Later ethnic pop derives from this.-->\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Western Oceanic languages|Western Oceanic]]\n|fam5=[[Papuan Tip languages|Papuan Tip]]\n|fam6=[[Nuclear Papuan Tip languages|Nuclear Papuan Tip]]\n|fam7=[[North Papuan Mainland \u2013 D'Entrecasteaux languages|North Papuan Mainland \u2013 D'Entrecasteaux]]\n|fam8=Dobu\u2013Duau\n|iso3=bwf\n|glotto=bose1237\n|glottorefname=Boselewa\n}}\n\n'''Boselewa''' is a small [[Austronesian]] language spoken in the [[D'Entrecasteaux Islands]] of [[Papua New Guinea]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Papuan Tip languages}}\n{{Languages of Papua New Guinea}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Nuclear Papuan Tip languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Milne Bay Province]]\n[[Category:D'Entrecasteaux Islands]]\n[[Category:Languages of Papua New Guinea]]\n\n\n{{PapuaNewGuinea-stub}}\n{{PapuanTip-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Boselewa\n|altname=\n|states=[[Papua New Guinea]]\n|region=[[Fergusson Island]], [[Milne Bay Province]]\n|speakers=610\n|date=1999\n|ref=e18\n|ethnicity=spoken by 40% (1999?)<ref name=e15>{{e15|bwf}}</ref><!--both figs 1st appear here, so may be same date.  Later ethnic pop derives from this.-->\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Western Oceanic languages|Western Oceanic]]\n|fam5=[[Papuan Tip languages|Papuan Tip]]\n|fam6=[[Nuclear Papuan Tip languages|Nuclear Papuan Tip]]\n|fam7=[[North Papuan Mainland \u2013 D'Entrecasteaux languages|North Papuan Mainland \u2013 D'Entrecasteaux]]\n|fam8=Dobu\u2013Duau\n|iso3=bwf\n|glotto=bose1237\n|glottorefname=Boselewa\n}}\n\n'''Boselewa''' is a small [[Austronesian]] language spoken in the [[D'Entrecasteaux Islands]] of [[Papua New Guinea]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Papuan Tip languages}}\n{{Languages of Papua New Guinea}}\n\n[[Category:Nuclear Papuan Tip languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Milne Bay Province]]\n[[Category:D'Entrecasteaux Islands]]\n[[Category:Languages of Papua New Guinea]]\n\n\n{{PapuaNewGuinea-stub}}\n{{PapuanTip-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boselewa_language"}
{"title_page": "Bosavi languages", "text_new": "{{Infobox language family\n|name=Bosavi\n|altname=Papuan Plateau\n|region=[[Papuan Plateau]], [[Papua New Guinea]]\n|familycolor=Papuan\n|fam1=[[Trans\u2013New Guinea languages|Trans\u2013New Guinea]]\n|glotto=bosa1245\n|glottorefname=Bosavi\n|map=Bosavi languages.svg\n|mapcaption=Map:  The Bosavi languages of New Guinea\n{{legend|#FF5E5F|The Bosavi languages}}\n{{legend|#7BB5B6|Other Trans\u2013New Guinea languages}}\n{{legend|#D9D9D9|Other Papuan languages}}\n{{legend|#E09D00|Austronesian languages}}\n{{legend|white|Uninhabited}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Bosavi languages''' are a [[language family|family]] of the [[Trans\u2013New Guinea languages]] in the classifications of [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]] and Timothy Usher. The family is named after [[Mount Bosavi]] and the [[Papuan Plateau]].\n\n==Languages==\nThe languages, which are closely related (though they may have only 10\u201315% of their vocabulary in common),{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} are:<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/newguineaworld/families/trans-new-guinea/papuan-plateau New Guinea World]</ref>\n*[[Mount Bosavi]]: [[Kaluli language|Kaluli]]\u2013[[Sonia language|Sonia]], [[Aimele language|Aimele]] (Kware), [[Kasua language|Kasua]]\n*[[Onobasulu language|Onobasulu]]\n*[[Mount Sisa]]: [[Edolo language|Edolo]]\u2013[[Beami language|Beami]]\n*[[Dibiyaso language|Dibiyaso]] (Bainapi)\n\nThe unity of the Bosavi languages was quantitatively{{clarify|date=February 2020}} demonstrated by Evans and Greenhill (2017).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Evans |first1=Bethwyn |last2=Greenhill |first2=Simon |date=2017 |title=A combined comparative and phylogenetic analysis of the Bosavi and East Strickland languages |url=https://wlp.shh.mpg.de/4/abstracts/EvansGreenhill.pdf |journal=4th Workshop on the Languages of Papua |location=Universitas Negeri Papua, Manokwari, West Papua, Indonesia}}</ref>\n\n==Pronouns==\nPronouns are:\n\n:{|\n! !!sg!!pl\n|-\n!1\n|*na||*ni-\n|-\n!2\n|*ga||*gi-\n|-\n!3\n|*ya||*yi-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Malcolm Ross Pronouns}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Papuan languages}}\n{{Languages of Papua New Guinea}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Bosavi languages| ]]\n[[Category:Papuan Plateau languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language family\n|name=Bosavi\n|altname=Papuan Plateau\n|region=[[Papuan Plateau]], [[Papua New Guinea]]\n|familycolor=Papuan\n|fam1=[[Trans\u2013New Guinea languages|Trans\u2013New Guinea]]\n|glotto=bosa1245\n|glottorefname=Bosavi\n|map=Bosavi languages.svg\n|mapcaption=Map:  The Bosavi languages of New Guinea\n{{legend|#FF5E5F|The Bosavi languages}}\n{{legend|#7BB5B6|Other Trans\u2013New Guinea languages}}\n{{legend|#D9D9D9|Other Papuan languages}}\n{{legend|#E09D00|Austronesian languages}}\n{{legend|white|Uninhabited}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Bosavi languages''' are a [[language family|family]] of the [[Trans\u2013New Guinea languages]] in the classifications of [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]] and Timothy Usher. The family is named after [[Mount Bosavi]] and the [[Papuan Plateau]].\n\n==Languages==\nThe languages, which are closely related (though they may have only 10\u201315% of their vocabulary in common),{{cn|date=February 2020}} are:<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/newguineaworld/families/trans-new-guinea/papuan-plateau New Guinea World]</ref>\n*[[Mount Bosavi]]: [[Kaluli language|Kaluli]]\u2013[[Sonia language|Sonia]], [[Aimele language|Aimele]] (Kware), [[Kasua language|Kasua]]\n*[[Onobasulu language|Onobasulu]]\n*[[Mount Sisa]]: [[Edolo language|Edolo]]\u2013[[Beami language|Beami]]\n*[[Dibiyaso language|Dibiyaso]] (Bainapi)\n\nThe unity of the Bosavi languages was quantitatively{{what|date=February 2020}} demonstrated by Evans and Greenhill (2017).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Evans |first1=Bethwyn |last2=Greenhill |first2=Simon |date=2017 |title=A combined comparative and phylogenetic analysis of the Bosavi and East Strickland languages |url=https://wlp.shh.mpg.de/4/abstracts/EvansGreenhill.pdf |journal=4th Workshop on the Languages of Papua |location=Universitas Negeri Papua, Manokwari, West Papua, Indonesia}}</ref>\n\n==Pronouns==\nPronouns are:\n\n:{|\n! !!sg!!pl\n|-\n!1\n|*na||*ni-\n|-\n!2\n|*ga||*gi-\n|-\n!3\n|*ya||*yi-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Malcolm Ross Pronouns}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Papuan languages}}\n{{Languages of Papua New Guinea}}\n[[Category:Languages of Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Bosavi languages| ]]\n\n[[Category:Papuan Plateau languages]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bosavi_languages"}
{"title_page": "Boruca language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Boruca\n|altname     = Bronca\n|states      = [[Costa Rica]]\n|ethnicity   = one thousand [[Boruca people]] (1991)<ref name=e18/>\n|speakers    = 3\n|date        = 2007\n|ref         = e18\n|familycolor = American\n|fam1        = [[Chibchan]]\n|fam2        = \n|iso3        = brn\n|glotto=boru1252\n|glottorefname=Boruca\n}}\n\nThe '''Boruca language''' (also known as '''Bronka''', '''Bronca''' or '''Br\u00fankajk'''.) is the native language of the [[Boruca]] people of [[Costa Rica]]. It is one of the [[Chibchan languages]]. It is nearly extinct; it was spoken fluently by only five women in 1986, while 30 to 35 others spoke it non-fluently. The rest of the tribe's 1,000 members speak [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. The language is taught as a second language at the local primary school Escuela Doris Z. Stone. One can hear Bronka words and phrases mixed into Spanish conversations but it is extremely rare to hear prolonged exchanges in Bronka.\n\nGreetings:\n\n'''\u00bfIsh\u00f3jcre r\u00e1ban?''' = What's up?\n\n'''Mor\u00e9n, mor\u00e9n.''' = Fine, well.<ref>{{cite book|last=Maroto Rojas|first=Esp\u00edritu Santo|title=Lengua o dialecto Boruca o Brunkajk|year=1999|publisher=Editorial de la Universidad de Costa Rica|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|isbn=9977-67-554-6|page=49|version=(in Spanish and Boruca)|chapter=Palabras varias Saludos}}</ref>\n\nThe personal pronouns in Boruca (the '''\u02c7''' represents a glottal stop.)<ref>{{cite book|last=Quesada Pacheco|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|title=Hablemos Boruca|year=1995|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|isbn=9977-60-114-3|page=33|version=(in Spanish and Boruca)}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Person !! Singular !! Plural\n|-\n| 1st || \u00e1t || di\u02c7 / di\u02c7 r\u00f3jc\n|-\n| 2nd || b\u00e1 || bi\u02c7 / bi\u02c7 r\u00f3jc\n|-\n| 3rd || i || i r\u00f3jc / i\u02c7 r\u00f3jc\n|}\n\nThe numbers (the \"\u1e45\" is used in place of an \"n\" with the [[diaeresis (diacritic)|diaeresis]] \"\u00a8\" over top, as this character is unavailable; \"\u1e45\" represents a slightly different sound from the normal n or \u00f1.)<ref>{{cite book|last=Quesada Pacheco|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|title=Hablemos boruca|year=1995|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|isbn=9977-60-114-3|page=82|version=(in Spanish and Boruca)}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Numbers !! Bronka\n|-\n| 1 || \u00e9\u02c7xe, \u00e9\u02c7xi\n|-\n| 2 || b\u00fa\u02c7c\n|-\n| 3 || ma\u1e45\n|-\n| 4 || b\u00e1jca\u1e45\n|-\n| 5 || shishc\u00e1\u1e45\n|-\n| 6 || t\u00e9shan\n|-\n| 7 || c\u00faj, c\u00fajc\n|-\n| 8 || \u00e9jta\u1e45\n|-\n| 9 || c\u00fajta\u1e45, \u00e9jcuj\n|-\n| 10 || t\u00e9jcuj, cr\u00f3shta\u1e45, b\u00fa\u02c7c c\u00faj\n|}\n\n[https://maps.google.com/maps?q=map+boruca&hl=en&ll=9.001919,-83.324497&spn=0.00569,0.009184&t=h&z=17 Map of Boruca]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Brunca Sign Language]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Chibchan languages}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Chibchan languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Endangered Chibchan languages]]\n\n\n{{CostaRica-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Boruca\n|altname     = Bronca\n|states      = [[Costa Rica]]\n|ethnicity   = one thousand [[Boruca people]] (1991)<ref name=e18/>\n|speakers    = 3\n|date        = 2007\n|ref         = e18\n|familycolor = American\n|fam1        = [[Chibchan]]\n|fam2        = \n|iso3        = brn\n|glotto=boru1252\n|glottorefname=Boruca\n}}\n\nThe '''Boruca language''' (also known as '''Bronka''', '''Bronca''' or '''Br\u00fankajk'''.) is the native language of the [[Boruca]] people of [[Costa Rica]]. It is one of the [[Chibchan languages]]. It is nearly extinct; it was spoken fluently by only five women in 1986, while 30 to 35 others spoke it non-fluently. The rest of the tribe's 1,000 members speak [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. The language is taught as a second language at the local primary school Escuela Doris Z. Stone. One can hear Bronka words and phrases mixed into Spanish conversations but it is extremely rare to hear prolonged exchanges in Bronka.\n\nGreetings:\n\n'''\u00bfIsh\u00f3jcre r\u00e1ban?''' = What's up?\n\n'''Mor\u00e9n, mor\u00e9n.''' = Fine, well.<ref>{{cite book|last=Maroto Rojas|first=Esp\u00edritu Santo|title=Lengua o dialecto Boruca o Brunkajk|year=1999|publisher=Editorial de la Universidad de Costa Rica|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|isbn=9977-67-554-6|page=49|version=(in Spanish and [[Boruca language|Boruca]])|chapter=Palabras varias Saludos}}</ref> \n\nThe personal pronouns in Boruca (the '''\u02c7''' represents a glottal stop.)<ref>{{cite book|last=Quesada Pacheco|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|title=Hablemos Boruca|year=1995|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|isbn=9977-60-114-3|page=33|version=(in Spanish and [[Boruca language|Boruca]])}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Person !! Singular !! Plural\n|-\n| 1st || \u00e1t || di\u02c7 / di\u02c7 r\u00f3jc\n|-\n| 2nd || b\u00e1 || bi\u02c7 / bi\u02c7 r\u00f3jc\n|-\n| 3rd || i || i r\u00f3jc / i\u02c7 r\u00f3jc\n|}\n\nThe numbers (the \"\u1e45\" is used in place of an \"n\" with the [[diaeresis (diacritic)|diaeresis]] \"\u00a8\" over top, as this character is unavailable; \"\u1e45\" represents a slightly different sound from the normal n or \u00f1.)<ref>{{cite book|last=Quesada Pacheco|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|title=Hablemos boruca|year=1995|publisher=Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica|location=San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|isbn=9977-60-114-3|page=82|version=(in Spanish and [[Boruca language|Boruca]])}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Numbers !! Bronka\n|-\n| 1 || \u00e9\u02c7xe, \u00e9\u02c7xi\n|-\n| 2 || b\u00fa\u02c7c\n|-\n| 3 || ma\u1e45\n|-\n| 4 || b\u00e1jca\u1e45\n|-\n| 5 || shishc\u00e1\u1e45\n|-\n| 6 || t\u00e9shan\n|-\n| 7 || c\u00faj, c\u00fajc\n|-\n| 8 || \u00e9jta\u1e45\n|-\n| 9 || c\u00fajta\u1e45, \u00e9jcuj\n|-\n| 10 || t\u00e9jcuj, cr\u00f3shta\u1e45, b\u00fa\u02c7c c\u00faj\n|}\n\n[https://maps.google.com/maps?q=map+boruca&hl=en&ll=9.001919,-83.324497&spn=0.00569,0.009184&t=h&z=17 Map of Boruca]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Brunca Sign Language]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Chibchan languages}}\n[[Category:Chibchan languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Endangered Chibchan languages]]\n\n\n{{CostaRica-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boruca_language"}
{"title_page": "Boro\u2013Garo languages", "text_new": "{{Infobox language family\n|name=Boro\u2013Garo\n|altname=\n|region=[[Northeast India]], [[Bangladesh]]\n|familycolor=Sino-Tibetan\n|fam2=[[Sal languages|Sal]]<ref>Also known as Boro-Konyak-Jingpho or Brahmaputran.</ref>\n|child1=[[Bodo languages|Boro]]\n|child2=[[Garo languages|Garo]]\n|child3=[[Koch languages|Koch]]\n|child4=[[Deori language|Deori]]  |child5=[[kokborok]]\n|glotto=bodo1279\n|glottorefname=Bodo-Garo\n}}\n\nThe '''Boro\u2013Garo languages''' are a branch of [[Sino-Tibetan languages]],  spoken primarily in [[Northeast India]] and parts of [[Bangladesh]].\n\nThe Boro\u2013Garo languages form four groups: Boro, Garo, Koch and Deori.  Boro\u2013Garo languages were historically very widespread throughout the [[Brahmaputra Valley]] and in what are now the northern parts of [[Bangladesh]],<ref name=\"Jacquesson2017\"/> and it is speculated that the proto-Boro-Garo language was the lingua franca of the Brahmaputra valley before it was replaced by [[Assamese language]], to which it has made major contributions.\n\n==Branches==\nThe Boro\u2013Garo languages are:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name in LSI\n! Modern names\n|-\n| Bodo \n| [[Bodo language|Boro]]\n|-\n| Lalung \n| [[Tiwa language (India)|Tiwa]]\n|-\n| Dimasa \n| [[Dimasa language|Dimasa]]\n|-\n| Garo \n| [[Garo language|Garo]]\n|-\n| Rabha \n| [[Rabha language|Rabha]]\n|-\n| Tipura \n| [[Kokborok language|Kokborok]]\n|- \n| Chutiya \n| [[Deori language|Deori]]\n|- \n| Moran \n| [[Moran language|Moran]] (since disappeared)\n|}\n\n*'''[[Bodo languages]]''': [[Bodo language|Bodo]], [[Dimasa language|Dimasa]], [[Tiwa language (India)|Tiwa]], [[Kokborok]] (Tripuri), [[Kachari language|Kachari]] \n*'''[[Garo languages]]''': [[Garo language|Garo]], [[Megam language|Megam]]\n*'''[[Koch languages]]''': [[Atong language (Sino-Tibetan)|Atong]], [[Koch language|Koch]], [[Ruga language|Ruga]], [[Rabha language|Rabha]]\n*[[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]], [[Moran language|Moran]]\n[[Hajong language|Old Hajong]] may have been a Bodo\u2013Garo language.\n\n[[Bodo language|Boro]] is an official language of the Indian state of [[Assam]] and [[India]]. [[Kokborok]] (Tripuri) is one of the official languages of the state of [[Tripura]]. [[Garo language|Garo]] is an associate official language of [[Meghalaya]]. [[Megam language|Megam]] has been strongly influenced by [[Khasic languages]], while [[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]] by the [[Idu Mishmi language]]\n\nLanguages of the family feature [[subject\u2013object\u2013verb|verb-final]] word order.  There is some flexibility in the order of the arguments, but a [[nominative\u2013accusative language|nominative\u2013accusative]] distinction is marked with post-nominal [[clitic]]s.  The languages also prefix [[classifier (linguistics)|classifier]]s to [[numeral (linguistics)|numeral]]s modifying nouns.  [[Grammatical tense|tense]], [[grammatical aspect|aspect]] and [[grammatical mood|mood]] are indicated using verbal [[suffix]]es.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=7}}\n\n==Origins==\nThe linkage of the Boro\u2013Garo languages with Konyak and Jingphaw languages suggest that proto-Boro-Garo entered Assam from somewhere to the northeast.<ref>{{harvcol|DeLancey|2012|p=13}}</ref> It has been proposed that the ''proto''-Boro-Garo language was a ''lingua franca'' of different linguistic communities, not all of who were native speakers,<ref>\"Briefly, I propose, following a suggestion by Burling (2007), that the Proto-Bodo-Garo first as a lingua franca used for communication across the various linguistic communicates of the region and its striking simplicity and transparency reflect a period when it was widely spoken by communities for whom it was not a native language.\" {{harvcol|DeLancey|2012|p=3}}</ref> and that it began as a [[Creole language|creolized]] lingua franca.<ref>{{harvcol|DeLancey|2012|p=5}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\n===Joseph & Burling (2006)===\nJoseph & Burling (2006:1-2) classify the Boro\u2013Garo languages into four major groups. Wood (2008:6) also follows this classification.\n*[[Bodo languages]]: [[Bodo language|Boro]], [[Tripuri language|Kokborok]], [[Tiwa language (India)|Tiwa]]\n*[[Garo language|Garo]]\n*[[Koch languages]]: [[Koch language|Koch]], [[Rabha language|Rabha]], Wanang, [[Atong language (Sino-Tibetan)|Atong]], and [[Ruga language|Ruga]]\n*[[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]]\n\n===Jacquesson (2017)===\nJacquesson (2017:112)<ref name=\"Jacquesson2017\">Jacquesson, Fran\u00e7ois and van Breugel, Seino (2017). \"The linguistic reconstruction of the past: The case of the Boro-Garo languages.\" In ''Linguistics of the Tibeto-Burman Area'', 40, 90-122.{{doi|10.1075/ltba.40.1.04van}} [Note: English translation of the French original: Jacquesson, Fran\u00e7ois (2006). \u2018La reconstruction linguistique du pass\u00e9: Le cas des language Boro-Garo\u2019. ''Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Linguistique de Paris'' 101(1): 273\u2013303.]</ref> classifies the Bodo-Garo languages as follows, and recognizes three major branches (Western, Central, and Eastern). The [[Koch languages]] and [[Garo language|Garo]] are grouped together as Western Bodo-Garo.\n*Western\n**[[Garo language|Garo]]\n**[[Rabha language|Rabha]], [[Koch language|Koch]]\n*[[Bodo languages|Central]]\n**[[Bodo language|Boro]], [[Bodo language|Mech]], Tiwa (Lalung)\n**Bru\n**[[Dimasa language|Dimasa]] \n**[[Tripuri language|Kokborok]]\n*Eastern\n**[[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]], [[Moran language|Moran]]\n\nJacquesson (2017)<ref name=\"Jacquesson2017\"/> believes that the Boro\u2013Garo languages had arrived in their present location from the southeast, and notes similarities shared with [[Zeme languages]] and [[Kuki-Chin languages]].\n\n==Reconstruction==\n[[Wiktionary:Appendix:List of Proto-Bodo-Garo reconstructions|Proto-Bodo\u2013Garo]] has been reconstructed by Joseph and Burling (2006) and by Wood (2008).\n\n==See also==\n*[[Wiktionary:Appendix:List of Proto-Bodo-Garo reconstructions|List of Proto-Bodo-Garo reconstructions]] (Wiktionary)\n*[[Reang]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=DeLancey |first1=Scott |editor3-first=Mark |editor3-last=w. Post |editor2-first=Stephen |editor2-last=Morey |editor1-first=Gwendolyn |editor1-last=Hyslop |year=2012 |title=On the Origin of Bodo-Garo |url= |journal=Northeast Indian Linguistics |volume=4 |issue= |pages=3\u201320 |doi=10.1017/UPO9789382264521.003 |access-date= |isbn=9789382264521 }}\n*Joseph, U.V., and Burling, Robbins. 2006. ''Comparative phonology of the Boro Garo languages''. Mysore: Central Institute of Indian Languages Publication.\n*Wood, Daniel Cody. 2008. [http://hdl.handle.net/1794/9485 ''An Initial Reconstruction of Proto-Boro-Garo'']. M.A. Thesis, University of Oregon.\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book\n  | chapter = The Tibeto-Burman languages of northeast India\n  | given = Robbins | surname = Burling\n  | pages = 169\u2013191\n  | title = The Sino-Tibetan languages\n  | editor-given1 = Graham | editor-surname1 = Thurgood\n  | editor-given2 = Randy J. | editor-surname2 = LaPolla\n  | location = London | publisher = Routledge | year = 2003\n  | isbn = 978-0-7007-1129-1\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = van Driem | first = George | authorlink = George van Driem\n  | title = Languages of the Himalayas: An Ethnolinguistic Handbook of the Greater Himalayan Region\n  | publisher = BRILL | year = 2001\n  | isbn = 978-90-04-12062-4\n  }}\n* {{cite thesis\n  | title = An Initial Reconstruction of Proto-Boro-Garo\n  | first = Daniel Cody | last = Wood\n  | publisher = University of Oregon | year = 2008 | degree = MA\n  | hdl = 1794/9485\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n\n{{Sal languages}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bodo-Garo languages}}\n[[Category:Sal languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language family\n|name=Boro\u2013Garo\n|altname=\n|region=[[Northeast India]], [[Bangladesh]]\n|familycolor=Sino-Tibetan\n|fam2=[[Sal languages|Sal]]<ref>Also known as Boro-Konyak-Jingpho or Brahmaputran.</ref>\n|child1=[[Bodo languages|Boro]]\n|child2=[[Garo languages|Garo]]\n|child3=[[Koch languages|Koch]]\n|child4=[[Deori language|Deori]]  |child5=[[Kokborok |kokborok]]\n|glotto=bodo1279\n|glottorefname=Bodo-Garo\n}} \n\nThe '''Boro\u2013Garo languages''' are a branch of [[Sino-Tibetan languages]],  spoken primarily in [[Northeast India]] and parts of [[Bangladesh]]. \n\nThe Boro-Garo languages form four groups: Boro, Garo, Koch and Deori.  Boro\u2013Garo languages were historically very widespread throughout the [[Brahmaputra Valley]] and in what are now the northern parts of [[Bangladesh]],<ref name=\"Jacquesson2017\"/> and it is speculated that the proto-Boro-Garo language was the lingua franca of the Brahmaputra valley before it was replaced by [[Assamese language]], to which it has made major contributions.\n\n==Branches==\nThe Boro\u2013Garo languages are:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name in LSI\n! Modern names\n|-\n| Bodo \n| [[Bodo language|Boro]]\n|-\n| Lalung \n| [[Tiwa language (India)|Tiwa]]\n|-\n| Dimasa \n| [[Dimasa language|Dimasa]]\n|-\n| Garo \n| [[Garo language|Garo]]\n|-\n| Rabha \n| [[Rabha language|Rabha]]\n|-\n| Tipura \n| [[Kokborok language|Kokborok]]\n|- \n| Chutiya \n| [[Deori language|Deori]]\n|- \n| Moran \n| [[Moran language|Moran]] (since disappeared)\n|}\n\n\n*'''[[Bodo languages]]''': [[Bodo language|Bodo]], [[Dimasa language|Dimasa]], [[Tiwa language (India)|Tiwa]], [[Kokborok]] (Tripuri), [[Kachari language|Kachari]] \n*'''[[Garo languages]]''': [[Garo language|Garo]], [[Megam language|Megam]]\n*'''[[Koch languages]]''': [[Atong language (Sino-Tibetan)|Atong]], [[Koch language|Koch]], [[Ruga language|Ruga]], [[Rabha language|Rabha]]\n*[[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]], [[Moran language|Moran]]\n[[Hajong language|Old Hajong]] may have been a Bodo\u2013Garo language.\n\n[[Bodo language|Boro]] is an official language of the Indian state of [[Assam]] and [[India]]. [[Kokborok]] (Tripuri) is one of the official languages of the state of [[Tripura]]. [[Garo language|Garo]] is an associate official language of [[Meghalaya]]. [[Megam language|Megam]] has been strongly influenced by [[Khasic languages]], while [[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]] by the [[Idu Mishmi language]]\n\nLanguages of the family feature [[subject\u2013object\u2013verb|verb-final]] word order.  There is some flexibility in the order of the arguments, but a [[nominative\u2013accusative language|nominative\u2013accusative]] distinction is marked with post-nominal [[clitic]]s.  The languages also prefix [[classifier (linguistics)|classifier]]s to [[numeral (linguistics)|numeral]]s modifying nouns.  [[Grammatical tense|tense]], [[grammatical aspect|aspect]] and [[grammatical mood|mood]] are indicated using verbal [[suffix]]es.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=7}}\n\n==Origins==\nThe linkage of the Boro-Garo languages with Konyak and Jingphaw languages suggest that proto-Boro-Garo entered Assam from somewhere to the northeast.<ref>{{harvcol|DeLancey|2012|p=13}}</ref> It has been proposed that the ''proto''-Boro-Garo language was a ''lingua franca'' of different linguistic communities, not all of who were native speakers,<ref>\"Briefly, I propose, following a suggestion by Burling (2007), that the Proto-Bodo-Garo first as a lingua franca used for communication across the various linguistic communicates of the region and its striking simplicity and transparency reflect a period when it was widely spoken by communities for whom it was not a native language.\" {{harvcol|DeLancey|2012|p=3}}</ref> and that it began as a [[Creole language|creolized]] lingua franca.<ref>{{harvcol|DeLancey|2012|p=5}}</ref>\n\n==Classification==\n===Joseph & Burling (2006)===\nJoseph & Burling (2006:1-2) classify the Boro-Garo languages into four major groups. Wood (2008:6) also follows this classification.\n*[[Bodo languages]]: [[Bodo language|Boro]], [[Tripuri language|Kokborok]], [[Tiwa language (India)|Tiwa]]\n*[[Garo language|Garo]]\n*[[Koch languages]]: [[Koch language|Koch]], [[Rabha language|Rabha]], Wanang, [[Atong language (Sino-Tibetan)|Atong]], and [[Ruga language|Ruga]]\n*[[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]]\n\n===Jacquesson (2017)===\nJacquesson (2017:112)<ref name=\"Jacquesson2017\">Jacquesson, Fran\u00e7ois and van Breugel, Seino (2017). \"The linguistic reconstruction of the past: The case of the Boro-Garo languages.\" In ''Linguistics of the Tibeto-Burman Area'', 40, 90-122.{{doi|10.1075/ltba.40.1.04van}} [Note: English translation of the French original: Jacquesson, Fran\u00e7ois (2006). \u2018La reconstruction linguistique du pass\u00e9: Le cas des language Boro-Garo\u2019. ''Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Linguistique de Paris'' 101(1): 273\u2013303.]</ref> classifies the Bodo-Garo languages as follows, and recognizes three major branches (Western, Central, and Eastern). The [[Koch languages]] and [[Garo language|Garo]] are grouped together as Western Bodo-Garo.\n*Western\n**[[Garo language|Garo]]\n**[[Rabha language|Rabha]], [[Koch language|Koch]]\n*[[Bodo languages|Central]]\n**[[Bodo language|Boro]], [[Bodo language|Mech]], Tiwa (Lalung)\n**Bru\n**[[Dimasa language|Dimasa]] \n**[[Tripuri language|Kokborok]]\n*Eastern\n**[[Deori language|Deori-Chutia]], [[Moran language|Moran]]\n\nJacquesson (2017)<ref name=\"Jacquesson2017\"/> believes that the Boro-Garo languages had arrived in their present location from the southeast, and notes similarities shared with [[Zeme languages]] and [[Kuki-Chin languages]].\n\n==Reconstruction==\n[[Wiktionary:Appendix:List of Proto-Bodo-Garo reconstructions|Proto-Bodo\u2013Garo]] has been reconstructed by Joseph and Burling (2006) and by Wood (2008).\n\n==See also==\n*[[Wiktionary:Appendix:List of Proto-Bodo-Garo reconstructions|List of Proto-Bodo-Garo reconstructions]] (Wiktionary)\n*[[Reang]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite 