{"title_page": "UNC Medical Center", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name = UNC Medical Center\n| emergency = [[Level 1 Trauma Center]]\n[[Trauma center|Level 1 Pediatric Trauma Center]]\n| beds = 905\n| image = North Carolina Memorial Hospital.jpg\n| caption = North Carolina Memorial Hospital (left) and North Carolina Children's Hospital (right), Chapel Hill, North Carolina\n| helipad = Yes\n| affiliation = [[UNC School of Medicine]]\n| founded = 1952\n| website = [https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/ UNCMC Website]\n| type = Teaching\n| address = 101 Manning Dr, Chapel Hill, NC\n| logo = UncmhMedical-center-logo.png\n| org/group = UNC Health Care\n| standards = \n}}'''UNC Medical Center''' ('''UNCMC''') is a 905-bed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ahd.com/free_profile/340061/UNC_Medical_Center/Chapel_Hill/North_Carolina/|title=American Hospital Directory - UNC Medical Center (340061) - Free Profile|website=www.ahd.com|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> [[non-profit]], public, research and [[Teaching hospital|academic medical center]] located in [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], [[North Carolina]], providing [[Tertiary care|tertiary]] care for the [[Research Triangle]], surrounding areas and North Carolina. The medical center is a part of the [[UNC Health Care]] Health System and is{{Coordinates|35.904744|-79.050458|region:US-NC_type:landmark|display=title}} made up of four hospitals that include the North Carolina Memorial Hospital, North Carolina Children's Hospital, North Carolina Neurosciences Hospital, North Carolina Women's Hospital, and the North Carolina Cancer Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fayobserver.com/news/20190319/live-wire-unc-health-system-includes-number-of-hospitals|title=Live Wire: UNC health system includes a number of hospitals|website=The Fayetteville Observer|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/hospitals-locations/profile/unc-hospitals/|title=UNC Hospitals|last=Hill|first=UNC Hospitals 101 Manning Drive Chapel|last2=Directions|first2=NC 27514 Get Driving|website=www.uncmedicalcenter.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> UNCMC is affiliated with the [[UNC School of Medicine|University of North Carolina School of Medicine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.med.unc.edu/patientcare/|title=Patient Care|website=UNC School of Medicine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> UNCMC features a [[American College of Surgeons|ACS]] designated adult and pediatric Level 1 Trauma Center<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facs.org/search/trauma-centers?state=NC|title=Trauma Centers|website=American College of Surgeons|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> and has a helipad to handle [[Medical evacuation|medevac]] patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/care-treatment/emergency-care/carolina-air-care/|title=Carolina Air Care {{!}} UNC Medical Center {{!}} Chapel Hill, NC|website=www.uncmedicalcenter.org|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytarheel.com/article/2020/01/unc-healthcare-helicopters-0122|title=The medics of the sky: how Carolina Air Care transports critical patients|website=The Daily Tar Heel|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nUNC Medical Center was first proposed in 1948 by [[R. Gregg Cherry|Governor Robert Gregg Cherry]] when picking a location for the UNC School of Medicine. A 400-bed hospital was proposed to be built next to the medical school, and ultimately completed in 1952.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncpedia.org/hospitals|title=Hospitals {{!}} NCpedia|website=www.ncpedia.org|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> The hospital only consisted of North Carolina Memorial Hospital until the new additions of the medical center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unchealthcare.org/about-us/|title=About Us {{!}} UNC Health Care System--North Carolina|website=www.unchealthcare.org|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\n== North Carolina Memorial Hospital ==\n[[File:UncmhMedical-center-at-night.jpg|thumb|UNC Medical Center at night]]\n[[File:UNC_Hospitals_Emergency_Room_Entry_20140831.jpg|thumb|UNC Memorial Hospital Emergency Department]]The first hospital in what later became known as UNC Hospitals and the UNC Health Care System was North Carolina Memorial Hospital, which opened on Sept. 2, 1952.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iei.ncsu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Silberman-History-of-Health.pdf|title=History of Health Care Policy Making in North Carolina|last=Silberman|first=Pam|date=|website=NC State University Institute for Emerging Issues|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> North Carolina Memorial Hospital is the largest hospital in the medical center featuring 803 beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/about/|title=About Us {{!}} UNC Medical Center|website=www.uncmedicalcenter.org|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> The hospital also includes an adult Level 1 Trauma Center, Burn Center, and Stroke Center that treat over 70,000 patients annually.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.med.unc.edu/emergmed/|title=Home|website=Emergency Medicine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was announced that a new 7 story, 335,000 ft<sup>2</sup> tower would be built on the UNC medical center campus at a cost of $257 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41536510/qc-commercial-llc-awarded-the-unc-surgical-tower-project|title=QC Commercial LLC Awarded the UNC Surgical Tower Project|website=www.wboc.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> The new addition is set to house 24 operating rooms and dedicates 2 floors to 56 new ICU beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/news/2018/07/11/unc-hospitals-ready-to-break-ground-on-new.html|title=UNC Hospitals ready to break ground on new surgical tower|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bizjournals.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> The addition will also include reception areas on each floor and offices for staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wunc.org/post/unc-set-break-ground-new-surgery-tower|title=UNC Set To Break Ground On New Surgery Tower|last=deBruyn|first=Jason|website=www.wunc.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.constructionglobal.com/major-projects/skanska-build-unc-hospitals-surgical-tower-north-carolina|title=Skanska to build UNC Hospitals Surgical Tower in North Carolina|website=www.constructionglobal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chapelboro.com/news/unc/unc-health-care-celebrates-construction-of-new-surgical-tower|title=Construction Beginning on UNC Health Care Surgical Tower|date=2019-05-22|website=Chapelboro.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\nThe [[Joint Commission]] has put UNC Medical Center's accreditation status on probation after finding several problems with the medical center. The Joint Commission has said that problems include insufficient suicide screening assessments and lack of suicide resistant furniture in psychiatric health areas. The hospital has responded by issuing a statement that there was \"no finding of any immediate threats to public health and safety.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article234315482.html|title=UNC Hospitals\u2019 accreditation is at risk after problems found at facilities|last=Murphy|first=Kate|date=|website=The News & Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/quality/unc-hospitals-placed-on-probation-by-joint-commission.html|title=UNC Hospitals placed on probation by Joint Commission|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carolinajournal.com/news-article/unc-hospitals-off-probation-though-accreditation-agency-cited-44-issues/|title=UNC Hospitals expects to regain accreditation even though agency cited 44 issues|website=Carolina Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Rankings ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+2020 US News & World Report NC Memorial Hospital<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|title=Best Hospitals|last=|first=|date=|website=US News & World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201235653/https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|archive-date=2020-02-01|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/north-carolina/charlotte/north-carolina-s-best-hospitals-latest-u-s-news-rankings|title=North Carolina's Best Hospitals: Latest U.S. News Rankings|date=2019-07-30|website=Charlotte, NC Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n!Specialty\n!Rank (In the U.S.)\n!Score (Out of 100)\n|-\n|Cancer\n|#27\n|60.8\n|-\n|Cardiology and Heart Surgery\n|N/A\n|42.6\n|-\n|Diabetes & Endocrinology\n|N/A\n|47.5\n|-\n|Ear Nose and Throat\n|#16\n|74.3\n|-\n|Gastroenterology & GI Surgery\n|#42\n|59.2\n|-\n|Geriatrics\n|N/A\n|60.1\n|-\n|Gynecology\n|#29\n|67.7\n|-\n|Nephrology\n|#29\n|59.2\n|-\n|Neurology & Neurosurgery\n|N/A\n|45.5\n|-\n|Orthopedics\n|N/A\n|37.8\n|-\n|Psychiatry\n|High Performing\n|3.2%\n|-\n|Pulmonology & Lung Surgery\n|High Performing\n|65.0\n|-\n|Rheumatology\n|High Performing\n|3.3%\n|-\n|Urology\n|N/A\n|80.1\n|}\n\n== North Carolina Children's Hospital==\n{{Infobox hospital\n| name = North Carolina Children's Hospital\n| type = Children's Hospital\n| emergency = [[Trauma center|Level 1 Pediatric Trauma Center]]\n| beds = 158\n| founded = 2001\n| affiliation = [[UNC School of Medicine]]\n| website = https://www.uncchildrens.org\n| logo = Childrens-logo-uncmcch.png\n| image = Northcarolinach.jpeg\n}}'''North Carolina Children's Hospital''' '''(NCCH)''' is a pediatric acute care hospital located within UNC Medical Center in Chapel Hill, North Carolina. The hospital has 150 beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncchildrens.org/uncmc/unc-childrens/patients-family/amenities/|title=Facilities & Amenities {{!}} UNC Children's {{!}} UNC Medical Center|website=www.uncchildrens.org|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> It is affiliated with The [[UNC School of Medicine|University of North Carolina School of Medicine]], and is a member of UNC Health. The hospital provides comprehensive pediatric specialties and subspecialties to infants, children, teens, and young adults aged 0-21<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncchildrens.org/uncmc/unc-childrens/locations/profile/unc-childrens-primary-care/|title=UNC Children's Primary Care Clinic|last=Hill|first=UNC Children's Primary Care Clinic 1512 E. Franklin St Suite 100 Chapel|last2=Directions|first2=NC 27514 Get Driving|website=www.uncchildrens.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> throughout [[North Carolina]]. North Carolina Children's Hospital features the only pediatric Level 1 Trauma Center in the region, and 1 of 3 in the state.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://healthtalk.unchealthcare.org/acs1/|title=N.C. Children's Hospital: Level I pediatric trauma center {{!}} UNC Health Talk|website=healthtalk.unchealthcare.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> \n\n=== Patient Care Units ===\n\n* '''64-bed inpatient unit''' - General Inpatient Care\n* '''8-bed Children's Intermediate Care Center''' - Severity Below ICU But Greater Than Inpatient Care\n* '''58-bed Newborn Critical Care Center''' - Intensive Care For Neonates\n* '''20-bed Pediatric Intensive Care Unit''' - Care For Critical Pediatric Patients\n* '''8-bed Children's Short Stay Unit''' - Care For Patients Requiring Less Than 24 Hours Of Care\n\n=== Controversy ===\n\nIn May 2019, it was revealed children with certain heart conditions had been dying at higher than expected rates after undergoing heart surgery at the hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/30/us/children-heart-surgery-cardiac.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/30/us/children-heart-surgery-cardiac.html|title=Doctors Were Alarmed: \u2018Would I Have My Children Have Surgery Here?\u2019|last=Gabler|first=Ellen|date=2019-05-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The concern was raised in 2017 by multiple cardiologists employed at the hospital. The cardiologists repeatedly raised concerns about the cardio surgery program and even began referring patients to other hospitals in the region. The cardiologists were concerned that the hospital was taking on cases that it could not handle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/quality/beyond-horrifying-cardiologists-warned-unc-children-s-of-heart-program-issues.html|title='Beyond horrifying': Cardiologists warned UNC Children's of heart program issues|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> When the hospital released their mortality rates, the results showed that the hospital had a higher cardio surgery death rate than nearly all of the other children's hospitals nationwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abclawcenters.com/blog/2019/07/25/medical-malpractice-news-scandal-rocks-unc-health-cares-pediatric-heart-surgery-program/|title=Scandal Rocks UNC Health Care's Pediatric Heart Surgery Program|last=rstokes|date=2019-07-25|website=Michigan Birth Injury & HIE Attorneys|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> In July, the North Carolina secretary of health called for the investigation into the allegations raised by the New York Times.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/31/us/unc-childrens-hospital-investigation.html|title=North Carolina to Investigate After Concerns Raised at Children\u2019s Hospital|last=Gabler|first=Ellen|date=2019-05-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2019/06/04/no-timeline-state-investigation-heart-program-unc/|title=No timeline for state investigation into NC Children\u2019s Hospital|last=Blythe|first=Anne|last2=June 4|first2=North Carolina Health News|date=2019-06-04|website=North Carolina Health News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02|last3=2019}}</ref> The hospital suspended its most complex heart surgeries to help restore confidence with the program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f9d0678a4d444b519ba93ac1b10158a0|title=Child death hike halts hospital's complex heart surgeries|date=2019-06-17|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc11.com/5350217/|title=UNC Children's Hospital pausing complex heart surgeries following critical report|date=2019-06-18|website=ABC11 Raleigh-Durham|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> The hospital made changes such as firing administrators and changing doctors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cardiovascularbusiness.com/topics/healthcare-economics/unc-pediatric-heart-surgery-program-under-fire|title=Trouble at UNC: State launches investigation into pediatric heart surgery program|website=Cardiovascular Business|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> State and federal inspectors have since confirmed that the hospital's cardio program is very different than years ago. The hospital has since cautiously resumed complex pediatric heart surgeries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/01/us/unc-childrens-hospital-heart-surgery.html|title=North Carolina Hospital Found Compliant but \u2018Significantly Different\u2019 After Complaints|last=Gabler|first=Ellen|date=2019-08-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2019/09/20/panel-clears-nc-childrens-hospital-for-complex-heart-surgeries/|title=NC Children\u2019s Hospital cleared for complex heart surgeries|last=Blythe|first=Anne|last2=September 20|first2=North Carolina Health News|date=2019-09-20|website=North Carolina Health News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02|last3=2019}}</ref>\n=== Rankings ===\nThe hospital is ranked nationally in 7 specialties and ranked #2 in North Carolina.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|title=University of North Carolina Hospitals in Chapel Hill, NC - Rankings, Ratings & Photos {{!}} US News Best Hospitals Rankings|date=2019-07-09|access-date=2020-02-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709021432/https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|archive-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+2020 U.S. News & World Report NC Children's Hospital<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chapelboro.com/town-square/unc-childrens-named-best-childrens-hospital-for-10th-straight-year|title=UNC Children's Named \"Best Children's Hospital\" For 10th Straight Year|date=2018-06-26|website=Chapelboro.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n!Specialty\n!Rank (In the U.S.)\n!Score (Out of 100)\n|-\n|Neonatology\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|Pediatric Cancer\n|#36\n|75.1\n|-\n|Pediatric Cardiology & Heart Surgery\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|Pediatric Diabetes & Endocrinology\n|#16\n|73.9\n|-\n|Pediatric Gastroenterology & GI Surgery\n|#36\n|68.7\n|-\n|Pediatric Nephrology\n|#30\n|75.7\n|-\n|Pediatric Neurology & Neurosurgery\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|Pediatric Orthopedics\n|#23\n|76.8\n|-\n|Pediatric Pulmonology & Lung Surgery\n|#16\n|74.9\n|-\n|Pediatric Urology\n|#37\n|67.8\n|}\n\n== North Carolina Cancer Hospital ==\n[[File:Nc-cancer-hospital-facade.jpg|thumb|The front of the N.C. Cancer Hospital at night.]]\nThe '''North Carolina Cancer Hospital''' is a public adult and pediatric cancer hospital. The hospital is the flagship site for UNC Cancer care and is the clinical home of the Lineberger Cancer Center. The 315,000 sq<sup>2</sup><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usa.skanska.com/what-we-deliver/projects/57165/North-Carolina-Cancer-Hospital--Physicians-Office-Building|title=North Carolina Cancer Hospital & Physician's Office Building|last=|first=|date=|website=Skanska USA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> is the state's only public cancer hospital. The new hospital opened in 2009 to replace the former 60-year-old building that used to be a tuberculosis sanatorium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytarheel.com/article/2009/09/n.c._cancer_hospital_opens_with_fanfare|title=N.C. Cancer Hospital opens with fanfare|website=The Daily Tar Heel|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> The center is one of 71 comprehensive cancer's nationwide and 1 of 3 in North Carolina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cancer.gov/research/nci-role/cancer-centers/find|title=Find an NCI-Designated Cancer Center|date=2012-08-13|website=National Cancer Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> The new hospital was created with $180 million in funds from the North Carolina State government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alumni.unc.edu/news/clinical-cancer-hospital-approved/|title=Clinical Cancer Hospital Approved - UNC General Alumni Association|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> The Cancer Hospital also includes a new Clinical Trials Unit allowing the hospital to access more than $147 million in grants from the National Institutes of Health that were previously unavailable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehealthcaremarketer.wordpress.com/2009/09/15/our-nations-newest-cancer-hospital/|title=Our Nation\u2019s Newest Cancer Hospital|last=Dandunlop|date=2009-09-16|website=The Healthcare Marketer|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> The hospital offers its pediatric services in conjunction with the adjacent N.C. Children's Hospital.\n\n=== Facilities ===\n\n* 101 examination, treatment, consultation, and procedure rooms<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mhaworks.com/projects/nc-cancer-center/|title=Durham Architects: MHAworks - Planning, Architecture and Interiors - Durham, North Carolina|website=MHAworks|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n* 65 inpatient beds for medical oncology and bone marrow transplant\n*70 chemotherapy infusion rooms<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wral.com/lifestyles/healthteam/story/6002443/|title=N.C. Cancer Hospital serves patients, doctors :|last=WRAL|date=2009-09-15|website=WRAL.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n* 1 CT Scanner and 2 General Radiology Rooms, 2 PET/CT Scanners\n* 21 new Emergency Department treatment spaces to supplement existing ED space in the N.C. Neurosciences Hospital\n*The facility features a telemedicine conference center\n\n=== Awards ===\nGrouped in with the UNC Medical Center, the hospital ranks #27 nationwide in cancer hospitals on the 2020 U.S. News & World Report hospital rankings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/rankings/cancer|title=Best Cancer Hospitals|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. News & World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 and 2017, Becker's Hospital Review ranked the hospital as one of the \"100 hospitals and health systems with great oncology programs.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/lists/100-hospitals-and-health-systems-with-great-oncology-programs-2014.html|title=100 hospitals and health systems with great oncology programs {{!}} 2014|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/lists/100-hospital-and-health-systems-with-great-oncology-programs-2017.html|title=100 Hospital and Health Systems With Great Oncology Programs 2017|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of North Carolina designated N.C. Cancer Hospital a Blue Distinction\u00ae Center+ in complex & rare cancers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.unchealthcare.org/news/2016/march/blue-distinction|title=UNC Hospitals\u2019 care earns Blue Distinction\u00ae Center+ Designation for Quality and Cost-Efficiency for Five Service Lines \u2014 News Room - UNC Health Care|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc\n*https://www.uncchildrens.org\n<!--- Categories --->{{North Carolina Trauma Centers}}\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name = UNC Medical Center\n| emergency = [[Level 1 Trauma Center]]\n[[Trauma center|Level 1 Pediatric Trauma Center]]\n| beds = 905\n| image = North Carolina Memorial Hospital.jpg\n| caption = North Carolina Memorial Hospital (left) and North Carolina Children's Hospital (right), Chapel Hill, North Carolina\n| helipad = Yes\n| affiliation = [[UNC School of Medicine]]\n| founded = 1952\n| website = [https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/ UNCMC Website]\n| type = Teaching\n| address = 101 Manning Dr, Chapel Hill, NC\n| logo = UncmhMedical-center-logo.png\n| org/group = UNC Health Care\n| standards = \n}}'''UNC Medical Center''' ('''UNCMC''') is a 905-bed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ahd.com/free_profile/340061/UNC_Medical_Center/Chapel_Hill/North_Carolina/|title=American Hospital Directory - UNC Medical Center (340061) - Free Profile|website=www.ahd.com|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> [[non-profit]], public, research and [[Teaching hospital|academic medical center]] located in [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], [[North Carolina]], providing [[Tertiary care|tertiary]] care for the [[Research Triangle]], surrounding areas and North Carolina. The medical center is a part of the [[UNC Health Care]] Health System and is{{Coordinates|35.904744|-79.050458|region:US-NC_type:landmark|display=title}} made up of four hospitals that include the North Carolina Memorial Hospital, North Carolina Children's Hospital, North Carolina Neurosciences Hospital, North Carolina Women's Hospital, and the North Carolina Cancer Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fayobserver.com/news/20190319/live-wire-unc-health-system-includes-number-of-hospitals|title=Live Wire: UNC health system includes a number of hospitals|website=The Fayetteville Observer|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/hospitals-locations/profile/unc-hospitals/|title=UNC Hospitals|last=Hill|first=UNC Hospitals 101 Manning Drive Chapel|last2=Directions|first2=NC 27514 Get Driving|website=www.uncmedicalcenter.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> UNCMC is affiliated with the [[UNC School of Medicine|University of North Carolina School of Medicine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.med.unc.edu/patientcare/|title=Patient Care|website=UNC School of Medicine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> UNCMC features a [[American College of Surgeons|ACS]] designated adult and pediatric Level 1 Trauma Center<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facs.org/search/trauma-centers?state=NC|title=Trauma Centers|website=American College of Surgeons|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> and has a helipad to handle [[Medical evacuation|medevac]] patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/care-treatment/emergency-care/carolina-air-care/|title=Carolina Air Care {{!}} UNC Medical Center {{!}} Chapel Hill, NC|website=www.uncmedicalcenter.org|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytarheel.com/article/2020/01/unc-healthcare-helicopters-0122|title=The medics of the sky: how Carolina Air Care transports critical patients|website=The Daily Tar Heel|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nUNC Medical Center was first proposed in 1948 by [[R. Gregg Cherry|Governor Robert Gregg Cherry]] when picking a location for the UNC School of Medicine. A 400-bed hospital was proposed to be built next to the medical school, and ultimately completed in 1952.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncpedia.org/hospitals|title=Hospitals {{!}} NCpedia|website=www.ncpedia.org|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> The hospital only consisted of North Carolina Memorial Hospital until the new additions of the medical center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unchealthcare.org/about-us/|title=About Us {{!}} UNC Health Care System--North Carolina|website=www.unchealthcare.org|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\n== North Carolina Memorial Hospital ==\n[[File:UncmhMedical-center-at-night.jpg|thumb|UNC Medical Center at night]]\n[[File:UNC_Hospitals_Emergency_Room_Entry_20140831.jpg|thumb|UNC Memorial Hospital Emergency Department]]The first hospital in what later became known as UNC Hospitals and the UNC Health Care System was North Carolina Memorial Hospital, which opened on Sept. 2, 1952.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iei.ncsu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Silberman-History-of-Health.pdf|title=History of Health Care Policy Making in North Carolina|last=Silberman|first=Pam|date=|website=NC State University Institute for Emerging Issues|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> North Carolina Memorial Hospital is the largest hospital in the medical center featuring 803 beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc/about/|title=About Us {{!}} UNC Medical Center|website=www.uncmedicalcenter.org|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref> The hospital also includes an adult Level 1 Trauma Center, Burn Center, and Stroke Center that treat over 70,000 patients annually.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.med.unc.edu/emergmed/|title=Home|website=Emergency Medicine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was announced that a new 7 story, 335,000 ft<sup>2</sup> tower would be built on the UNC medical center campus at a cost of $257 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41536510/qc-commercial-llc-awarded-the-unc-surgical-tower-project|title=QC Commercial LLC Awarded the UNC Surgical Tower Project|website=www.wboc.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> The new addition is set to house 24 operating rooms and dedicates 2 floors to 56 new ICU beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/news/2018/07/11/unc-hospitals-ready-to-break-ground-on-new.html|title=UNC Hospitals ready to break ground on new surgical tower|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bizjournals.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> The addition will also include reception areas on each floor and offices for staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wunc.org/post/unc-set-break-ground-new-surgery-tower|title=UNC Set To Break Ground On New Surgery Tower|last=deBruyn|first=Jason|website=www.wunc.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.constructionglobal.com/major-projects/skanska-build-unc-hospitals-surgical-tower-north-carolina|title=Skanska to build UNC Hospitals Surgical Tower in North Carolina|website=www.constructionglobal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chapelboro.com/news/unc/unc-health-care-celebrates-construction-of-new-surgical-tower|title=Construction Beginning on UNC Health Care Surgical Tower|date=2019-05-22|website=Chapelboro.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\nThe [[Joint Commission]] has put UNC Medical Center's accreditation status on probation after finding several problems with the medical center. The Joint Commission has said that problems include insufficient suicide screening assessments and lack of suicide resistant furniture in psychiatric health areas. The hospital has responded by issuing a statement that there was \"no finding of any immediate threats to public health and safety.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article234315482.html|title=UNC Hospitals\u2019 accreditation is at risk after problems found at facilities|last=Murphy|first=Kate|date=|website=The News & Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/quality/unc-hospitals-placed-on-probation-by-joint-commission.html|title=UNC Hospitals placed on probation by Joint Commission|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carolinajournal.com/news-article/unc-hospitals-off-probation-though-accreditation-agency-cited-44-issues/|title=UNC Hospitals expects to regain accreditation even though agency cited 44 issues|website=Carolina Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Rankings ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+2020 US News & World Report NC Memorial Hospital<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|title=Best Hospitals|last=|first=|date=|website=US News & World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201235653/https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|archive-date=2020-02-01|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/north-carolina/charlotte/north-carolina-s-best-hospitals-latest-u-s-news-rankings|title=North Carolina's Best Hospitals: Latest U.S. News Rankings|date=2019-07-30|website=Charlotte, NC Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n!Specialty\n!Rank (In the U.S.)\n!Score (Out of 100)\n|-\n|Cancer\n|#27\n|60.8\n|-\n|Cardiology and Heart Surgery\n|N/A\n|42.6\n|-\n|Diabetes & Endocrinology\n|N/A\n|47.5\n|-\n|Ear Nose and Throat\n|#16\n|74.3\n|-\n|Gastroenterology & GI Surgery\n|#42\n|59.2\n|-\n|Geriatrics\n|N/A\n|60.1\n|-\n|Gynecology\n|#29\n|67.7\n|-\n|Nephrology\n|#29\n|59.2\n|-\n|Neurology & Neurosurgery\n|N/A\n|45.5\n|-\n|Orthopedics\n|N/A\n|37.8\n|-\n|Psychiatry\n|High Preforming\n|3.2%\n|-\n|Pulmonology & Lung Surgery\n|High Preforming\n|65.0\n|-\n|Rheumatology\n|High Preforming\n|3.3%\n|-\n|Urology\n|N/A\n|80.1\n|}\n\n== North Carolina Children's Hospital==\n{{Infobox hospital\n| name = North Carolina Children's Hospital\n| type = Children's Hospital\n| emergency = [[Trauma center|Level 1 Pediatric Trauma Center]]\n| beds = 158\n| founded = 2001\n| affiliation = [[UNC School of Medicine]]\n| website = https://www.uncchildrens.org\n| logo = Childrens-logo-uncmcch.png\n| image = Northcarolinach.jpeg\n}}'''North Carolina Children's Hospital''' '''(NCCH)''' is a pediatric acute care hospital located within UNC Medical Center in Chapel Hill, North Carolina. The hospital has 150 beds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncchildrens.org/uncmc/unc-childrens/patients-family/amenities/|title=Facilities & Amenities {{!}} UNC Children's {{!}} UNC Medical Center|website=www.uncchildrens.org|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> It is affiliated with The [[UNC School of Medicine|University of North Carolina School of Medicine]], and is a member of UNC Health. The hospital provides comprehensive pediatric specialties and subspecialties to infants, children, teens, and young adults aged 0-21<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncchildrens.org/uncmc/unc-childrens/locations/profile/unc-childrens-primary-care/|title=UNC Children's Primary Care Clinic|last=Hill|first=UNC Children's Primary Care Clinic 1512 E. Franklin St Suite 100 Chapel|last2=Directions|first2=NC 27514 Get Driving|website=www.uncchildrens.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> throughout [[North Carolina]]. North Carolina Children's Hospital features the only pediatric Level 1 Trauma Center in the region, and 1 of 3 in the state.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://healthtalk.unchealthcare.org/acs1/|title=N.C. Children's Hospital: Level I pediatric trauma center {{!}} UNC Health Talk|website=healthtalk.unchealthcare.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> \n\n=== Patient Care Units ===\n\n* '''64-bed inpatient unit''' - General Inpatient Care\n* '''8-bed Children's Intermediate Care Center''' - Severity Below ICU But Greater Than Inpatient Care\n* '''58-bed Newborn Critical Care Center''' - Intensive Care For Neonates\n* '''20-bed Pediatric Intensive Care Unit''' - Care For Critical Pediatric Patients\n* '''8-bed Children's Short Stay Unit''' - Care For Patients Requiring Less Than 24 Hours Of Care\n\n=== Controversy ===\n\nIn May 2019, it was revealed children with certain heart conditions had been dying at higher than expected rates after undergoing heart surgery at the hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/30/us/children-heart-surgery-cardiac.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/30/us/children-heart-surgery-cardiac.html|title=Doctors Were Alarmed: \u2018Would I Have My Children Have Surgery Here?\u2019|last=Gabler|first=Ellen|date=2019-05-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The concern was raised in 2017 by multiple cardiologists employed at the hospital. The cardiologists repeatedly raised concerns about the cardio surgery program and even began referring patients to other hospitals in the region. The cardiologists were concerned that the hospital was taking on cases that it could not handle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/quality/beyond-horrifying-cardiologists-warned-unc-children-s-of-heart-program-issues.html|title='Beyond horrifying': Cardiologists warned UNC Children's of heart program issues|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> When the hospital released their mortality rates, the results showed that the hospital had a higher cardio surgery death rate than nearly all of the other children's hospitals nationwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abclawcenters.com/blog/2019/07/25/medical-malpractice-news-scandal-rocks-unc-health-cares-pediatric-heart-surgery-program/|title=Scandal Rocks UNC Health Care's Pediatric Heart Surgery Program|last=rstokes|date=2019-07-25|website=Michigan Birth Injury & HIE Attorneys|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> In July, the North Carolina secretary of health called for the investigation into the allegations raised by the New York Times.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/31/us/unc-childrens-hospital-investigation.html|title=North Carolina to Investigate After Concerns Raised at Children\u2019s Hospital|last=Gabler|first=Ellen|date=2019-05-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2019/06/04/no-timeline-state-investigation-heart-program-unc/|title=No timeline for state investigation into NC Children\u2019s Hospital|last=Blythe|first=Anne|last2=June 4|first2=North Carolina Health News|date=2019-06-04|website=North Carolina Health News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02|last3=2019}}</ref> The hospital suspended its most complex heart surgeries to help restore confidence with the program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/f9d0678a4d444b519ba93ac1b10158a0|title=Child death hike halts hospital's complex heart surgeries|date=2019-06-17|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc11.com/5350217/|title=UNC Children's Hospital pausing complex heart surgeries following critical report|date=2019-06-18|website=ABC11 Raleigh-Durham|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> The hospital made changes such as firing administrators and changing doctors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cardiovascularbusiness.com/topics/healthcare-economics/unc-pediatric-heart-surgery-program-under-fire|title=Trouble at UNC: State launches investigation into pediatric heart surgery program|website=Cardiovascular Business|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> State and federal inspectors have since confirmed that the hospital's cardio program is very different than years ago. The hospital has since cautiously resumed complex pediatric heart surgeries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/01/us/unc-childrens-hospital-heart-surgery.html|title=North Carolina Hospital Found Compliant but \u2018Significantly Different\u2019 After Complaints|last=Gabler|first=Ellen|date=2019-08-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northcarolinahealthnews.org/2019/09/20/panel-clears-nc-childrens-hospital-for-complex-heart-surgeries/|title=NC Children\u2019s Hospital cleared for complex heart surgeries|last=Blythe|first=Anne|last2=September 20|first2=North Carolina Health News|date=2019-09-20|website=North Carolina Health News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-02|last3=2019}}</ref>\n=== Rankings ===\nThe hospital is ranked nationally in 7 specialties and ranked #2 in North Carolina.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|title=University of North Carolina Hospitals in Chapel Hill, NC - Rankings, Ratings & Photos {{!}} US News Best Hospitals Rankings|date=2019-07-09|access-date=2020-02-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709021432/https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/nc/university-of-north-carolina-hospitals-6360260|archive-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+2020 U.S. News & World Report NC Children's Hospital<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chapelboro.com/town-square/unc-childrens-named-best-childrens-hospital-for-10th-straight-year|title=UNC Children's Named \"Best Children's Hospital\" For 10th Straight Year|date=2018-06-26|website=Chapelboro.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n!Specialty\n!Rank (In the U.S.)\n!Score (Out of 100)\n|-\n|Neonatology\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|Pediatric Cancer\n|#36\n|75.1\n|-\n|Pediatric Cardiology & Heart Surgery\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|Pediatric Diabetes & Endocrinology\n|#16\n|73.9\n|-\n|Pediatric Gastroenterology & GI Surgery\n|#36\n|68.7\n|-\n|Pediatric Nephrology\n|#30\n|75.7\n|-\n|Pediatric Neurology & Neurosurgery\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n|Pediatric Orthopedics\n|#23\n|76.8\n|-\n|Pediatric Pulmonology & Lung Surgery\n|#16\n|74.9\n|-\n|Pediatric Urology\n|#37\n|67.8\n|}\n\n== North Carolina Cancer Hospital ==\n[[File:Nc-cancer-hospital-facade.jpg|thumb|The front of the N.C. Cancer Hospital at night.]]\nThe '''North Carolina Cancer Hospital''' is a public adult and pediatric cancer hospital. The hospital is the flagship site for UNC Cancer care and is the clinical home of the Lineberger Cancer Center. The 315,000 sq<sup>2</sup><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usa.skanska.com/what-we-deliver/projects/57165/North-Carolina-Cancer-Hospital--Physicians-Office-Building|title=North Carolina Cancer Hospital & Physician's Office Building|last=|first=|date=|website=Skanska USA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> is the state's only public cancer hospital. The new hospital opened in 2009 to replace the former 60-year-old building that used to be a tuberculosis sanatorium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytarheel.com/article/2009/09/n.c._cancer_hospital_opens_with_fanfare|title=N.C. Cancer Hospital opens with fanfare|website=The Daily Tar Heel|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> The center is one of 71 comprehensive cancer's nationwide and 1 of 3 in North Carolina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cancer.gov/research/nci-role/cancer-centers/find|title=Find an NCI-Designated Cancer Center|date=2012-08-13|website=National Cancer Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> The new hospital was created with $180 million in funds from the North Carolina State government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alumni.unc.edu/news/clinical-cancer-hospital-approved/|title=Clinical Cancer Hospital Approved - UNC General Alumni Association|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> The Cancer Hospital also includes a new Clinical Trials Unit allowing the hospital to access more than $147 million in grants from the National Institutes of Health that were previously unavailable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehealthcaremarketer.wordpress.com/2009/09/15/our-nations-newest-cancer-hospital/|title=Our Nation\u2019s Newest Cancer Hospital|last=Dandunlop|date=2009-09-16|website=The Healthcare Marketer|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> The hospital offers its pediatric services in conjunction with the adjacent N.C. Children's Hospital.\n\n=== Facilities ===\n\n* 101 examination, treatment, consultation, and procedure rooms<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mhaworks.com/projects/nc-cancer-center/|title=Durham Architects: MHAworks - Planning, Architecture and Interiors - Durham, North Carolina|website=MHAworks|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n* 65 inpatient beds for medical oncology and bone marrow transplant\n*70 chemotherapy infusion rooms<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wral.com/lifestyles/healthteam/story/6002443/|title=N.C. Cancer Hospital serves patients, doctors :|last=WRAL|date=2009-09-15|website=WRAL.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n* 1 CT Scanner and 2 General Radiology Rooms, 2 PET/CT Scanners\n* 21 new Emergency Department treatment spaces to supplement existing ED space in the N.C. Neurosciences Hospital\n*The facility features a telemedicine conference center\n\n=== Awards ===\nGrouped in with the UNC Medical Center, the hospital ranks #27 nationwide in cancer hospitals on the 2020 U.S. News & World Report hospital rankings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/rankings/cancer|title=Best Cancer Hospitals|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. News & World Report|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 and 2017, Becker's Hospital Review ranked the hospital as one of the \"100 hospitals and health systems with great oncology programs.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/lists/100-hospitals-and-health-systems-with-great-oncology-programs-2014.html|title=100 hospitals and health systems with great oncology programs {{!}} 2014|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/lists/100-hospital-and-health-systems-with-great-oncology-programs-2017.html|title=100 Hospital and Health Systems With Great Oncology Programs 2017|website=www.beckershospitalreview.com|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of North Carolina designated N.C. Cancer Hospital a Blue Distinction\u00ae Center+ in complex & rare cancers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.unchealthcare.org/news/2016/march/blue-distinction|title=UNC Hospitals\u2019 care earns Blue Distinction\u00ae Center+ Designation for Quality and Cost-Efficiency for Five Service Lines \u2014 News Room - UNC Health Care|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*https://www.uncmedicalcenter.org/uncmc\n*https://www.uncchildrens.org\n<!--- Categories --->{{North Carolina Trauma Centers}}\n[[Category:Hospitals in North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRankings:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNC_Medical_Center"}
{"title_page": "Bororoan languages", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|language family indigenous to Brazil}}\n{{Infobox language family\n| name = Bor\u00f4roan\n| region = [[Brazil]]\n| familycolor = American\n| fam1 = [[Macro-G\u00ea languages|Macro-G\u00ea]]\n| glotto = boro1281\n| glottorefname = Bororoan\n| map = Bororoan languages.png\n| mapcaption = Geographical distribution of the Bor\u00f4roan languages\n| glottoname = \n| notes = \n| ancestor = \n}}\n\nThe '''Bor\u00f4roan languages''' of Brazil are [[Bororo language|Bor\u00f4ro]] and the extinct [[Umot\u00edna language|Umot\u00edna]] and [[Otuke language|Otuke]]. They form part of the proposed [[Macro-J\u00ea languages|Macro-J\u00ea language family]].\n\nThey are called the '''Borotuke languages''' by [[John Alden Mason|Mason]] (1950), a [[portmanteau]] of [[Bororo language|Bororo]] and [[Otuke language|Otuke]].<ref name=\"Mason-1950\">{{cite book |last=Mason |first=John Alden |authorlink=John Alden Mason |date=1950 |chapter=The languages of South America |editor-first1=Julian |editor-last1=Steward |title=Handbook of South American Indians |volume=6 |pages=157\u2013317 |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]], [[Bureau of American Ethnology]] Bulletin 143 |location=Washington, D.C., Government Printing Office}}</ref>\n\nKaufman (1994) suggests a relationship with the [[Chiquitano language]].<ref>Kaufman, Terrence. 1994. The native languages of South America. In: Christopher Moseley and R. E. Asher (eds.), ''Atlas of the World\u2019s Languages'', 59\u201393. London: Routledge.</ref>\n\n==Languages==\nThe relationship between the languages is,<ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15116/1/2013_LidianeSzerwinskCamargos.pdf]</ref>\n*[[Umotina language|Umotina]] ''(\u2020)''\n*Otuke\u2013Bororo\n**[[Bororo language|Bor\u00f4ro]]\n**[[Otuke language|Otuke]] ''(\u2020)''\n\nSee [[Otuke language|Otuke]] for various additional varieties of the Chiquito Plains in Bolivia which may have been dialects of it, such as Kovare and Kurumina.\n\nThere are other recorded groups that may have spoken languages or dialects closer to [[Bororo language|Bor\u00f4ro]], such as Aravir\u00e1, but nothing is directly known about these languages:<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref>\n*'''Aravir\u00e1''' - extinct language once spoken on the [[Caba\u00e7al River]] and [[Sepotuba River]] in Mato Grosso\n*'''Orari''' (Eastern Bor\u00f4ro, Orarimugodoge) - spoken on the [[Valhas River]], [[Gar\u00e7as River]], and [[Madeira River]] in Mato Grosso\n\n==Vocabulary==\n[[\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka|Loukotka]] (1968) lists the following basic vocabulary items.<ref name=\"Loukotka\"/>\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! gloss !! [[Bororo language|Bor\u00f3ro]] !! Orari !! [[Umotina language|Umutina]] !! [[Otuke language|Otuque]]\n|-\n! tongue\n| i-t\u00e1uro || i-kaura || azo\u02d0 || ki-taho\n|-\n! hand\n| i-k\u00e9ra || i-kera || azyida || seni\n|-\n! fire\n| y\u00f3ru || dzy\u00f3ru || zo\u02d0ru\u02d0 || reru\n|-\n! stone\n| tori || tori || tauri || tohori\n|-\n! sun\n| kueri || meri || baru || neri\n|-\n! moon\n| \u00e1ri || ari || a\u02d0li\u02d0 || ari\n|-\n! earth\n| r\u00f3to || mottu || moto || moktuhu\n|-\n! jaguar\n| ad\u00fago || adugo || azyukuet\u00e1 || anteko\n|-\n! fish\n| kare || karo || har\u00e9 || aharo\n|-\n! house\n| b\u00e1i || bai || isip\u00e1 || huala\n|-\n! bow\n| ba\u00edga || voiga || b\u00f3ika || vevika\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Macro-J\u00ea languages}}\n{{South American languages}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bororoan Languages}}\n[[Category:Bororoan languages]]\n[[Category:Macro-J\u00ea languages]]\n[[Category:Language families]]\n[[Category:Languages of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of South America (Central)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|language family indigenous to Brazil}}\n{{Infobox language family\n| name = Bor\u00f4roan\n| region = [[Brazil]]\n| familycolor = American\n| fam1 = [[Macro-G\u00ea languages|Macro-G\u00ea]]\n| glotto = boro1281\n| glottorefname = Bororoan\n| map = Bororoan languages.png\n| mapcaption = Geographical distribution of the Bor\u00f4roan languages\n| glottoname = \n| notes = \n| ancestor = \n}}\n\nThe '''Bor\u00f4roan languages''' of Brazil are [[Bororo language|Bor\u00f4ro]] and the extinct [[Umot\u00edna language|Umot\u00edna]] and [[Otuke language|Otuke]]. They form part of the proposed [[Macro-J\u00ea languages|Macro-J\u00ea language family]].\n\nThey are called the '''Borotuke languages''' by [[John Alden Mason|Mason]] (1950), a [[portmanteau]] of [[Bororo language|Bororo]] and [[Otuke language|Otuke]].<ref name=\"Mason-1950\">{{cite book |last=Mason |first=John Alden |authorlink=John Alden Mason |date=1950 |chapter=The languages of South America |editor-first1=Julian |editor-last1=Steward |title=Handbook of South American Indians |volume=6 |pages=157\u2013317 |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]], [[Bureau of American Ethnology]] Bulletin 143 |location=Washington, D.C., Government Printing Office}}</ref>\n\nKaufman (1994) suggests a relationship with the [[Chiquitano language]].<ref>Kaufman, Terrence. 1994. The native languages of South America. In: Christopher Moseley and R. E. Asher (eds.), ''Atlas of the World\u2019s Languages'', 59\u201393. London: Routledge.</ref>\n\n==Languages==\nThe relationship between the languages is,<ref>[http://repositorio.unb.br/bitstream/10482/15116/1/2013_LidianeSzerwinskCamargos.pdf]</ref>\n*[[Umotina language|Umotina]] ''(\u2020)''\n*Otuke\u2013Bororo\n**[[Bororo language|Bor\u00f4ro]]\n**[[Otuke language|Otuke]] ''(\u2020)''\n\nSee [[Otuke language|Otuke]] for various additional varieties of the Chiquito Plains in Bolivia which may have been dialects of it, such as Kovare and Kurumina.\n\nThere are other recorded groups that may have spoken languages or dialects closer to [[Bororo language|Bor\u00f4ro]], such as Aravir\u00e1, but nothing is directly known about these languages:<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref>\n*'''Aravir\u00e1''' - extinct language once spoken on the [[Caba\u00e7al River]] and [[Sepotuba River]] in Mato Grosso\n*'''Orari''' (Eastern Bor\u00f4ro, Orarimugodoge) - spoken on the [[Valhas River]], [[Gar\u00e7as River]], and [[Madeira River]] in Mato Grosso\n\n==Vocabulary==\n[[\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka|Loukotka]] (1968) lists the following basic vocabulary items.<ref name=\"Loukotka\">{{cite book |last=Loukotka |first=\u010cestm\u00edr |authorlink=\u010cestm\u00edr Loukotka |title=Classification of South American Indian languages |url=https://archive.org/details/classificationof0007louk |url-access=registration |publisher=UCLA Latin American Center |year=1968 |location=Los Angeles}}</ref>\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! gloss !! [[Bororo language|Bor\u00f3ro]] !! Orari !! [[Umotina language|Umutina]] !! [[Otuke language|Otuque]]\n|-\n! tongue\n| i-t\u00e1uro || i-kaura || azo\u02d0 || ki-taho\n|-\n! hand\n| i-k\u00e9ra || i-kera || azyida || seni\n|-\n! fire\n| y\u00f3ru || dzy\u00f3ru || zo\u02d0ru\u02d0 || reru\n|-\n! stone\n| tori || tori || tauri || tohori\n|-\n! sun\n| kueri || meri || baru || neri\n|-\n! moon\n| \u00e1ri || ari || a\u02d0li\u02d0 || ari\n|-\n! earth\n| r\u00f3to || mottu || moto || moktuhu\n|-\n! jaguar\n| ad\u00fago || adugo || azyukuet\u00e1 || anteko\n|-\n! fish\n| kare || karo || har\u00e9 || aharo\n|-\n! house\n| b\u00e1i || bai || isip\u00e1 || huala\n|-\n! bow\n| ba\u00edga || voiga || b\u00f3ika || vevika\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Macro-J\u00ea languages}}\n{{South American languages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bororoan Languages}}\n[[Category:Bororoan languages]]\n[[Category:Macro-J\u00ea languages]]\n[[Category:Language families]]\n[[Category:Languages of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of South America (Central)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bororoan_languages"}
{"title_page": "Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{Notability|Places|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER\n| image = LOTTE CASTLE.png\n| image_alt = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER symbol and logo\n| floor_count = F.35 - B.4\n| stop_date = 2012\n| architect = LOTTE Construction\n| address = St. Geumgok ([[Hwamyeong-dong]] 2324), [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], {{flag|South Korea}} [[South Korea]]\n}}\n\n'''Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER'''([[Korean language|Korean]]: \ud654\uba85\ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac\uce74\uc774\uc800) is a large apartment complex located in [[Hwamyeong-dong]], [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], [[South Korea]].\n\nBuilt in 2012, it is reconstructed from the Hwamyeong Jugong apartments. The complex comprises 48 buildings, and houses 5,239 apartments plus commercial facilities. It is the largest single apartment complex in Busan city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lottecastle.co.kr/apt/quickSearch/list.do#|title=Prestige of Life \ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac|website=www.lottecastle.co.kr|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIt has a swimming pool, fitness center, indoor golf course, and a private library. The [[Sujeong]] subway station is located just outside the main gate of the complex.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Residential buildings in South Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{Notability|Places|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER\n| image = LOTTE CASTLE.png\n| image_alt = LOTTE CASTLE KAISER symbol and logo\n| floor_count = F.35 - B.4\n| stop_date = 2012\n| architect = LOTTE Construction\n| address = St. Geumgok ([[Hwamyeong-dong]] 2324), [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], {{flag|South Korea}} [[South Korea]]\n}}\n\n'''Hwamyeong LOTTE CASTLE KAISER'''([[Korean language|Korean]]: \ud654\uba85\ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac\uce74\uc774\uc800) is a large apartment complex located in [[Hwamyeong-dong]], [[Buk-gu]], [[Busan]], [[South Korea]].\n\nIt is a reconstructed form of Hwamyeong Jugong apartment. It was built in 2012. The complex comprises 48 building, including 5,239 apartments plus commercial facilities. It is the largest single apartment complex in Busan city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lottecastle.co.kr/apt/quickSearch/list.do#|title=Prestige of Life \ub86f\ub370\uce90\uc2ac|website=www.lottecastle.co.kr|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIt has a swimming pool, fitness center, indoor golf course, and a private library. The [[Sujeong]] subway station is located just outside the main gate of the complex.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Residential buildings in South Korea]]\n", "name_user": "Barkhart", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hwamyeong_LOTTE_CASTLE_KAISER"}
{"title_page": "Vesyoly, Shovgenovsky District, Republic of Adygea", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Vesyoly\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0451\u043b\u044b\u0439 \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Khutor\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Adygea#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Adygea]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Shovgenovsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|03|N|40|03|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/adigeya/shovgenovskiy-rayon/veseliy-hutor/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0445\u0443\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u044b\u0439 \u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u0410\u0434\u044b\u0433\u0435\u044f]</ref>\n}}\n'''Vesyoly''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0435\u0441\u0451\u043b\u044b\u0439}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|khutor]]) in Zarevskoye Rural Settlement of [[Shovgenovsky District]], the [[Adygea|Republic of Adygea]], [[Russia]]. The population was 249 as of 2018.<ref name=\"krsdstat\">{{cite web|url=http://krsdstat.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/krsdstat/resources/3ca4e38044dfe71585cbafde4cdebdf4/%D0%A7%D0%B8%D1%81%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D1%8C+%D0%BF%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F+%D0%BF%D0%BE+%D0%9C%D0%9E+%D0%B8+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D1%8B%D0%BC+%D0%BF%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%BA%D1%82%D0%B0%D0%BC+%D0%A0%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BF%D1%83%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%B8+%D0%90%D0%B4%D1%8B%D0%B3%D0%B5%D1%8F+%D0%BF%D0%BE+%D1%81%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8E+%D0%BD%D0%B0+1+%D1%8F%D0%BD%D0%B2%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%8F+2018+%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%B0.doc|website=krsdstat.gks.ru|title=\u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043f\u043e \u041c\u041e \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0420\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0410\u0434\u044b\u0433\u0435\u044f \u043f\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0438\u044e \u043d\u0430 1 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> There are 3 streets.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Shovgenovsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Adygea]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Shovgenovsky District]]\n\n{{Adygea-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Vesyoly\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0451\u043b\u044b\u0439 \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Khutor\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Adygea#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Adygea]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Shovgenovsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|03|N|40|03|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/adigeya/shovgenovskiy-rayon/veseliy-hutor/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0445\u0443\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u044b\u0439 \u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u0410\u0434\u044b\u0433\u0435\u044f]</ref>\n}}\n'''Vesyoly''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0435\u0441\u0451\u043b\u044b\u0439}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|khutor]]) in Zarevskoye Rural Settlement of [[Shovgenovsky District]], the [[Adygea|Republic of Adygea]], [[Russia]]. The population was 249 as of 2018.<ref name=\"krsdstat\">{{cite web|url=http://krsdstat.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/krsdstat/resources/3ca4e38044dfe71585cbafde4cdebdf4/%D0%A7%D0%B8%D1%81%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D1%8C+%D0%BF%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8F+%D0%BF%D0%BE+%D0%9C%D0%9E+%D0%B8+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D1%8B%D0%BC+%D0%BF%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%BA%D1%82%D0%B0%D0%BC+%D0%A0%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BF%D1%83%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%B8+%D0%90%D0%B4%D1%8B%D0%B3%D0%B5%D1%8F+%D0%BF%D0%BE+%D1%81%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8E+%D0%BD%D0%B0+1+%D1%8F%D0%BD%D0%B2%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%8F+2018+%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%B0.doc|website=krsdstat.gks.ru|title=\u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043f\u043e \u041c\u041e \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0420\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0410\u0434\u044b\u0433\u0435\u044f \u043f\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0438\u044e \u043d\u0430 1 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> There are 3 streets.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Shovgenovsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Adygea]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Shovgenovsky District]]\n\n\n{{Adygea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vesyoly,_Shovgenovsky_District,_Republic_of_Adygea"}
{"title_page": "Bororo language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language \n  |name=Bor\u00f4ro\n  |nativename=Boe Wad\u00e1ru\n  |states=[[Brazil]]\n  |region=central [[Mato Grosso]]\n  |ethnicity=[[Bororo]]\n  |speakers={{sigfig|1390|2}}\n  |date=2007\n  |ref=e18\n  |familycolor=American\n  |fam1=[[Macro-G\u00ea languages|Macro-G\u00ea]]\n  |fam2=[[Bororoan languages|Bororoan]]\n  |dia1=Bor\u00f3ro (Biribocon\u00e9)\n  |dia2=Orari (Orarimugodoge, Eastern Bororo)\n  |iso3=bor\n|glotto=boro1282\n|glottorefname=Bororo\n}}\n\n'''Bororo''' (Bor\u00f4ro), also known as '''Boe''', is the sole surviving language of a small family believed to be part of the [[Macro-G\u00ea languages]].<ref name=indiancultures>{{cite web|url=http://indian-cultures.com/Cultures/bororo.html |title=Bororo Indians |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927005815/http://indian-cultures.com/Cultures/bororo.html |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref> It is spoken by the [[Bororo]], hunters and gatherers in the Central [[Mato Grosso]] region of [[Brazil]].\n\n== Phonology ==\nBororo has a mid-sized phonemic inventory of seven vowels and fifteen consonants.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Ainore Boe egore: um estudo descritivo da l\u00edngua bororo econseq\u00fc\u00eancias para a teoria de caso e concord\u00e2ncia.|last=Nonato|first=Rafael Bazerra|publisher=Instituto de Estudos de Linguagem|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=19\u201323}}</ref> Orthographic representations, when they differ from IPA, are shown in angle brackets (all from Nonato 2008, based on [[Americanist phonetic notation|Americanist transcription]]).\n\n=== Vowels ===\nThe vowel system of Bororo is somewhat cross-linguistically unusual in that it distinguishes [[roundedness]] only in its [[back vowel]]s (although Crowell (1979) analyzes these as underlyingly central<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Grammar of Bororo|last=Crowell|first=Thomas Harris|publisher=Cornell University|year=1979|isbn=|location=|pages=15}}</ref>).\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\" data-ve-attributes=\"{&quot;style&quot;:&quot;text-align: center;&quot;}\"\n<th rowspan=\"2\"></th><th rowspan=\"2\">[[Front vowel|Front]]</th><th colspan=\"2\">[[Back vowel|Back]]</th>\n|- <th>Unrounded</th><th>Rounded</th><tr><th>[[High vowel|High]]</th><td>i</td><td>\u026f <\u00fc></td><td aria-labelledby=\"23x15px&amp;#124;border_&amp;#124;alt=Brazil&amp;#124;link=Brazil_Languages_of_Brazil\">u</td></tr><tr><th href=\"Category:Bororo people\">[[Mid vowel|Mid]]</th><td href=\"Category:Languages of Brazil\">e</td><td href=\"Category:Indigenous languages of South America (Central)\">\u0264 <\u00f6></td><td>o</td></tr>\n|-Unrounded\n! href=\"Category:All stub articles\" |Unrounded\n!Rounded\n|- href=\"Low vowel\"\n![[High vowel|High]]\n| href=\"Tenseness\" |i\n| href=\"free variation\" |\u026f <\u00fc>\n|u\n|-\n![[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n|e\n|\u0264 <\u00f6>\n|o\n|-\n![[Low vowel|Low]]\n| colspan=\"3\" |a\n|}The mid vowels /e \u0264 o/ alternate with the open-mid (or \"[[Tenseness|lax]]\") vowels [\u025b \u028c \u0254] in apparent [[free variation]].\n\nThe unrounded back vowels /\u026f \u0264/ become central [\u0268 \u0258] word-finally. Furthermore, [\u0258] (i.e. word-final /\u0264/) is not distinguished from, and often surfaces as, front [\u025b]. As a result, /\u0264/ and /e/ are at least partially merged word-finally.\n\n==== Diphthongs and long vowels ====\nBororo has a rich inventory of twelve [[diphthong]]s:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!\n!'''-i'''\n!-e\n!-u\n!-o\n!-a\n|-\n|'''a-'''\n|ai\u032f\n|ae\u032f\n|au\u032f\n|ao\u032f\n|\n|-\n|'''e-'''\n|ei\u032f\n|\n|\n|eo\u032f\n|e\u032fa\n|-\n|'''o-'''\n|oi\u032f\n|oe\u032f\n|ou\u032f\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''\u0264-'''\n|\u0264i\u032f\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''\u026f-'''\n|\u026fi\u032f\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\nAll pure vowels can also occur long, i.e. as /i\u02d0 e\u02d0 \u026f\u02d0 \u0264\u02d0 u\u02d0 o\u02d0 a\u02d0/. In contrast to other languages with phonemic [[vowel length]], however, these are quite rare, and there seems to be no reason to distinguish long vowels from same-vowel sequences. This is evidenced by the mandatory lengthening of monosyllables, where the vowel of a monosyllable is repeated to form a long vowel: for example, /ba/ \"village\" becomes /baa\u032f/ [ba\u02d0].\n\n=== Consonants ===\nUnusually for a South American language, Bororo has no phonemic [[Fricative consonant|fricatives]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\" data-ve-attributes=\"{&quot;style&quot;:&quot;text-align: center;&quot;}\"\n!\n![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n![[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n![[Plosive]] or [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n|p {{IPA|b}}\n|t d\n|t\u0283 d\u0292 <c j>\n|{{IPA|k}} g k\u02b7 \u0261\u02b7 <kw gw>\n|-\n![[Nasal stop|Nasal]]\n|{{IPA|m}}\n|n\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Flap consonant|Flap]]\n|\n|\u027e <r>\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n|\n|\n|j <y>\n|w\n|}\nThe velar stop /k/ becomes [[Aspirated consonant|aspirated]] [k\u02b0] before nonback vowels /a e i/; the labiovelar approximant /w/ becomes labiodental [[Labiodental approximant|[\u028b]]] in the same environment. Plain and labialized velar stops /{{IPA|k}} g k\u02b7 \u0261\u02b7/ merge as labialized [k\u02b7 \u0261\u02b7] before rounded vowels /u o/. The voiced velar stop /g/ lenites to fricative [[Voiced velar fricative|[\u0263]]] between vowels.\n\n=== Syllable structure and stress ===\nThe canonical syllable structure in Bororo is (C)V: that is, a mandatory vowel nucleus (or diphthong), optionally preceded by a single onset consonant. Aside from unmodified loanwords from Portuguese (which are quite common, and becoming more so), Bororo syllables never have onset consonant clusters or codas.\n\nStress in Bororo occurs generally (again with the exception of unmodified Portuguese loanwords) on the penultimate [[Mora (linguistics)|mora]]. Since diphthongs contain two morae, this means that a diphthong in either penultimate or final position will generally be stressed: [\u02c8bai\u032f\u0261a] \"bow\", [ka\u02c8nao\u032f] \"pimple, scale\". Before compounding, however, diphthongs are reanalyzed as a monomoraic syllable, and stress is assigned again to the penultimate syllable of the whole compound: [ke\u02c8rakae\u032f] \"finger\", from /kera/ \"hand\" and /kae\u032f/ \"digit\".\n\n=== Morphophonology ===\nBororo has a process of stem-initial [[Consonant mutation|mutation]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The phonology of Bor\u00f3ro verb, postposition, and noun paradigms.|last=Crowell|first=Thomas Harris|publisher=Arquivos de Anatomia e Antropologia|year=1977|isbn=|location=Instituto de Antropologia Prof. Souza Marques, Rio de Janeiro|pages=162}}</ref> When a stem (whether a noun, verb, or preposition) beginning in a consonant takes on a prefix itself containing a consonant, the stem-initial consonant is voiced; for example, ''kodu'' \"to go\" becomes ''ikodu'' \"I go\" with the first person singular (prefix ''i-'') but ''pagodu'' \"we go\" in first person plural inclusive (prefix ''pa''-). In addition, /b/ becomes /w/ and /d\u0292/ becomes /j/ when following a prefix, regardless of whether the latter has a consonant or not: ''bogai'' \"for\" becomes ''iwogai'' \"for me\". Stems beginning with /d g m n r j w/ do not undergo any change. This process is part of a wider [[Consonant harmony|harmony]] restriction in Bororo, rare among the world's languages: no word (excluding clitics and compounds) may contain more than one voiceless obstruent.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Phonology Squib: Bororo stop voicing|last=Nonato|first=Rafael Bezerra|publisher=|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=1}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, a stem beginning in a vowel requires the insertion of a \"thematic\" consonant to attach a prefix. The consonant used varies both by the prefix and the stem-initial vowel: the first-person singular, first-person plural exclusive, and third-person plural prefixes insert the thematic consonant -''t-/-d''- before stems beginning in ''a-'' or ''o-'', while all other combinations (i.e. other personal prefixes or stem-initial ''i-''; no native stems begin in ''e-'' or ''u-'') insert ''-k-/-g-.'' For example, whereas ''ore'' \"children\" becomes ''i-t-ore'' \"my children\", ''iw\u00f6g\u00fc'' \"steal\" becomes ''i-k-iw\u00f6g\u00fc'' \"I steal\". A few irregular stems which would be expected to take ''-t-/-d-'' instead take ''-n-'': ''oika'' \"anxiety\" becomes ''inoika'' \"my anxiety\", rather than ''*itoiga'' or similar. Finally, since vowel-initial stems never take a third-person singular prefix, no thematic vowel is inserted. This process is summarized in the table below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Thematic consonants\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Prefix\n! colspan=\"3\" |Initial vowel\n|-\n!''i-''\n!''a-, o- (regular)''\n!''a-, o- (irregular)''\n|-\n|1sg ''i-''\n1pl.ex ''ce-''\n\n3pl ''e-''\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''ikiwogu'' \"I steal\"\n\n''cegiwogu'' \"we steal\"\n|'''''-t/d-'''''\n''itore'' \"my children\"\n\n''cedore'' \"our children\"\n|'''''-n-'''''\n''inoika'' \"my anxiety\"\n\n''cenoika'' \"our anxiety\"\n|-\n|3sg ''\u2205-''\n|'''''-\u2205-'''''\n\n''iwogu'' \"he steals\"\n|'''''-\u2205-'''''\n\n''ore'' \"his children\"\n|'''''-\u2205-'''''\n\n''oika'' \"his anxiety\"\n|-\n|All other prefixes\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''akiwogu'' \"you steal\"\n\n''tagiwogu'' \"you (pl.) steal\"\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''akore'' \"your children\"\n\n''tagore'' \"your (pl.) children)\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''akoiga'' \"your anxiety\"\n\n''tagoiga'' \"your (pl.) anxiety\"\n|}\n\n== Morphology ==\nBororo, like most languages of South America, is [[Synthetic language|synthetic]] and [[Agglutinative language|agglutinative]] (albeit with some degree of fusion). However, it cannot strictly be labelled \"[[Polysynthetic language|polysynthetic]]\"; it does not make use of [[Incorporation (linguistics)|incorporation]] or any other means of particularly extensive [[Morphological derivation|derivation]]. Nominal morphology is fairly simple - on a level comparable with modern [[Romance languages]] - and verbal morphology, while somewhat more complex, cannot exceed three or four affixes on any given verb, in sharp contrast to the better-known \"polysynthetic\" languages of the Americas such as [[Classical Nahuatl grammar|Nahuatl]] or [[Mohawk language|Mohawk]].\n\nSix basic word classes exist in Bororo: nouns and verbs (both open classes) and conjunctions, postpositions, adverbs, and pronouns (all closed).<ref>Nonato 2008, p. 34</ref> Note that there is no independent class of adjectives; the functions of adjectives in European languages are filled by verbs or nouns in Bororo. This section provides an overview of Bororo morphology as organized by these classes.\n\n=== Nouns ===\nThere is no category of obligatory nominal affixes in Bororo; a noun phrase may therefore be composed of a single unmarked root.\n\n==== Plurality ====\nMost nouns are pluralized by means of a plural suffix, whose most common allomorph is ''-doge'': ''arigao'' \"dog\" pluralizes to ''arigao-doge'' \"dogs\". The other allomorphs are ''-e'' (mainly following names of animals, e.g. ''juko-e'' \"monkeys\"), ''-mage'' (mainly following kinship terms, e.g. ''i-rago-mage'' \"my grandchildren\") and -''ge'' (mainly following pronouns, e.g. ''ema-ge'' \"they\"). In addition, there is a \"zero morpheme\" ''*bo-'' which can occur only with the plural suffix ''-e'', meaning \"things\" or \"people\", hence the Bororos' own term for themselves ''Boe.''\n\nSome nouns, however, are basically plural and require a [[Singulative number|marked singular]] suffix ''-d\u00fc.'' These generally refer to human beings; examples include ''barae'' \"white people\" (''baraed\u00fc'' \"a white person\") and ''ime'' \"men\" (''imed\u00fc'' \"a man\").\n\n==== Diminution and gender ====\n[[Diminutive|Diminution]] is a productive process in Bororo. The diminutive suffix is -''rogu''; ''awag\u00fc'' \"cobra\" therefore may become ''awag\u00fc-rogu'' \"little cobra\" (Portuguese ''cobrinha''). This has the allomorph ''-k\u00fcg\u00fcre'' when attached to a plural noun: ''awagoe'' \"cobras\" (an irregular plural) becomes ''awagoe-k\u00fcg\u00fcre'' \"little cobras\".\n\nBororo has no obligatory marking of [[grammatical gender]]. Many distinctions made by noun gender in Portuguese and other languages with the category are simply made by [[Suppletion|suppletive]] forms in Bororo, as in ''marido /'' ''ored\u00fcje'' \"husband / wife\" (Portuguese ''esposo / esposa''), or by compounding with the nouns ''imed\u00fc'' \"man\" and ''ared\u00fc'' \"woman\" - hence ''tapira imed\u00fc'' \"bull\" and ''tapira ared\u00fc'' \"cow\" from ''tapira'' \"cattle\". However, there is also a feminine derivative suffix ''-do'', which is used with personal names and demonstratives: ''aw\u00fc'' \"this\", ''aw\u00fc-do'' \"this (woman)\".\n\n==== Postpositions ====\nBororo uses postpositions rather than prepositions. Notably, these postpositions may be [[Inflected preposition|inflected]] with the same set of bound pronouns as verbs and inalienable possession; for example, ''ae'' \"to, toward\" can become ''et-ai'' \"to them\".\n\n===== Focus =====\nOne postposition, ''ji'', is used to establish the nominal focus of a sentence - what Crowell (1979) refers to as \"range or referent\".<ref>Crowell 1979, p. 29</ref> In some cases, this functions very similarly to focusing prepositions in English: ''e-mago-re tori '''ji''''', \"they talked '''about''' the mountains\". However, the range of [[ambitransitive verb]]s in Bororo is much narrower (if indeed ambitransitives exist at all) than in English, and so several verbs which are transitive in English require focusing with ''-ji'' in Bororo: ''imed\u00fc jor\u00fcd\u00fc-re karo '''ji''''' \"the men ate the fish\" (compare ''a-jor\u00fcd\u00fc-re'' \"you ate\"). These verbs - further examples of which are ''ra'' \"sing\", ''aid\u00fc'' \"want\", and ''r\u00f6'' \"do\" - function exactly as any other intransitive verb in Bororo.\n\n===== Demonstratives =====\nBororo has three degrees of [[Deixis|deictic distance]]: near (''a-''), medium (''no-''), and distant (''ce-''). To modify a noun, these must precede the relative marker ''-w\u00fc'': '''''a-w\u00fc''' imed\u00fc'' \"'''this''' man\", '''''ce'''-w\u00fc imed\u00fc'' \"'''that''' man (over there)\". Since Bororo lacks [[Article (grammar)|articles]], these occasionally take their place, but not nearly as frequently as true articles are used in English or Portuguese.\n\n==== Possession ====\nLike many indigenous languages of South America, Bororo distinguishes [[Clusivity|inclusive and exclusive first-person plurals]] as well as [[Inalienable possession|alienable and inalienable possession]]. Inalienable possession is the only nominal category marked by prefixes; since these are identical with the pronominal prefixes of verbs, they are listed in the section \"Pronouns\". The table below provides a list of alienable possessors with the example word ''tori'', \"stone\":\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Alienable possession\n!\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n!1\n|''ino tori'' \"my stone\"\n|''pago tori'' \"our stone\" (inclusive)\n''ceno tori'' \"our stone\" (exclusive)\n|-\n!2\n|''ako tori''\n|''tago tori''\n|-\n!3\n|''o tori''\n|''eno tori''\n|-\n!Coreferential\n| colspan=\"2\" |''to-dori'' \"(one's) own stone\"\n|-\n!Reciprocal\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pu-dori'' \"each other's stone\"\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\nBororo verbal morphology is basically divided along lines of [[Transitivity (grammar)|transitivity]]. Both transitive and intransitive verbs take the same set of bound pronouns to convey subjects and objects (e.g. '''''i'''-reru-re, '''a'''-reru-re'' \"I danced, you danced\" / '''''i'''-re '''a-'''reru-d\u00f6'' \"I make you dance\"), but each has an exclusive set of suffixes. \"Intransitive\" suffixes naturally apply to intransitive verbs, for which there is only one core argument - for example, the neutral aspect ''-re'' in ''i-reru-'''re''''' - but also to the [[Ergative case|agent of a transitive clause]], hence ''i-'''re''' a-reru-d\u00f6''; meanwhile, \"transitive\" suffixes can only be applied to the main verb of a transitive clause - e.g. the causative ''-d\u00f6'' in ''i-re a-reru-'''d\u00f6'''.'' For this reason, the suffixes listed in this section cannot properly be called \"verbal\" suffixes alone; they are grouped in this section merely for convenience.\n\n==== Intransitive and ergative ====\nAs mentioned above, these morphemes are suffixed either to the verb of an intransitive clause or to the agent of a transitive clause (A).\n\n===== Aspect =====\nBororo uses six suffixes, as well as a null suffix /-\u2205/, to convey [[grammatical aspect]]: three explicit grammatical aspects, divided into \"direct\" and \"[[Indirect speech|indirect]]\" marking. These are the only strictly mandatory affixes of any kind; they vary in frequency, but all are productive and fairly common. All of these seven options are mutually exclusive.\n\n====== Neutral ======\nThe most common suffix in Bororo by far is the declarative or \"neutral\" ''-re.'' This suffix conveys a basic and unmarked tense, aspect, and mood for a declarative or interrogative sentence: ''kowaru kuri-'''re''''' \"the horse is big\", ''kaiba kodu-'''re''''' \"where did he go?\" Since it does not convey any tense information, it can be translated as either present or past in English: ''kowaru kuri-re'', for example, could be interpreted either as \"the horse is big\" or \"the horse was big\".\n\n====== Stative ======\nThe stative suffix ''-n\u00fcre'' indicates that the action described by the verb is either ongoing or essential to the subject: ''et-ore e-ra-'''n\u00fcre''''' \"the children were singing\", ''imed\u00fc pega-'''n\u00fcre''''' \"the man is (essentially) bad\" (contrast with neutral ''imed\u00fc pega-'''re''''' \"the man is bad\").\n\n====== Purpose / Hortative ======\nThe \"purpose\" suffix -''w\u00f6'' indicates that the action in question is the desired result of another (itself usually marked with neutral aspect). This usage always requires a nominalizer ''d\u00fc-'' and the postposition ''-bogai,'' \"in order to\": ''i-tu-re a-nudu-'''w\u00f6''' d\u00fc-bogai'' \"I left so that you could sleep\" (or \"... in order for you to sleep\").\n\nThis suffix is also used to indicate a [[hortative]] mood: ''pa-goage-'''w\u00f6''' karo-ji'' \"let's eat the fish\". This usage does not require another clause or the ''d\u00fc-bogai'' construction.\n\n====== Recent ======\nRecent aspect is not conveyed with a suffix ''per se'' but rather the absence of a suffix; that is, a sentence without an aspect suffix is to be understood as occurring in the present or the recent past. Sentences using the other aspect markers may also be understood as present or recent, but only the absence of a suffix conveys this explicitly: ''imed\u00fc maru-\u2205'' \"the man is hunting\".\n\n====== Indirect ======\nAll three explicit aspect suffixes can also be rendered as indirect, meaning that the action they describe was itself described in speech or thought - corresponding broadly to the subjunctive in European languages. Verbs marked as indirect therefore always follow another verb (again usually in the neutral aspect): ''imed\u00fc ako-'''re''' awag\u00fc pega-'''ye''','' \"the man said that the cobra was bad / mean\". However, direct suffixes may also occur in this context; the indirect only adds an explicit layer of uncertainty or secondhand knowledge. For example, ''i-mear\u00fcdae-re a-m\u00fcg\u00fc-'''ye''''' means \"I thought you were there (but I didn't know)\", whereas ''i-mear\u00fcdae-re a-m\u00fcg\u00fc-'''re''''' would mean \"I thought you were there (and so you were)\".\n\nThere is no independent indirect affix. Instead, the three ordinary aspect suffixes change to apparently-related but historically obscure alternate forms when rendered as indirect. There is no indirect version of the recent aspect ''-\u2205''; its meaning appears to be covered by the neutral indirect ''-ye''. The direct and indirect aspectual suffixes are compared below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Aspectual suffixes\n!Aspect\n!Direct\n!Indirect\n|-\n!Neutral\n| -''re''\n| -''ye''\n|-\n!Stative\n|''-n\u00fcre''\n| -''y\u00fcre''\n|-\n!Purpose\n|''-w\u00f6''\n| -''w\u00f6e''\n|-\n!Recent\n|''-\u2205''\n|N/A (''-ye'')\n|}\n\n===== Negative =====\nThe negative suffix ''-ka- / -ga''- simply negates a verb as in English, and may be followed by any aspect marker: ''a-reru-re'' \"you danced\" becomes ''a-reru-'''ka'''-re'' \"you did not dance\". This likewise forms a negative imperative without any special marking or fusion: ''a-reru-ka-ba'' \"don't dance!\"\n\n===== Hypothetical =====\nThe hypothetical suffix ''-m\u00f6d\u00fc-'' indicates that the action is assumed (whether by the speaker or indirectly), but not definitely stated, to have taken place: ''u-tu-'''m\u00f6d\u00fc'''-ka-re'' \"he '''probably''' did not go\", ''u-tu-m\u00f6d\u00fc-ye'' \"(someone said that) he did not go\". This fuses with the neutral suffix ''-re'' to form ''-m\u00f6de'': ''u-tu-m\u00f6de'' \"he probably went\".\n\n===== Inchoative =====\nThe inchoative suffix ''-g\u00f6d\u00fc'' indicates that an action is beginning or has begun: ''meri rekod\u00fc-'''g\u00f6d\u00fc'''-re'' \"the sun '''is beginning''' to set\".\n\n==== Transitive ====\nThese three suffixes apply only to verbs which carries the patient or object of a transitive clause (O).\n\n===== Causative =====\nThe causative suffix ''-d\u00f6'' indicates that the subject of the verb causes the main object to perform an action, adding a level of [[Valency (linguistics)|valency]]: ''i-re a-tu-'''d\u00f6''''' \"I made you go\". Theoretically, this suffix could embed new verbs indefinitely: ''i-re a-d\u00f6 u-d\u00f6 e-tu-d\u00f6'' \"I made you make him make them go\", but as in English it is rare to use more than two degrees.\n\n===== Inceptive =====\nThe inceptive suffix ''-g\u00f6'' never occurs independently; it is the result of fusion with the causative. As a result, it has both a strictly [[Inchoative aspect|inceptive]] meaning and a causative one, and therefore similarly adds a degree of valency. Several verbs which could be translated with single morphologically simple words in English are formed using this suffix: examples include ''r\u00fcdiwa-'''g\u00f6''''' \"to teach\", literally \"to cause to begin to know\" and ''pemega-'''g\u00f6''''' \"to prepare\", literally \"to cause to begin to be ready / good\".\n\n===== Imminent =====\nThe imminent suffix ''-yagu'' indicates that an action is or was about to happen, or alternatively that it is only \"nearly\" accomplished: ''a-re a-tu-'''yagu''''' \"you were about to go\", ''e-re t\u00fc-'''yagu''' pu-reo-re'' \"they are almost alike\". This is technically a transitive sentence in Bororo, unlike in English; however, it is restricted entirely to coreferential arguments (i.e. the subject and object are identical).\n\n=== Pronouns ===\nPersonal pronouns are divided into free and bound forms. Free forms are used to strongly mark a topic (marked by the \"fronting\" suffix ''-re:'' homophonous with but not identical to the declarative ''re-''): '''''imi'''-re i-tu-re'' \"(as for me,) I'm going\". They are also used in \"verbless\" sentences (for which see below): '''''ema'''-re-o'' \"here it is / this is it\". Bound forms, meanwhile, are used to mark verb subjects and objects, inalienable possession, and postpositional inflection. The full list of free and bound forms (but not alienable possessors, for which see \"Possession\" above) is shown in the table below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Free\n! colspan=\"2\" |Bound\n|-\n!\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n!1\n|''imi''\n|''pagi'' (inclusive)\n''cegi'' (exclusive)\n|''i- (yo-)<sup>1</sup>''\n|''pa-''\n''ce-''\n|-\n!2\n|''aki''\n|''tagi''\n|''a''\n|''ta-''\n|-\n!3\n|''ema''\n|''ema-ge''\n|''u-, \u2205-<sup>2</sup>''\n|''e-''\n|-\n!Coreferential\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pudumi''\n| colspan=\"2\" |''t\u00fc ~ ci-''\n|-\n!Reciprocal\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pugi / pu''\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pu-''\n|}\n\n# Crowell (1979) references a first-person singular bound form ''yo-'' occasionally, but does not provide any description of this form or its use; it may be a typographic error. Nonato (2008) does not record it.\n# ''U-'' is used as the third-person bound pronoun as an agentive subject, as the subject of some irregular intransitive verbs (most commonly ''-tu-'' \"to go\") and as the inalienable possessor of some irregular nouns. Otherwise, third person singular is not marked.\n\n== Syntax ==\n\n=== Transitive and intransitive clauses ===\nAs seen above, a different set of suffixes applies to intransitive verbs and transitive subjects on the one hand, and verbs containing transitive objects on the other. It follows, therefore, that an intransitive clause must contain only a single verb of the former type (e.g. ''i-reru-re'' \"you dance\"), whereas a transitive clause must contain one of each. In the latter case, the \"subject\" word precedes the \"object-verb\": for example, '''''a<sub>1</sub>'''-re '''i<sub>2</sub>'''-wiye'' \"'''you<sub>1</sub>''' advised '''me<sub>2</sub>'''\". The use of bound pronouns is required even if the sentence contains a full noun in either subject or object position: ''ime '''e<sub>1</sub>'''-re areme '''e<sub>2</sub>'''-wiye'', word-for-word \"the men they<sub>1</sub>-did the women them<sub>2</sub> advise\" - \"the men advise the women\".<ref>Crowell 1979, p. 22</ref>\n\nSince ambitransitive verbs are at least exceedingly rare in Bororo, however, and intransitives with postpositional focus are very common, the frequency of strictly \"transitive\" constructions is far fewer than that of English or Portuguese.\n\n=== Yes-no questions ===\nYes-no questions (\"did/do...\" etc.) follow the same syntactical rules as declarative and imperative clauses in Bororo. Indeed, an interrogative clause may differ from a declarative one only by intonation: ''ature'' \"you went\", ''ature?'' \"did you go?\" However, a yes-no question may also be indicated explicitly by placing the clitic ''=na'' immediately after the questioned element: ''aturena?'' \"did you go?\" This clitic is mandatory after a question that contains only a single uninflected word, for example with pronouns: ''imina''? \"me?\"<ref>Crowell 1979, pp. 75-76</ref>\n\n=== Informational (\"wh-\") questions ===\nBororo has six question words, all ending in the interrogative morpheme ''-ba'': ''kabo-ba'' \"what\", ''yog\u00fcd\u00fc-ba'' \"who\", ''kakodiw\u00fc-ba'' \u2019which', ''ino-ba'' \u2019how', ''kai-ba'' \u2019where' and ''kodi-ba'' 'why'. If the question element is modified in some way (e.g. by a preposition), the following modifier must itself be marked with ''-ba'': '''''kabo<sub>1</sub>'''-ba '''tabo<sub>2</sub>'''-ba imed\u00fc maragod\u00fc-re'' \"'''what<sub>1</sub>''' did the man work '''with<sub>2</sub>'''?\"\n\nAs this example illustrates, Bororo makes use of [[wh-movement]]. An exception to this rule is ''pa'', an alternative form of ''kai-ba'' \"where\", which follows rather than precedes its subject: ''imed\u00fc pa?'' \"where is the man?\"\n\n=== Copular clauses ===\nUnlike in English, many well-formed Bororo clauses lack a verb entirely, in which case the first noun (the subject) takes the \"intransitive-ergative\" suffixes described above. These clauses usually correspond to those formed using the verb \"to be\" in English: '''''p\u00f6b\u00f6'''''-''re w\u00f6e'' \"there is '''water''' here\", '''''ema'''-re-o'' \"here '''it''' is\", etc. Crowell (1979) divides these clauses, which he calls \"copulative\", into \"existential\", \"equative\" and \"identificational\".<ref>Crowell 1979, p. 37</ref> Unlike clauses with verbs, these use free pronoun forms exclusively (with the exception of inalienable possession).\n\nExistential clauses denote the existence of their subject, optionally qualified by time and place. These are formed simply by applying the relevant inflection to the noun phrase: ''karo-re'' \"there are fish / fish exist\", ''karo-re p\u00f6b\u00f6'' ''tada'' \"there are fish in the water\", etc. If the subject of these clauses is modified by possession, this is taken as a full possessive statement: ''i-ke-re'', \"I have food\" (lit. \"my food is\").\n\nEquative clauses denote an identity between two noun phrases. These are formed by the juxtaposition of two noun phrases, only the first of which is inflected: ''imed\u00fc-re imi'', \"I am a man\". If these noun phrases are modified outside of inflection (e.g. are possessed by a full noun rather than a prefixed pronoun), they require the \"complex equative\" particle ''rema'' (singular) or ''remage'' (plural) to end the clause: ''Kadagare onareged\u00fc-re Creusa rema'' \"Creusa is Kadagare's child\".\n\nIdentificational clauses are used to present an object within a particular space. These are formed identically to existential clauses, followed by the addition of one of a set of suffixes ''-o, -no,'' and ''-ce,'' which correspond directly to the deictic prefixes ''a''-, ''no-'' and ''ce-'': ''karo-re-o'' \"here / this is a fish\".\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Maybury-Lewis, David, and Joan Bamberger. ''Dialectical Societies: The G\u00ea and Bororo of Central Brazil''. Harvard studies in cultural anthropology, 1. Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1979. {{ISBN|0-674-20285-6}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Languages of Brazil}}\n{{Macro-J\u00ea languages}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bororo people]]\n[[Category:Bororoan languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of South America (Central)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language \n  |name=Bor\u00f4ro\n  |nativename=Boe Wad\u00e1ru\n  |states=[[Brazil]]\n  |region=central [[Mato Grosso]]\n  |ethnicity=[[Bororo]]\n  |speakers={{sigfig|1390|2}}\n  |date=2007\n  |ref=e18\n  |familycolor=American\n  |fam1=[[Macro-G\u00ea languages|Macro-G\u00ea]]\n  |fam2=[[Bororoan languages|Bororoan]]\n  |dia1=Bor\u00f3ro (Biribocon\u00e9)\n  |dia2=Orari (Orarimugodoge, Eastern Bororo)\n  |iso3=bor\n|glotto=boro1282\n|glottorefname=Bororo\n}}\n\n'''Bororo''' (Bor\u00f4ro), also known as '''Boe''', is the sole surviving language of a small family believed to be part of the [[Macro-G\u00ea languages]].<ref name=indiancultures>{{cite web|url=http://indian-cultures.com/Cultures/bororo.html |title=Bororo Indians |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927005815/http://indian-cultures.com/Cultures/bororo.html |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref> It is spoken by the [[Bororo]], hunters and gatherers in the Central [[Mato Grosso]] region of [[Brazil]].\n\n== Phonology ==\nBororo has a mid-sized phonemic inventory of seven vowels and fifteen consonants.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Ainore Boe egore: um estudo descritivo da l\u00edngua bororo econseq\u00fc\u00eancias para a teoria de caso e concord\u00e2ncia.|last=Nonato|first=Rafael Bazerra|publisher=Instituto de Estudos de Linguagem|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=19-23}}</ref> Orthographic representations, when they differ from IPA, are shown in angle brackets (all from Nonato 2008, based on [[Americanist phonetic notation|Americanist transcription]]).\n\n=== Vowels ===\nThe vowel system of Bororo is somewhat cross-linguistically unusual in that it distinguishes [[roundedness]] only in its [[Back vowel|back vowels]] (although Crowell (1979) analyzes these as underlyingly central<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Grammar of Bororo|last=Crowell|first=Thomas Harris|publisher=Cornell University|year=1979|isbn=|location=|pages=15}}</ref>).\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\" data-ve-attributes=\"{&quot;style&quot;:&quot;text-align: center;&quot;}\"\n<th rowspan=\"2\"></th><th rowspan=\"2\">[[Front vowel|Front]]</th><th colspan=\"2\">[[Back vowel|Back]]</th>\n|- <th>Unrounded</th><th>Rounded</th><tr><th>[[High vowel|High]]</th><td>i</td><td>\u026f <\u00fc></td><td aria-labelledby=\"23x15px&amp;#124;border_&amp;#124;alt=Brazil&amp;#124;link=Brazil_Languages_of_Brazil\">u</td></tr><tr><th href=\"Category:Bororo people\">[[Mid vowel|Mid]]</th><td href=\"Category:Languages of Brazil\">e</td><td href=\"Category:Indigenous languages of South America (Central)\">\u0264 <\u00f6></td><td>o</td></tr>\n|-Unrounded\n! href=\"Category:All stub articles\" |Unrounded\n!Rounded\n|- href=\"Low vowel\"\n![[High vowel|High]]\n| href=\"Tenseness\" |i\n| href=\"free variation\" |\u026f <\u00fc>\n|u\n|-\n![[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n|e\n|\u0264 <\u00f6>\n|o\n|-\n![[Low vowel|Low]]\n| colspan=\"3\" |a\n|}The mid vowels /e \u0264 o/ alternate with the open-mid (or \"[[Tenseness|lax]]\") vowels [\u025b \u028c \u0254] in apparent [[free variation]].\n\nThe unrounded back vowels /\u026f \u0264/ become central [\u0268 \u0258] word-finally. Furthermore, [\u0258] (i.e. word-final /\u0264/) is not distinguished from, and often surfaces as, front [\u025b]. As a result, /\u0264/ and /e/ are at least partially merged word-finally.\n\n==== Diphthongs and long vowels ====\nBororo has a rich inventory of twelve [[Diphthong|diphthongs]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!\n!'''-i'''\n!-e\n!-u\n!-o\n!-a\n|-\n|'''a-'''\n|ai\u032f\n|ae\u032f\n|au\u032f\n|ao\u032f\n|\n|-\n|'''e-'''\n|ei\u032f\n|\n|\n|eo\u032f\n|e\u032fa\n|-\n|'''o-'''\n|oi\u032f\n|oe\u032f\n|ou\u032f\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''\u0264-'''\n|\u0264i\u032f\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''\u026f-'''\n|\u026fi\u032f\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\nAll pure vowels can also occur long, i.e. as /i\u02d0 e\u02d0 \u026f\u02d0 \u0264\u02d0 u\u02d0 o\u02d0 a\u02d0/. In contrast to other languages with phonemic [[vowel length]], however, these are quite rare, and there seems to be no reason to distinguish long vowels from same-vowel sequences. This is evidenced by the mandatory lengthening of monosyllables, where the vowel of a monosyllable is repeated to form a long vowel: for example, /ba/ \"village\" becomes /baa\u032f/ [ba\u02d0].\n\n=== Consonants ===\nUnusually for a South American language, Bororo has no phonemic [[Fricative consonant|fricatives]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\" data-ve-attributes=\"{&quot;style&quot;:&quot;text-align: center;&quot;}\"\n!\n![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n![[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n![[Plosive]] or [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n|p {{IPA|b}}\n|t d\n|t\u0283 d\u0292 <c j>\n|{{IPA|k}} g k\u02b7 \u0261\u02b7 <kw gw>\n|-\n![[Nasal stop|Nasal]]\n|{{IPA|m}}\n|n\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Flap consonant|Flap]]\n|\n|\u027e <r>\n|\n|\n|-\n![[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n|\n|\n|j <y>\n|w\n|}\nThe velar stop /k/ becomes [[Aspirated consonant|aspirated]] [k\u02b0] before nonback vowels /a e i/; the labiovelar approximant /w/ becomes labiodental [[Labiodental approximant|[\u028b]]] in the same environment. Plain and labialized velar stops /{{IPA|k}} g k\u02b7 \u0261\u02b7/ merge as labialized [k\u02b7 \u0261\u02b7] before rounded vowels /u o/. The voiced velar stop /g/ lenites to fricative [[Voiced velar fricative|[\u0263]]] between vowels.\n\n=== Syllable structure and stress ===\nThe canonical syllable structure in Bororo is (C)V: that is, a mandatory vowel nucleus (or diphthong), optionally preceded by a single onset consonant. Aside from unmodified loanwords from Portuguese (which are quite common, and becoming more so), Bororo syllables never have onset consonant clusters or codas.\n\nStress in Bororo occurs generally (again with the exception of unmodified Portuguese loanwords) on the penultimate [[Mora (linguistics)|mora]]. Since diphthongs contain two morae, this means that a diphthong in either penultimate or final position will generally be stressed: [\u02c8bai\u032f\u0261a] \"bow\", [ka\u02c8nao\u032f] \"pimple, scale\". Before compounding, however, diphthongs are reanalyzed as a monomoraic syllable, and stress is assigned again to the penultimate syllable of the whole compound: [ke\u02c8rakae\u032f] \"finger\", from /kera/ \"hand\" and /kae\u032f/ \"digit\".\n\n=== Morphophonology ===\nBororo has a process of stem-initial [[Consonant mutation|mutation]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The phonology of Bor\u00f3ro verb, postposition, and noun paradigms.|last=Crowell|first=Thomas Harris|publisher=Arquivos de Anatomia e Antropologia|year=1977|isbn=|location=Instituto de Antropologia Prof. Souza Marques, Rio de Janeiro|pages=162}}</ref> When a stem (whether a noun, verb, or preposition) beginning in a consonant takes on a prefix itself containing a consonant, the stem-initial consonant is voiced; for example, ''kodu'' \"to go\" becomes ''ikodu'' \"I go\" with the first person singular (prefix ''i-'') but ''pagodu'' \"we go\" in first person plural inclusive (prefix ''pa''-). In addition, /b/ becomes /w/ and /d\u0292/ becomes /j/ when following a prefix, regardless of whether the latter has a consonant or not: ''bogai'' \"for\" becomes ''iwogai'' \"for me\". Stems beginning with /d g m n r j w/ do not undergo any change. This process is part of a wider [[Consonant harmony|harmony]] restriction in Bororo, rare among the world's languages: no word (excluding clitics and compounds) may contain more than one voiceless obstruent.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Phonology Squib: Bororo stop voicing|last=Nonato|first=Rafael Bezerra|publisher=|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=1}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, a stem beginning in a vowel requires the insertion of a \"thematic\" consonant to attach a prefix. The consonant used varies both by the prefix and the stem-initial vowel: the first-person singular, first-person plural exclusive, and third-person plural prefixes insert the thematic consonant -''t-/-d''- before stems beginning in ''a-'' or ''o-'', while all other combinations (i.e. other personal prefixes or stem-initial ''i-''; no native stems begin in ''e-'' or ''u-'') insert ''-k-/-g-.'' For example, whereas ''ore'' \"children\" becomes ''i-t-ore'' \"my children\", ''iw\u00f6g\u00fc'' \"steal\" becomes ''i-k-iw\u00f6g\u00fc'' \"I steal\". A few irregular stems which would be expected to take ''-t-/-d-'' instead take ''-n-'': ''oika'' \"anxiety\" becomes ''inoika'' \"my anxiety\", rather than ''*itoiga'' or similar. Finally, since vowel-initial stems never take a third-person singular prefix, no thematic vowel is inserted. This process is summarized in the table below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Thematic consonants\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Prefix\n! colspan=\"3\" |Initial vowel\n|-\n!''i-''\n!''a-, o- (regular)''\n!''a-, o- (irregular)''\n|-\n|1sg ''i-''\n1pl.ex ''ce-''\n\n3pl ''e-''\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''ikiwogu'' \"I steal\"\n\n''cegiwogu'' \"we steal\"\n|'''''-t/d-'''''\n''itore'' \"my children\"\n\n''cedore'' \"our children\"\n|'''''-n-'''''\n''inoika'' \"my anxiety\"\n\n''cenoika'' \"our anxiety\"\n|-\n|3sg ''\u2205-''\n|'''''-\u2205-'''''\n\n''iwogu'' \"he steals\"\n|'''''-\u2205-'''''\n\n''ore'' \"his children\"\n|'''''-\u2205-'''''\n\n''oika'' \"his anxiety\"\n|-\n|All other prefixes\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''akiwogu'' \"you steal\"\n\n''tagiwogu'' \"you (pl.) steal\"\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''akore'' \"your children\"\n\n''tagore'' \"your (pl.) children)\n|'''''-k/g-'''''\n''akoiga'' \"your anxiety\"\n\n''tagoiga'' \"your (pl.) anxiety\"\n|}\n\n== Morphology ==\nBororo, like most languages of South America, is [[Synthetic language|synthetic]] and [[Agglutinative language|agglutinative]] (albeit with some degree of fusion). However, it cannot strictly be labelled \"[[Polysynthetic language|polysynthetic]]\"; it does not make use of [[Incorporation (linguistics)|incorporation]] or any other means of particularly extensive [[Morphological derivation|derivation]]. Nominal morphology is fairly simple - on a level comparable with modern [[Romance languages]] - and verbal morphology, while somewhat more complex, cannot exceed three or four affixes on any given verb, in sharp contrast to the better-known \"polysynthetic\" languages of the Americas such as [[Classical Nahuatl grammar|Nahuatl]] or [[Mohawk language|Mohawk]].\n\nSix basic word classes exist in Bororo: nouns and verbs (both open classes) and conjunctions, postpositions, adverbs, and pronouns (all closed).<ref>Nonato 2008, p. 34</ref> Note that there is no independent class of adjectives; the functions of adjectives in European languages are filled by verbs or nouns in Bororo. This section provides an overview of Bororo morphology as organized by these classes.\n\n=== Nouns ===\nThere is no category of obligatory nominal affixes in Bororo; a noun phrase may therefore be composed of a single unmarked root.\n\n==== Plurality ====\nMost nouns are pluralized by means of a plural suffix, whose most common allomorph is ''-doge'': ''arigao'' \"dog\" pluralizes to ''arigao-doge'' \"dogs\". The other allomorphs are ''-e'' (mainly following names of animals, e.g. ''juko-e'' \"monkeys\"), ''-mage'' (mainly following kinship terms, e.g. ''i-rago-mage'' \"my grandchildren\") and -''ge'' (mainly following pronouns, e.g. ''ema-ge'' \"they\"). In addition, there is a \"zero morpheme\" ''*bo-'' which can occur only with the plural suffix ''-e'', meaning \"things\" or \"people\", hence the Bororos' own term for themselves ''Boe.''\n\nSome nouns, however, are basically plural and require a [[Singulative number|marked singular]] suffix ''-d\u00fc.'' These generally refer to human beings; examples include ''barae'' \"white people\" (''baraed\u00fc'' \"a white person\") and ''ime'' \"men\" (''imed\u00fc'' \"a man\").\n\n==== Diminution and gender ====\n[[Diminutive|Diminution]] is a productive process in Bororo. The diminutive suffix is -''rogu''; ''awag\u00fc'' \"cobra\" therefore may become ''awag\u00fc-rogu'' \"little cobra\" (Portuguese ''cobrinha''). This has the allomorph ''-k\u00fcg\u00fcre'' when attached to a plural noun: ''awagoe'' \"cobras\" (an irregular plural) becomes ''awagoe-k\u00fcg\u00fcre'' \"little cobras\".\n\nBororo has no obligatory marking of [[grammatical gender]]. Many distinctions made by noun gender in Portuguese and other languages with the category are simply made by [[Suppletion|suppletive]] forms in Bororo, as in ''marido /'' ''ored\u00fcje'' \"husband / wife\" (Portuguese ''esposo / esposa''), or by compounding with the nouns ''imed\u00fc'' \"man\" and ''ared\u00fc'' \"woman\" - hence ''tapira imed\u00fc'' \"bull\" and ''tapira ared\u00fc'' \"cow\" from ''tapira'' \"cattle\". However, there is also a feminine derivative suffix ''-do'', which is used with personal names and demonstratives: ''aw\u00fc'' \"this\", ''aw\u00fc-do'' \"this (woman)\".\n\n==== Postpositions ====\nBororo uses postpositions rather than prepositions. Notably, these postpositions may be [[Inflected preposition|inflected]] with the same set of bound pronouns as verbs and inalienable possession; for example, ''ae'' \"to, toward\" can become ''et-ai'' \"to them\".\n\n===== Focus =====\nOne postposition, ''ji'', is used to establish the nominal focus of a sentence - what Crowell (1979) refers to as \"range or referent\".<ref>Crowell 1979, p. 29</ref> In some cases, this functions very similarly to focusing prepositions in English: ''e-mago-re tori '''ji''''', \"they talked '''about''' the mountains\". However, the range of [[Ambitransitive verb|ambitransitive verbs]] in Bororo is much narrower (if indeed ambitransitives exist at all) than in English, and so several verbs which are transitive in English require focusing with ''-ji'' in Bororo: ''imed\u00fc jor\u00fcd\u00fc-re karo '''ji''''' \"the men ate the fish\" (compare ''a-jor\u00fcd\u00fc-re'' \"you ate\"). These verbs - further examples of which are ''ra'' \"sing\", ''aid\u00fc'' \"want\", and ''r\u00f6'' \"do\" - function exactly as any other intransitive verb in Bororo.\n\n===== Demonstratives =====\nBororo has three degrees of [[Deixis|deictic distance]]: near (''a-''), medium (''no-''), and distant (''ce-''). To modify a noun, these must precede the relative marker ''-w\u00fc'': '''''a-w\u00fc''' imed\u00fc'' \"'''this''' man\", '''''ce'''-w\u00fc imed\u00fc'' \"'''that''' man (over there)\". Since Bororo lacks [[Article (grammar)|articles]], these occasionally take their place, but not nearly as frequently as true articles are used in English or Portuguese.\n\n==== Possession ====\nLike many indigenous languages of South America, Bororo distinguishes [[Clusivity|inclusive and exclusive first-person plurals]] as well as [[Inalienable possession|alienable and inalienable possession]]. Inalienable possession is the only nominal category marked by prefixes; since these are identical with the pronominal prefixes of verbs, they are listed in the section \"Pronouns\". The table below provides a list of alienable possessors with the example word ''tori'', \"stone\":\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Alienable possession\n!\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n!1\n|''ino tori'' \"my stone\"\n|''pago tori'' \"our stone\" (inclusive)\n''ceno tori'' \"our stone\" (exclusive)\n|-\n!2\n|''ako tori''\n|''tago tori''\n|-\n!3\n|''o tori''\n|''eno tori''\n|-\n!Coreferential\n| colspan=\"2\" |''to-dori'' \"(one's) own stone\"\n|-\n!Reciprocal\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pu-dori'' \"each other's stone\"\n|}\n\n=== Verbs ===\nBororo verbal morphology is basically divided along lines of [[Transitivity (grammar)|transitivity]]. Both transitive and intransitive verbs take the same set of bound pronouns to convey subjects and objects (e.g. '''''i'''-reru-re, '''a'''-reru-re'' \"I danced, you danced\" / '''''i'''-re '''a-'''reru-d\u00f6'' \"I make you dance\"), but each has an exclusive set of suffixes. \"Intransitive\" suffixes naturally apply to intransitive verbs, for which there is only one core argument - for example, the neutral aspect ''-re'' in ''i-reru-'''re''''' - but also to the [[Ergative case|agent of a transitive clause]], hence ''i-'''re''' a-reru-d\u00f6''; meanwhile, \"transitive\" suffixes can only be applied to the main verb of a transitive clause - e.g. the causative ''-d\u00f6'' in ''i-re a-reru-'''d\u00f6'''.'' For this reason, the suffixes listed in this section cannot properly be called \"verbal\" suffixes alone; they are grouped in this section merely for convenience.\n\n==== Intransitive and ergative ====\nAs mentioned above, these morphemes are suffixed either to the verb of an intransitive clause or to the agent of a transitive clause (A).\n\n===== Aspect =====\nBororo uses six suffixes, as well as a null suffix /-\u2205/, to convey [[grammatical aspect]]: three explicit grammatical aspects, divided into \"direct\" and \"[[Indirect speech|indirect]]\" marking. These are the only strictly mandatory affixes of any kind; they vary in frequency, but all are productive and fairly common. All of these seven options are mutually exclusive.\n\n====== Neutral ======\nThe most common suffix in Bororo by far is the declarative or \"neutral\" ''-re.'' This suffix conveys a basic and unmarked tense, aspect, and mood for a declarative or interrogative sentence: ''kowaru kuri-'''re''''' \"the horse is big\", ''kaiba kodu-'''re''''' \"where did he go?\" Since it does not convey any tense information, it can be translated as either present or past in English: ''kowaru kuri-re'', for example, could be interpreted either as \"the horse is big\" or \"the horse was big\".\n\n====== Stative ======\nThe stative suffix ''-n\u00fcre'' indicates that the action described by the verb is either ongoing or essential to the subject: ''et-ore e-ra-'''n\u00fcre''''' \"the children were singing\", ''imed\u00fc pega-'''n\u00fcre''''' \"the man is (essentially) bad\" (contrast with neutral ''imed\u00fc pega-'''re''''' \"the man is bad\").\n\n====== Purpose / Hortative ======\nThe \"purpose\" suffix -''w\u00f6'' indicates that the action in question is the desired result of another (itself usually marked with neutral aspect). This usage always requires a nominalizer ''d\u00fc-'' and the postposition ''-bogai,'' \"in order to\": ''i-tu-re a-nudu-'''w\u00f6''' d\u00fc-bogai'' \"I left so that you could sleep\" (or \"... in order for you to sleep\").\n\nThis suffix is also used to indicate a [[hortative]] mood: ''pa-goage-'''w\u00f6''' karo-ji'' \"let's eat the fish\". This usage does not require another clause or the ''d\u00fc-bogai'' construction.\n\n====== Recent ======\nRecent aspect is not conveyed with a suffix ''per se'' but rather the absence of a suffix; that is, a sentence without an aspect suffix is to be understood as occurring in the present or the recent past. Sentences using the other aspect markers may also be understood as present or recent, but only the absence of a suffix conveys this explicitly: ''imed\u00fc maru-\u2205'' \"the man is hunting\".\n\n====== Indirect ======\nAll three explicit aspect suffixes can also be rendered as indirect, meaning that the action they describe was itself described in speech or thought - corresponding broadly to the subjunctive in European languages. Verbs marked as indirect therefore always follow another verb (again usually in the neutral aspect): ''imed\u00fc ako-'''re''' awag\u00fc pega-'''ye''','' \"the man said that the cobra was bad / mean\". However, direct suffixes may also occur in this context; the indirect only adds an explicit layer of uncertainty or secondhand knowledge. For example, ''i-mear\u00fcdae-re a-m\u00fcg\u00fc-'''ye''''' means \"I thought you were there (but I didn't know)\", whereas ''i-mear\u00fcdae-re a-m\u00fcg\u00fc-'''re''''' would mean \"I thought you were there (and so you were)\".\n\nThere is no independent indirect affix. Instead, the three ordinary aspect suffixes change to apparently-related but historically obscure alternate forms when rendered as indirect. There is no indirect version of the recent aspect ''-\u2205''; its meaning appears to be covered by the neutral indirect ''-ye''. The direct and indirect aspectual suffixes are compared below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Aspectual suffixes\n!Aspect\n!Direct\n!Indirect\n|-\n!Neutral\n| -''re''\n| -''ye''\n|-\n!Stative\n|''-n\u00fcre''\n| -''y\u00fcre''\n|-\n!Purpose\n|''-w\u00f6''\n| -''w\u00f6e''\n|-\n!Recent\n|''-\u2205''\n|N/A (''-ye'')\n|}\n\n===== Negative =====\nThe negative suffix ''-ka- / -ga''- simply negates a verb as in English, and may be followed by any aspect marker: ''a-reru-re'' \"you danced\" becomes ''a-reru-'''ka'''-re'' \"you did not dance\". This likewise forms a negative imperative without any special marking or fusion: ''a-reru-ka-ba'' \"don't dance!\"\n\n===== Hypothetical =====\nThe hypothetical suffix ''-m\u00f6d\u00fc-'' indicates that the action is assumed (whether by the speaker or indirectly), but not definitely stated, to have taken place: ''u-tu-'''m\u00f6d\u00fc'''-ka-re'' \"he '''probably''' did not go\", ''u-tu-m\u00f6d\u00fc-ye'' \"(someone said that) he did not go\". This fuses with the neutral suffix ''-re'' to form ''-m\u00f6de'': ''u-tu-m\u00f6de'' \"he probably went\".\n\n===== Inchoative =====\nThe inchoative suffix ''-g\u00f6d\u00fc'' indicates that an action is beginning or has begun: ''meri rekod\u00fc-'''g\u00f6d\u00fc'''-re'' \"the sun '''is beginning''' to set\".\n\n==== Transitive ====\nThese three suffixes apply only to verbs which carries the patient or object of a transitive clause (O).\n\n===== Causative =====\nThe causative suffix ''-d\u00f6'' indicates that the subject of the verb causes the main object to perform an action, adding a level of [[Valency (linguistics)|valency]]: ''i-re a-tu-'''d\u00f6''''' \"I made you go\". Theoretically, this suffix could embed new verbs indefinitely: ''i-re a-d\u00f6 u-d\u00f6 e-tu-d\u00f6'' \"I made you make him make them go\", but as in English it is rare to use more than two degrees.\n\n===== Inceptive =====\nThe inceptive suffix ''-g\u00f6'' never occurs independently; it is the result of fusion with the causative. As a result, it has both a strictly [[Inchoative aspect|inceptive]] meaning and a causative one, and therefore similarly adds a degree of valency. Several verbs which could be translated with single morphologically simple words in English are formed using this suffix: examples include ''r\u00fcdiwa-'''g\u00f6''''' \"to teach\", literally \"to cause to begin to know\" and ''pemega-'''g\u00f6''''' \"to prepare\", literally \"to cause to begin to be ready / good\".\n\n===== Imminent =====\nThe imminent suffix ''-yagu'' indicates that an action is or was about to happen, or alternatively that it is only \"nearly\" accomplished: ''a-re a-tu-'''yagu''''' \"you were about to go\", ''e-re t\u00fc-'''yagu''' pu-reo-re'' \"they are almost alike\". This is technically a transitive sentence in Bororo, unlike in English; however, it is restricted entirely to coreferential arguments (i.e. the subject and object are identical).\n\n=== Pronouns ===\nPersonal pronouns are divided into free and bound forms. Free forms are used to strongly mark a topic (marked by the \"fronting\" suffix ''-re:'' homophonous with but not identical to the declarative ''re-''): '''''imi'''-re i-tu-re'' \"(as for me,) I'm going\". They are also used in \"verbless\" sentences (for which see below): '''''ema'''-re-o'' \"here it is / this is it\". Bound forms, meanwhile, are used to mark verb subjects and objects, inalienable possession, and postpositional inflection. The full list of free and bound forms (but not alienable possessors, for which see \"Possession\" above) is shown in the table below.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Free\n! colspan=\"2\" |Bound\n|-\n!\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n!1\n|''imi''\n|''pagi'' (inclusive)\n''cegi'' (exclusive)\n|''i- (yo-)<sup>1</sup>''\n|''pa-''\n''ce-''\n|-\n!2\n|''aki''\n|''tagi''\n|''a''\n|''ta-''\n|-\n!3\n|''ema''\n|''ema-ge''\n|''u-, \u2205-<sup>2</sup>''\n|''e-''\n|-\n!Coreferential\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pudumi''\n| colspan=\"2\" |''t\u00fc ~ ci-''\n|-\n!Reciprocal\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pugi / pu''\n| colspan=\"2\" |''pu-''\n|}\n\n# Crowell (1979) references a first-person singular bound form ''yo-'' occasionally, but does not provide any description of this form or its use; it may be a typographic error. Nonato (2008) does not record it.\n# ''U-'' is used as the third-person bound pronoun as an agentive subject, as the subject of some irregular intransitive verbs (most commonly ''-tu-'' \"to go\") and as the inalienable possessor of some irregular nouns. Otherwise, third person singular is not marked.\n\n== Syntax ==\n\n=== Transitive and intransitive clauses ===\nAs seen above, a different set of suffixes applies to intransitive verbs and transitive subjects on the one hand, and verbs containing transitive objects on the other. It follows, therefore, that an intransitive clause must contain only a single verb of the former type (e.g. ''i-reru-re'' \"you dance\"), whereas a transitive clause must contain one of each. In the latter case, the \"subject\" word precedes the \"object-verb\": for example, '''''a<sub>1</sub>'''-re '''i<sub>2</sub>'''-wiye'' \"'''you<sub>1</sub>''' advised '''me<sub>2</sub>'''\". The use of bound pronouns is required even if the sentence contains a full noun in either subject or object position: ''ime '''e<sub>1</sub>'''-re areme '''e<sub>2</sub>'''-wiye'', word-for-word \"the men they<sub>1</sub>-did the women them<sub>2</sub> advise\" - \"the men advise the women\".<ref>Crowell 1979, p. 22</ref>\n\nSince ambitransitive verbs are at least exceedingly rare in Bororo, however, and intransitives with postpositional focus are very common, the frequency of strictly \"transitive\" constructions is far fewer than that of English or Portuguese.\n\n=== Yes-no questions ===\nYes-no questions (\"did/do...\" etc.) follow the same syntactical rules as declarative and imperative clauses in Bororo. Indeed, an interrogative clause may differ from a declarative one only by intonation: ''ature'' \"you went\", ''ature?'' \"did you go?\" However, a yes-no question may also be indicated explicitly by placing the clitic ''=na'' immediately after the questioned element: ''aturena?'' \"did you go?\" This clitic is mandatory after a question that contains only a single uninflected word, for example with pronouns: ''imina''? \"me?\"<ref>Crowell 1979, pp. 75-76</ref>\n\n=== Informational (\"wh-\") questions ===\nBororo has six question words, all ending in the interrogative morpheme ''-ba'': ''kabo-ba'' \"what\", ''yog\u00fcd\u00fc-ba'' \"who\", ''kakodiw\u00fc-ba'' \u2019which', ''ino-ba'' \u2019how', ''kai-ba'' \u2019where' and ''kodi-ba'' 'why'. If the question element is modified in some way (e.g. by a preposition), the following modifier must itself be marked with ''-ba'': '''''kabo<sub>1</sub>'''-ba '''tabo<sub>2</sub>'''-ba imed\u00fc maragod\u00fc-re'' \"'''what<sub>1</sub>''' did the man work '''with<sub>2</sub>'''?\"\n\nAs this example illustrates, Bororo makes use of [[wh-movement]]. An exception to this rule is ''pa'', an alternative form of ''kai-ba'' \"where\", which follows rather than precedes its subject: ''imed\u00fc pa?'' \"where is the man?\"\n\n=== Copular clauses ===\nUnlike in English, many well-formed Bororo clauses lack a verb entirely, in which case the first noun (the subject) takes the \"intransitive-ergative\" suffixes described above. These clauses usually correspond to those formed using the verb \"to be\" in English: '''''p\u00f6b\u00f6'''''-''re w\u00f6e'' \"there is '''water''' here\", '''''ema'''-re-o'' \"here '''it''' is\", etc. Crowell (1979) divides these clauses, which he calls \"copulative\", into \"existential\", \"equative\" and \"identificational\".<ref>Crowell 1979, p. 37</ref> Unlike clauses with verbs, these use free pronoun forms exclusively (with the exception of inalienable possession).\n\nExistential clauses denote the existence of their subject, optionally qualified by time and place. These are formed simply by applying the relevant inflection to the noun phrase: ''karo-re'' \"there are fish / fish exist\", ''karo-re p\u00f6b\u00f6'' ''tada'' \"there are fish in the water\", etc. If the subject of these clauses is modified by possession, this is taken as a full possessive statement: ''i-ke-re'', \"I have food\" (lit. \"my food is\").\n\nEquative clauses denote an identity between two noun phrases. These are formed by the juxtaposition of two noun phrases, only the first of which is inflected: ''imed\u00fc-re imi'', \"I am a man\". If these noun phrases are modified outside of inflection (e.g. are possessed by a full noun rather than a prefixed pronoun), they require the \"complex equative\" particle ''rema'' (singular) or ''remage'' (plural) to end the clause: ''Kadagare onareged\u00fc-re Creusa rema'' \"Creusa is Kadagare's child\".\n\nIdentificational clauses are used to present an object within a particular space. These are formed identically to existential clauses, followed by the addition of one of a set of suffixes ''-o, -no,'' and ''-ce,'' which correspond directly to the deictic prefixes ''a''-, ''no-'' and ''ce-'': ''karo-re-o'' \"here / this is a fish\".\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Maybury-Lewis, David, and Joan Bamberger. ''Dialectical Societies: The G\u00ea and Bororo of Central Brazil''. Harvard studies in cultural anthropology, 1. Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1979. {{ISBN|0-674-20285-6}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Languages of Brazil}}\n{{Macro-J\u00ea languages}}\n\n[[Category:Bororo people]]\n[[Category:Bororoan languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of South America (Central)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bororo_language"}
{"title_page": "Ayub Bachchu", "text_new": "{{Short description|Bangladeshi singer, musician, guitarist and record producer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name             = Ayub Bachchu\n| image            = LRB Ayub Bachchu (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Bachchu performing live in the ''[[Emami]]'' Fair and Handsome Award in October 2014.\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = bn\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1962|08|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Patiya Upazila|Patiya]], [[Chittagong]], [[East Pakistan]] (Now in Chittagong, Bangladesh)\n| nationality      = [[Bangladeshi]]\n| education        = [[Govt. Muslim High School]], Chittagong \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2018|10|18|1962|08|16|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh\n| death_cause      = [[Cardiac failure]]\n| resting_place    = Buried in Chaitanya Goli, Chittagong, Bangladesh \n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|record producer|businessman}}\n| father           = Ishaque Chowdhury\n| mother           = Nurjahan Begum\n| spouse           = {{ubl|{{marriage|Ferdous Ayub Chandana|31 January 1991|18 October 2018|his death}}}}\n| children         = 2; including Fairuz and Ahnaf\n| website          = {{URL|ablrb.net}}\n| module = \n {{Infobox musical artist\n | embed = yes\n | background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n | origin           = Chittagong, Bangladesh \n | years_active     = 1977\u20132018\n | genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n | instrument       = {{hlist|[[Guitar]]|[[bass guitar|bass]]|[[vocals]]|[[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]}}\n | label            = {{hlist|CMV|AB Kitchen|Soundtek|Sargam|Sangeeta}}\n | associated_acts  = {{hlist | [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]] | [[Souls (band)|Souls]] | [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]] | [[James (musician)|James]] | [[Kumar Bishwajit]] | [[Asif Akbar]] | [[S.I. Tutul]] }}\n }} <!-- end of Infobox musical artist -->\n| signature        = Ayub Bachchu Robin signature.jpg\n}} <!-- end of Infobox person -->\n\n'''Ayub Bachchu''' ({{IPA-bn|ae\u032fub bat\u0283t\u0283u}}; 16 August 1962 &ndash; 18 October 2018) was a Bangladeshi [[rock music|rock]] guitarist, composer and singer-songwriter, who was the founder of the Bangladeshi rock band [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]]<ref>{{cite news |author=Saimum Saad |title=Ayub Bachchu sole owner of LRB, only heirs can run it: Copyright Office |url=https://bdnews24.com/entertainment/2019/04/16/ayub-bachchu-sole-owner-of-lrb-only-heirs-can-run-it-copyright-office |work=bdnews24.com |date=2019-04-16 |access-date=18 April 2019}}</ref> and earned success as the lead singer and the lead guitarist of the band.\n\nBorn in [[Patiya Upazila|Patiya]], Bachchu came to [[Chittagong]] with his family in the early 1970s. He formed his first band \"Ugly Boys\" in 1977, while studying in high school and joined in rock band Feelings (Now known as Nagar Baul) as the guitarist the same year. He played in the band from 1977 to 1980. In 1980, he joined [[Souls (band)|Souls]] where he played for ten years and appeared in four studio albums including ''Super Souls'' (1982), ''College Er Corridore'' (1985), ''Manush Matir Kachakachi'' (1987) and ''East and West'' (1988). In 1991, he left the band to form his own band LRB, where he was the vocalist and guitarist for 27 years, until his death in 2018. He released the first ever [[double album]]: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II'' in 1992, with the band. LRB's third studio album ''[[Shukh (album)|Shukh]]'', which featured \"[[Cholo Bodle Jai]]\", one of the greatest rock songs in Bangladesh. He also received well success as a solo artist. His first solo album ''[[Rokto Golap]]'' was released in September 1986. He got his breakthrough by releasing albums like ''[[Moyna (album)|Moyna]]'' (1988) and ''[[Koshto (album)|Koshto]]'' (1995) which received well success. He released only one [[instrumental rock]] album in his career: ''Sound of Silence'' (2007), which is the first ever instrumental album in Bangladesh.\n\nBachchu released several best selling-albums with LRB, and as a solo performer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu - New Music, Songs Playlist and Latest News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/591b4193-7876-4508-87f4-9ae67f4f3d46 |publisher=[[BBC Music]] |accessdate=2019-05-14 |first=\u0989\u0987\u09b2\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09ae |last=\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09cd\u09ab\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u0987}}</ref> Bachchu is widely regarded as the greatest and most influential guitarist of [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu: An inspiration for the young generation |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/185153/Rock-inspiration-for-the-young |publisher=[[Prothom Alo]] |date=19 October 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> He has won six [[Meril Prothom Alo Awards]], one [[Channel i Music Awards|Citycell-Channel I Music Award]] with LRB and won the [[Bachsas Awards]] in the Best Male Vocal category in 2004. In 2017, he won the [[Tele Cine Awards|Tele Cine]] Lifetime Achievement Award.\n\nBachchu married his girlfriend Ferdous Ayub Chandana on January 31, 1991, with whom he had a daughter, Fairuz Saffra Ayub and a son, Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub. In October 2018, Bachchu died of [[cardiac failure]] in his own residence in Dhaka, six years after he was suffering of lung ailment. He gave his last performance in [[Rangpur City]] two days before his death. He was buried in Chaitanya Goli in Chittagong, beside his mother's grave.<ref name=\":05\" />\n\n==Early life==\n\nBachchu was born in Chittagong in [[Patiya Upazila|Patiya]] at Khorna union on 16 August 1962 to Mohammad Ishaque Chowdhury (father) and Nurjahan Begum (mother).<ref name=\":09\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu - Celebrities of Bangladesh |url=https://www.mediabangladesh.net/bcard/ayub-bachchu/ |publisher=Media Bangladesh |accessdate=2019-05-19}}</ref> The family moved to the Chittagong city after the [[Liberation War of Bangladesh]]. They resided in Jubilee Road. He had a brother and a sister. He was the eldest among them. His nickname was Robin. He got his first acoustic guitar from his father as a gift 1973, when he was in class four. He learned to play guitar from Jacob Dayas a [[Myanmar|Burmese]] man, who used to live in Chittagong. He borrowed an electric guitar from his friend,[[Kumar Bishwajit]], which was a [[Teisco|Teisco Guitar]]. Bishwajit gave him the guitar after he [Bachchu] showed more interest towards it. He was very attracted to the guitar playing techniques of [[Jimi Hendrix]] and [[Joe Satriani]]. He was admitted to [[Government Muslim High School]] in 1975. In 1979, he graduated from Muslim High School.<ref name=\":06\">{{cite news |last=Ul Ibad |first=Mahid |title=I always had one goal, and that was to become a musician, I had no other option |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/10/18/i-always-had-one-goal-and-that-was-to-become-a-musician-i-had-no-other-option-2 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=9 August 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> His parents did not support him on becoming a musician. But, after his family saw his passion for rock music, they agreed on letting him become a musician. While studying in high school, Bachchu formed a band named \"Golden Boys\", which was later renamed as \"Ugly Boys\". Kumar Bishwajit was the lead singer of the band and Bachchu was the guitarist. They used to do club shows and shows in weddings (Mostly in the Patiya Upazilla). The group disbanded after Bachchu joined [[Souls (band)|Souls]] in 1980.<ref name=\"Ayub Bachchu at a glance\">{{cite news |author=Mahid Ul Ibad |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/185118/Ayub-Bachchu-at-a-glance|title=Ayub Bachchu at a glance |publisher=[[Prothom Alo]] |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== 1977&ndash;1990: Feelings and Souls ===\n{{Further|James (musician)|Souls (band)}}\nWhile working with his own band Ugly Boys, Bachchu joined the [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Nagar Baul|Feelings]] (now known as Nagar Baul) in 1977. Feelings' frontman [[James (musician)|James]] stated that he saw Bachchu playing guitar at a tea stall. He was amazed by the playing style of Bachchu and he asked him to join the band. In the mid-1977, he joined the band as the lead guitarist and only stayed with the band for next two years until in 1980, he got a contract from Souls, as their lead guitarist Sajed ul Alam had left the band for the [[United States]]. Bachchu was playing with Feelings in a club in Chittagong, where Souls' keyboards player Naqib Khan was present. He was amazed by the playing of Bachchu and he talked to lead singer [[Tapan Chowdhury (singer)|Tapan Chowdhury]] about it. Both of them saw Bachchu playing in the club next day and they asked him to join Souls. He joined Souls in early-1980 and played with the band for next 10 years as the lead guitarist, songwriter and occasional singer. He had appeared on four studio albums of the band, including ''Super Souls'' (1982), ''College Er Corridore'' (1985) and ''Manush Matir Kachakachi'' (1987), which features the first song sung by him, \"Harano Bikeler Golpo\". His last album with Souls was ''East and West'' (1988). In the late-1990, Bachchu left Souls and went on to form his own band [[Love Runs Blind|Little River Band]], which later became famous as Love Runs Blind. He reunited with Souls in several reunion shows and has performed with members of the band like [[Tapan Chowdhury]], [[Kumar Bishwajit]] and Naqib Khan in several shows.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.dw.com/bn/\u09ad\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0-\u0995\u09be\u0981\u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7-\u098f\u09ac\u09bf-\u0989\u09a1\u09bc\u09be\u09b2-\u09a6\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8-\u0986\u0995\u09be\u09b6\u09c7/g-45939606| title=\u09ad\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09be\u0981\u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u2018\u098f\u09ac\u09bf\u2019 \u0989\u09a1\u09bc\u09be\u09b2 \u09a6\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u0986\u0995\u09be\u09b6\u09c7| publisher=Deutsche Welle| date=2018-10-18| accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu: Life of a Maestro |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/feature/people-feature/2018/10/18/ayub-bachchu-life-of-a-maestro |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=18 October 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Bachchu told ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'' that:\n\n{{quote|I left Souls because of two different tastes in sounds. They liked one kind of music, I liked another. I was into loud, rocking, powerful sounds, and the rest of the members wanted quiet, melodious sounds. You cannot just compromise day after day. We never really had any big arguments, but it occurred to me that it would be better if I just quit and do something different.<ref name=\"What Rocks AB's World?\">{{cite news |author=Sushmita S. Preetha |title=What Rocks AB's World? |url=https://archive.thedailystar.net/magazine/2012/11/02/cover.htm |work=Star Weeknd |publisher=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=2012-11-09 |access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref>}}\n\n=== 1991-2018: LRB ===\n{{Main|Love Runs Blind}}\n[[File:Ayub Bachchu.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Bachchu performing at the City of Winter Garden in 2008]]\n\nAfter Bachchu got out of [[Souls (band)|Souls]] in the late-1990, he came to Dhaka in 1991 and in January he married Ferdous Chandana, with whom he had a relationship since 1986. He formed a band named '''Yellow River Band''' in April 5, 1991 with [[S.I. Tutul]] on keyboards, Saidul Hasan Swapan on bass guitars and Habib Anwar Joy on drums.{{efn|Many have stated that Bachchu named his band Little Robin's Band (as his nickname was Robin) when forming in 1991 and changed the name in 1997 when Bachchu found out he was not little anymore. But, it is considered to be a rumor as Bachchu was already 29 years old when he was forming the band. Bachchu has stated that Yellow River Band was the band's first name and they were mistakenly called Little River Band in a club show in Dhaka. As Bachchu liked the name he kept the name for the band. But, they had to change it again in 1997 after finding out about the australian rock band with the same name.}} When they were performing in a club in the mid-1991, they were mistakenly called the '''Little River Band''', which Bachchu liked and officially named his band. But, after they heard about the [[Little River Band|Australian rock band of the same name]] they changed their name to '''Love Runs Blind''' in 1997. In April 1991, LRB did their first ever concert in the [[University of Dhaka]], a concert that was arranged by BAMBA, celebrating the downfall of autocratic leader [[Hussein Muhammad Ershad]]. In January 1992, they released the first ever [[double album]]: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II''. The band's third studio album ''[[Shukh (album)|Shukh]]'', was released in June 1993 and is considered one of the greatest rock albums of Bangladesh. It included \"[[Cholo Bodle Jai]]\", which regarded by some as Bachchu's greatest work. They released several albums in the 1990s and soon became one of the most popular rock acts of Bangladesh. In 1996, they performed in [[Bengaluru]], which was their first concert outside Bangladesh. LRB is the only Bangladeshi artist to perform in the [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/ayub-bachchu-passes-away-1648585| title=Rock legend Ayub Bachchu passes away| date=2018-10-18| work=The Daily Star| accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref>\n\nAfter Bachchu's death, the other members of LRB announced [[Balam (singer)|Balam Jahangir]] as their new lead singer. Bachchu's wife and daughter was not satisfied with the members of the band performing with a new singer under the name LRB. They asked the members to change the name. The band was disbanded for few days and the other members of the band along with Balam formed a new band named, \"Balam and the Legacy\".<ref name=\"Balam and the Legacy\">{{cite news |title=Love Runs Blind changes name to Balam and the Legacy |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/04/15/lrb-changes-name-to-balam-the-legacy |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=2019-04-15 |accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref> [[Bangladesh Copyright Office]] said that: \"Bachchu is the sole owner of LRB, only his heirs can run the band with the same name.\" On April 15, 2019, Bachchu's son Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub posted in his Facebook account that he was \"okay\" with the other members of the band keeping the name, and later Bachchu's wife and daughter also agreed on it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu's family agrees to let the band keep the name LRB, copyright unclear |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/04/17/ab-family-agrees-to-let-band-keep-lrb-name-copyright-unclear |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=2019-04-17 |accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Solo career ===\n==== Early solo work: 1986-1988 ====\n{{Main|Rokto Golap|Moyna (album)}}\n\nWhile working with [[Souls (band)|Souls]], Bachchu had already recorded and released two album: ''[[Rokto Golap]]'' and ''[[Moyna (album)|Moyna]]'', both of which mostly contained [[pop rock]] songs. Some of the songs on those albums also contained [[Bangladeshi classical music|classical music]] fusion and featured instrument like [[tabla]]. ''Rokto Golap'', contain pop rock, classical and also [[Music of Bangladesh#Modern bangla music|adhunik bangla]] songs, while ''Moyna'' is an album that features pop rock and hard rock songs and helped him get his breakthrough. It has sold an estimated 60,000 copies in Bangladesh. Released in September 1986, ''Rokto Golap'' is his first solo album, released by Zahed Electronics, which contains the first [[hard rock]] song released by him, \"Anamika\". The album featured Ahsan Elahi (Fanty) of [[James (musician)|Feelings]] on drums and percussion. Manam Ahmed of [[Miles (band)|Miles]] on keyboards. Bachchu played both the [[bass guitar]] and [[electric guitar]] on the album. Ahsan Elahi (Fanty) and Manam Ahmed are also featured in his second album. The second album ''Moyna'' also features Emon and Mintu on keyboards and Khayem Pearu on bass guitars.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==== ''Koshto'': 1995 ====\n{{Main|Koshto (album)}}\nBachchu left Souls in the late-1990 and formed his own band [[Love Runs Blind]] in April 5, 1991. The band released the first ever [[double album]] in Bangladesh: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II'' in 1992. Bachchu didn't release a solo album for seven years. After the release of LRB's ''[[Ghumonto Shohore]]'' in 1995, he went on to record the album ''[[Koshto (album)|Koshto]]'' in the Audio Art Studio, where ''Ghumonto Shohore'' was recorded. The album came out in October 1995. The album is regarded by many as his best work. It included hit songs like \"Koshto Pete Valobashi\", \"Koshto Kake Bole\" and \"Jege Achi Eka\". The album was produced by Bachchu and co-produced by Azam Babu and musicians were [[S.I. Tutul]] of LRB on keyboards and Ahsan Elahi (Fanty) of Feelings on drums and percussion. By the release of the album, it was well received by fans. By 1996, the album had sold over 300,000 copies and is one of the best selling albums of Bangladesh.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==== ''Shomoy'' and ''Eka'': 1998-1999 ====\n\nThough [[Bachchu]] left [[Souls (band)|Souls]] because of his love for \"rocking, powerful guitar music\", his solo career was mostly [[pop rock]], [[soft rock]] music. Since the beginning of his career, Bachchu had a fascination for [[blues music|blues]], [[jazz music|jazz]] and [[funk music|funk]]. He's love for those genres reflected on his band, [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]]'s music, but he wanted to do blues, jazz and funk in his solo career. By the early-1998, Bachchu founded his own studio [[AB Kitchen]], which later became a label. Bachchu had already released two [[double albums]] with his band LRB: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II'' in 1992 and ''Amader'' and ''Bishmoy'' in 1998. He wanted to release double albums as a solo artist. The recording sessions for his fourth album ''Shomoy'' and fifth album ''Eka'' started in the mid-1998 in his own studio. Both albums were released in early-1999 by Soundtek Electronics. Both albums wasn't well received by fans like his previous album. About this two albums Bachchu said that:\n\n{{quote|Those albums were not received well at all. My regular audience thought it was too high-thought. They didn't want something so serious. After that, I didn't experiment much in my solo albums. What's the point if no one appreciates them.<ref name=\"What Rocks AB's World?\" />}}\n\n=== Other works ===\nBachchu performed live with Richard and Le Gang, [[Remo Fernandes]], Nandon Bugchi and [[Bickram Ghosh]] of India and [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]], [[Nagar Baul|Feelings]], [[Miles (band)|Miles]], [[Warfaze]]. He appeared as a judge on \"IIM Joka Rock Fest\" in India, [[Benson and hedges|Benson and Hedges Star Search]] I and II, and D-Rockstar I. Bachchu was one of the panel judges of [[Bangladeshi Idol]]. He led LRB at the South Asian Bands Festival 2013. He has worked as a music director for Azam Khan, Niloy Das, [[Khalid Hasan Milu]], [[Tapan Chowdhury (singer)|Tapan Chowdhury]], [[Rupam Islam]], Hasan Abidur Reza Jewel, Alam Ara Minu, Jholo and many others.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ayub Bachhu busy with World Cup song \n|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=217864:ayub-bachhu-busy-with-world-cup-song&catid=182:city-life&Itemid=220 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2014-06-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101082016/http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=217864%3Aayub-bachhu-busy-with-world-cup-song&catid=182%3Acity-life&Itemid=220 |archive-date=2015-01-01}}</ref> Bachchu was renowned for his musical scoring of television commercials. He wrote songs for [[Grameenphone]], provided the tune and music arrangement for the song \"Dol Lage Dol\" for the local television channels on the occasion of the [[FIFA World Cup 2014]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2013/07/01/ayub-bachchu-walks-out-from-bangladeshi-idol|title=Ayub Bachchu walks out from the reality show 'Bangladeshi Idol'|date=2013-07-01|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news/lrb-set-to-participate-in-south-asian-bands-festival-2013|title=LRB set to participate in South Asian Bands Festival 2013|date=2013-11-26|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Five new Ayub Bachchu songs launched by GP |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/five-new-ayub-bachchu-songs-launched-by-gp-12419 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2014-02-22}}</ref> Bachchu collaborated with [[Radio Foorti]] to bring new talents and fresh voices into the spotlight by giving them a platform to perform and shine. Bachchu was one of the leaders of Bangladesh Musical Bands Association (BAMBA). In [[Bangabandhu National Stadium]], in the \"T-20 World Cup 2014\" opening ceremony, Bachchu got in a controversy with [[Hamin Ahmed]] of Miles, which led him to cancel the membership of the association.<ref>{{cite news |last=Malik |first=Shadma |date=2014-07-20 |title=BAMBA to go big with 3-day concert this Eid |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2014/07/19/bamba-to-go-big-with-3-day-concert-this-eid-2 |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n===Personal relationships===\n====Ferdous Chandana====\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Ayub Bachchu and his family.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Ayub Bachchu with his family. Clockwise from top: Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub, Fairuz Saffra Ayub, Ayub Bachchu and Ferdous Chandana]] -->\nBachchu met Ferdous Chandana in the early 1986, when he came to Dhaka to record his debut solo album ''[[Rokto Golap]]''. He said that, he fell in love with Chandana when he saw her picture stuck in his friend's mirror.<ref name=\"What Rocks AB's World?\" /> When Chandana's family found out about Bachchu they didn't let her meet him. He said that the [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]] song \"Ferari Mon\", from the band's ''self titled debut album'' told the story of how he wanted to meet Chandana, \"This mind of mine, doesn\u2019t care for any barrier. Hoping to find you, it comes back again and again.\" He left for Dhaka with only [[Bangladeshi taka|BDT]] \u09f3600 with him.<ref name=\":03\">{{cite news |title=When Bachchu came to Dhaka, he had only 600 taka in his pocket |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/music/when-he-came-to-dhaka-bachchu-had-600-taka-in-his-pocket-shafin-ahmed/articleshow/66301076.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=2018-10-21 |accessdate=2019-05-13 |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad}}</ref> He was struggling to live in Dhaka and pay his rents in the hotel. He got back to [[Chittagong]] after the recording ended for his debut album. When he left [[Souls (band)|Souls]] in late 1990, he came to Dhaka and proposed Chandana to marry him. Chandana's family didn't agree at first, but later both Bachchu's and Chandana's family agreed on letting them marry. He married Chandana on 31 January 1991. The couple had two children: daughter Fairuz Saffra Ayub (b. 1994) and son Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub (b. 1996).{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== AB Kitchen ===\nAB Kitchen is a full service audio recording studio and production company founded by Ayub Bachchu in 1998. Over 40 [[studio albums]], numerous AD Jingles, TV drama, films and film scores have been recorded in the studio. The first album produced by the label was Bachchu's ''[[Shomoy]]'' in 1999. From 2001, all the albums of LRB have been recorded and released by the label. It has also started three projects, including D-Rockstars (2005), R-Music (2006) and Sa 2 Sa (2007). All of these were televised respectively in [[G-Series (record label)|G-Series TV]], [[RTV (Bangladesh)|RTV]] and [[Channel I]].{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n== Musicianship ==\n=== Guitars ===\n{{quotebox|Ayub Bachchu had fallen in love for the first time when he was a teenager. Though it was not just for any tootsie from the neighborhood. It was for the smell of the burnished fret-board and the sound of the six strings that was the gateway to his own utopia. It took him to his paradise, where he kept exploring until the last moments of his life like an evergreen wanderer. Till the very day he died, Bachchu had no less than 60 guitars in his collection, which he took care of like a father does to his children. Over a week has now gone by after the magician's departure. His beloved offspring Tazwar and Fairuz still cannot hide their teary eyes. Come to wonder, aren't his guitars also weeping for their foregoer?<ref name=\":1\"/>\n|source= \u2014 ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'', October 2018|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\nBachchu had cited [[Jimi Hendrix]] as the \"biggest influence on his guitar playing\". He has also cited [[Steve Vai]] and [[Joe Satriani]] as a big influence on his playing. In 2003, after [[S.I. Tutul]] had left [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]], Bachchu further didn't add a [[keyboardist]] in the lineup. He recruited Abdullah al Masud as the rhythm guitarist of the band. Also, Bachchu was becoming interested in guitarists like [[John Petrucci]], [[Jason Becker]], [[Rusty Cooley]] and [[Sacred Mother Tongue]] guitarist Andy James.<ref name=\":06\" /> Since then, LRB's music has gone much louder than the past and the band started releasing [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] songs.\n\nAt the time of his death, Bachchu had a collection of 65 guitars. He mostly played [[Ibanez Guitars|Ibanez]] guitars, particularly the [[Carvin]] guitar. He used [[Carvin Guitars|Carvin]] Kiesel guitars, [[Dean Guitars|Dean]] Rusty Cooley RC6 and Michael Angelo Batio. He also owned various signature guitars by some of his favorite guitarists, including a Steve Vai JEM Junior White, Jason Becker JB200C. In July 2017, he sold five of his guitars to young guitar players, with whom he wanted to start a competition of guitarists.{{efn|Sources indicate that Bachchu sold five of his guitars because he couldn\u2019t bear the maintenance costs for them anymore. The five guitars were [[Ernie Ball]] Music Man Axis, [[Carvin Guitars|Carvin]] Jason Becker, Ernie Ball Music Man [[John Petrucci]] and [[Charvel]].}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu to sell 5 of his guitars |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/153007/Bachchu-to-sell-guitars |work=[[Prothom Alo]] |access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref> He used a [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] JCM2000 amp onstage.\n\n=== Early influences ===\n{{Quotebox|Most of all I like [[Jimi Hendrix|Hendrix]]. He did not make the guitar playing very critical note after note. He played the guitar as per his feelings. I have been trying that.|source= \u2014 ''[[Dhaka Tribune]]'', October 2018|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\nBachchu's singing style has often been found similar to [[Music of Bangladesh#Modern bangla music|Adhunik bangla]] musicians. As he was a bandmate with [[Tapan Chowdhury (singer)|Tapan Chowdhury]] in [[Souls (band)|Souls]], he had an influence from Adhunik music.<ref name=\":07\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu was a complete musician, who could do any kind of music: Tapan Chowdhury |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/185156/Bachchu-was-a-complete-musician-Tapan-Chowdhury |publisher=[[Prothom Alo]] |accessdate=2019-05-16}}</ref> Indian musician Prabuddha Banerjee said that: \"I found his voice extremely romantic and I always wondered if he could sing Bengali retro numbers. In fact, though he was a rock musician, his style of singing always captured the romanticism of adhunik bangla music.<ref name=\":02\" /> Bachchu's high pitched screaming in the LRB songs \"Gotokal Raate\" and \"Khoniker Jonno\", from the band's third album ''[[Shukh (album)|Shukh]]'', has been cited similar to the high pitched vocals of [[Ian Gillan]] of [[Deep Purple]]. He was also a big fan of [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]]. Bachchu was inspired by him to write and sing rock songs in [[Bengali language|Bengali]].\n\nBachchu's lyrics are inspired by [[the Eagles]], [[Deep Purple]], [[Pink Floyd]] and [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]. He has stated that the lyrics' of the Eagles songs \"[[Witchy Woman]]\" and \"[[Hotel California (song)|Hotel California]]\" are one of his most favorite lyrics. Also, [[the Beatles]] and [[Iron Maiden]] were among his lyrics inspiration.<ref name=\":06\" />\n\n== Death ==\nIn 2009, Bachchu underwent a successful heart valve surgery and became a regular patient at the [[Square Hospital, Dhaka|Square Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Legendary Bangladeshi Rockstar Ayub Bachchu dead at 56 |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/legendary-bangladeshi-singer-ayub-bachchu-passes-away-at-56-due-to-heart-failure-1913155.html |publisher=News18 |date=2018-10-18 |accessdate=2019-05-13}}</ref> Bachchu was admitted to the Square Hospital on November 27, 2012. He was admitted  in the [[Coronary Care Unit]] (CCU) under supervision of Dr. Mirza Nizamuddin of the hospital. Bachchu was suffering from lung ailment. Due to accretion of water in his lungs, he was experiencing respiratory problems. He recovered after receiving treatment.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu hospitalised |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=259156 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2012-11-29 |accessdate=2013-01-12}}</ref> On Thursday, 18 October 2018, he died of [[cardiac failure]] at his residence in [[Maghbazar]], [[Dhaka]] at 21:55 [[Bangladesh Standard Time|BST]] at the age of 56.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladeshi rock legend Ayub Bachchu has died |url=https://www.anandabazar.com/bangladesh-news/bangladeshi-rock-music-legend-ayub-bachchu-died-dgtl-1.883319 |publisher=Ananda Bazaar |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref> Dr. Mirza Nizamuddin of Square Hospital's Director of Medical Services said to the ''[[Dhaka Tribune]]'', \"Ayub Bachchu suffered heart failure at his home around 9:30 am, and left for Square Hospital with his driver by car. He died on his way to the hospital. He was found dead on arrival after he reached the hospital at 9:40 am. On-duty doctors announced his death at 9:55 am.<ref name=\": 08\">{{cite news |title=In Memoriam: The artists we lost in 2018 |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2018/12/29/in-memoriam-artistes-we-lost-in-2018 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |accessdate=2019-05-17}}</ref>\" He gave his last performance in [[Rangpur City|Rangpur]], Bangladesh, two days before his death.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rock star Ayub Bachchu passes away: President, PM express deep shock |url=http://unb.com.bd/category/Entertainment/legendary-singer-ayub-bacchu-dies/4502 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |agency=UNB News |publisher=[[United News of Bangladesh]] |date=18 October 2018}}</ref> He was declared dead at the [[Square Hospital, Dhaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/legendary-bangladeshi-singer-ayub-bachchu-passes-away-at-56-due-to-heart-failure-1913155.html|title=Legendary Bangladeshi Singer Ayub Bachchu Passes Away at 56 Due to Heart Failure|publisher=News18}}</ref> He was kept in [[Shaheed Minar, Dhaka|the Central Shaheed Minar]] up to four hours in October 19, where his contemporaries and fans paid tribute to him for the last time.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite news |title=A sea of mourners in the Central Shaheed Minar |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/fans-gather-shaheed-minar-pay-tributes-ayub-bachchu-1649086 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]] |date=20 October 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Popular artist Ayub Bachchu dies at 56 after heart failure |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/ayub-bachchu-popular-bangladeshi-singer-songwriter-and-guitarist-dies-at-56-after-heart-failure-5403281.html |publisher=First Post Entertainment |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref> His first Janaza was held in the National Eidgah Field in Dhaka.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu's Janaza in Dhaka on Friday |url=https://www.jagonews24.com/en/entertainment/news/42096 |publisher=Jago News24 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Remembering Ayub Bachchu through his music |url=http://icetoday.net/2018/10/remembering-ayub-bachchu-through-his-music/ |publisher=icetoday.net |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref> His body was taken to [[Chittagong City]] on 20 October 2018 in his maternal house in East Madarbari.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2018/10/20/ayub-bachchu-laid-to-rest-in-chattogram-amid-outpouring-of-love-tribute|title=Ayub Bachchu laid to rest in Chattogram amid outpouring of love, tribute|access-date=2018-10-21}}</ref> He was taken in the Jamaitul Falah Mosque for his 4th and last [[Janaza]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Last Janaza of Ayub Bachchu held in Jamaitul Falah Mosque in Chittagong |url=http://m.dainikshiksha.com/en/last-tributes-paid-to-ayub-bachchu-1st-janaza-held/152071/ |publisher=Dainik Shiksha |date=2018-10-19 |accessdate=2019-05-14}}</ref> He was buried in the graveyard of Chaitanya Goli, beside his mother's grave.<ref name=\":05\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu laid to rest next to his mother |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/10/20/ayub-bachchu-laid-to-rest-next-to-his-mother |accessdate=October 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Rock legend Ayub Bachchu passes away | url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/ayub-bachchu-passes-away-1648585 | work=The Daily Star | date=2018-10-18 |accessdate=2018-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=India grieves over Ayub Bachchu's untimely demise |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/music/india-and-bangladesh-grieve-over-ayub-bachchus-untimely-demise/articleshow/66272928.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Tribute concert ===\n\nAfter the death of Bachchu, rock and [[metal music|metal]] artists of Bangladesh held a tribute concert at the Music and Dance Auditorium of [[Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy]] on December 2, 2018, arranged by BAMBA.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu: While a Nation Gently Weeps |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/showbiz/ayub-bachchu-sudden-death-while-nation-gently-weeps-1652206 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=27 October 2018 |accessdate=10 May 2019 |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad}}</ref> Some of the notable performances included, \"Keu Shukhi Noy\" performed by [[Shafin Ahmed]], \"Rupali Guitar\" performed by [[Bappa Mazumder]], \"Nil Bedona\" by Jamshed Chowdhury ([[Powersurge (band)|Powersurge]]). Emil (Shunno) and Sufi ([[Arbovirus (band)|Arbovirus]]) together performed the song \"Bangladesh\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Tribute to Ayub Bachchu by BAMBA |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/music/tribute-to-music-legend-ayub-bachchu-bamba-farewell-1668256 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]] |date=3 December 2018 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nArtists from both [[West Bengal]] and Bangladesh held a tribute concert for Bachchu at the Patuli Lokosanskriti Mela Ground in Kolkata on 24 December, titled \"In the Memorium of Ayub Bachchu, the Rocking of two Bangla\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Tribute Concert in Kolkata |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2018/11/14/ayub-bachchu-tribute-concert-in-kolkata-on-nov-24 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=14 November 2018 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=In Memorium of Ayub Bachchu |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/feature/2018/11/25/two-bengals-pay-tribute-to-ayub-bachchu-in-kolkata |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=25 November 2018 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref> The concert was organized by Cafe Kabira, a popular cafe in Kolkata. Bangladeshi musicians included, Maqsood Haque (Maqsood 'O Dhaka), Sina Hasan (Bangla Five), George Lincoln D'Costa ([[Artcell]]), Mehreen, Subrata Barua Rony (ex-[[Souls (band)|Souls]]), Imran Hussain ([[Rockstrata]]). Bachchu's teacher Jacob Dayas was also present at the concert. The show featured Indian artists like, Pradip Chattopadhyay Bula and Bapi ([[Moheener Ghoraguli]]), Anindya (Shohor), Avijit Burman and Soumitra Roy (Bhumi), Upal (Chandrabindu), [[Shilajit Majumder]], Gaurav Chattopadhyai (Lakkhichhara), Bramhakhapa, Deb Chowdhury and Sidhu (Cactus) performed at the concert.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n10 Bangladeshi bands from [[Canada]] including, Oboshor, Band4, Tulu and the Lightman, Sector 2.0, Reflection, Chandan and Friends, Shoor, Shikor, Jantrik, TWB and Manush held a tribute concert at the [[Blessed Cardinal Newman Catholic High School|Cardinal Newman High School]] in [[Toronto]] on December 15, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu goes International |url=http://news.priyo.com/entertainment/2012/01/21/ayub-bachchu-goes-internationa-45695.html |work=Priyo |date=2012-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123095605/http://news.priyo.com/entertainment/2012/01/21/ayub-bachchu-goes-internationa-45695.html |archive-date=2012-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{quote box|quote=\"The trend in Bangladeshi music that Azam Khan initiated was taken to a new height by Ayub Bachchu. His death is an irreparable loss for Bangladeshi music.\"|source = \u2013 [[Fakir Alamgir]]<ref name=\":10\" />|width=27%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\n\nBachchu is widely regarded as one of the greatest and most influential guitarist of Bangladesh. He ranked second on ''The Top Tens'' list of \"Top 10 Greatest Guitarist of Bangladesh\". [[Ibrahim Ahmed Kamal]] who ranked first in the list has said that, \"The ranking is not correct, it was created to abuse the Great Ayub Bachchu\". He is also credited for popularizing [[rock music]] in Bangladesh in the 1990s as the frontman of [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]] and as a solo artist, along with Nagar Baul, [[Miles (band)|Miles]] and [[Ark (Bangladeshi band)|Ark]].<ref name=\":07\" /> He is also considered to be one of the \"big three rockstars of Bangladesh\" along with [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]] and [[James (musician)|James]].{{sfn|Kimmerman|2009|p=26}} He is also considered to be the first electric guitarist in Bangladesh to use [[Distortion|distortion]] in songs. About that he said to Ekattor TV: \"I was being forced to leave [[Souls (band)|Souls]], because I wanted to play distorted guitar\".\n\nGuitarist who were influenced by him includes, Ibrahim Ahmed Kamal ([[Warfaze]]), [[Iqbal Asif Jewel]] ([[Miles (band)|Miles]], Legend, Warfaze), Ershad Zaman ([[Artcell]]), George Lincoln D' Costa (Artcell), Kazi Faisal Mahmud (Metal Maze, Artcell), Oni Hasan (Vibe, Warfaze), Emon Chowdhury ([[Chirkut]]), Samir Hafiz ([[Powersurge (band)|Powersurge]], [[Severe Dementia]], [[Raef al Hasan Rafa|AvoidRafa]]).\n\nEx-Minister of Cultural Affairs, [[Asaduzzaman Noor]] said, \"the fact that people from all walk of life were affected by the departure of Ayub Bachchu is testament to his greatness as an artist. I was fortunate enough to have personally known him since his starting days. He was an immensely passionate person.\" [[Hamin Ahmed]] of [[Miles (band)|Miles]] said, \"when Ayub Bachchu started his career, the guitar wasn't as prominent as an instrument. He made sure that it was the heart and soul of his music, and the entire country followed. That alone is enough to explain his legacy.\" [[Bappa Mazumder]] of [[Dalchhut]] said, \"The great man not only taught us about music, but taught us how to be a great human. I always admired how much he loved his mother, and requested other people to take care of their parents.\" Indian singer-songwriter [[Sahana Bajpaie]] said to ''[[Daily Sun (Bangladesh)|Daily Sun]]'': \"I was 12 when I first realised there is a Bengali musician who plays the guitar like Jimi Hendrix. He was one of the pioneers of Bengali rock music. My teenage was inspired by his music. He became a family friend when I was in Bangladesh. His simplicity was outstanding. His contributions to music will be remembered by generations to come.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{cite news |title=India music world mourns over the untimely demise of legendary Bangla rock singer Ayub Bachchu |url=https://www.daily-sun.com/post/344059/2018/10/18/India-music-world-mourns-for-Ayub-Bachchu%E2%80%99s-premature-death |work=[[Daily Sun (Bangladesh)|Daily Sun]] |date=2018-10-18 |accessdate=2019-05-12 |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad}}</ref>\n\nIn 19 December 2018 [[Asif Akbar]] has released a song for Ayub Bachchu, with the title \"A Tribute to the Great Legend Ayub Bachchu\" from Dhruba Music Station.<ref name=\"A Tribute\">{{cite news |title=Asif Akbar releases new song for Ayub Bachchu |url=http://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=173857 |work=The Daily Observer |date=19 December 2018 |access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rupali Guitar (01).jpg|thumb|The Rupali Guitar in [[Chittagong|Probortok Circle, Chittagong]]]]\n\nOn 20 October 2018, the mayor of [[Chittagong City Corporation]], [[A J M Nasir Uddin]] proposed that an \"important road in the port city Chittagong be named after him and a seminar hall in Muslim Hall be named after him.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=An important road in the port city chittagong would be named after Ayub Bachchu: CCC Mayor |url=https://m.daily-bangladesh.com/english/A-port-city-road-to-be-named-after-Ayub-Bachchu-CCC-Mayor/12426 |work=The Daily Bangladesh |date=2018-10-20 |accessdate=2019-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad |title=Chittagong City Corporation to name road after Ayub Bachchu |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2018/10/20/chittagong-road-to-be-named-after-ayub-bachchu |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=2018-10-20 |accessdate=2019-05-04}}</ref> Chattogram City Corporation Mayor AJM Nasir Uddin unveiled the sculpture of the guitar at the Probortok intersection in Chattogram. The sculpture of the 18-feet tall guitar is made of steel and has six strings.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ashfaque |last=Nipun |title=THE RUPALI GUITAR strikes a chord |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/the-rupali-guitar-strikes-chord-1801960 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=19 September 2019 |accessdate=12 October 2019 |}}</ref>\n\n=== Achievements ===\n16th '''[[Tele Cine Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2017 || Ayub Bachchu || Lifetime Achievement Award<ref>{{cite news |author=|title=Six Bangladeshi artists win the Tele Cine Awards |url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/17103/bangladeshi-film-artistes-win-awards-in-kolkata |work=New Age |accessdate=15 March 2019 |date=2017-06-05}}</ref>|| {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n32nd '''[[Bachsas Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2004 || Ayub Bachchu || Best Male Vocal<ref name=\"32nd BACHSAS\">{{cite news |author1=Afsar Ahmed |title=32nd BACHSAS Awards: A glitzy night Recognition of outstanding media talents |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2004/06/28/d406281402119.htm |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=28 June 2004}}</ref> || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n'''[[Meril Prothom Alo Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 1998 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1999 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2000 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|- \n| 2001 || ''Mon Chaile Mon Pabe {{small|(You'll Get My Heart if You Want it)}}'' || Album of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2005 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Sporsho {{small|(Touch)}}'' || Album of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2009 || \"Bolini Tomai {{small|(Didn't Tell You)}}\" || Best Male Vocal of the Year || {{nominated}}\n{{end}}\n\n'''[[Channel i Music Awards|Citycell-Channel I Music Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Sporsho {{small|(Touch)}}'' || Album of the Year || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{See also|Love Runs Blind discography}}\n\n=== Solo albums ===\n* ''[[Rokto Golap]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Moyna (album)|Moyna]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Koshto (album)|Koshto]]'' (1995)\n* ''Shomoy'' (1999)\n* ''Eka'' (1999)\n* ''Prem Tumi Ki'' (2000)\n* ''Duti Mon'' (2002)\n* ''Kafela'' (2002)\n* ''Prem Premer Moto'' (2003)\n* ''Pother Gaan'' (2004)\n* ''Vatir Gaane Matir Tane'' (2006)\n* ''Jibon'' (2006)\n* ''Sound of Silence'' (2007)\n* ''Rim Jhim Brishti'' (2008)\n* ''Bolini Kokhono'' (2009)\n* ''Jiboner Golpo'' (2015)\n\n=== Souls ===\n{{Main|Souls (band)#discography}}\n* ''Super Souls'' (1982)\n* ''College Er Corridore'' (1985)\n* ''Manush Matir Kachakachi'' (1987)\n* ''East and West'' (1988)\n\n=== Film scores ===\nBelow is the list of films where Bachchu produced the original soundtrack.\n* ''Luttoraj'' (1996)\n* ''Sagorika'' (1998)\n* ''Lal Badshah'' (1999)\n* ''[[Ammajan]]'' (1999)\n* ''Gunda Number 1'' (2000)\n* ''[[Bachelor (2004 film)|Bachelor]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Wrong Number (2004 film)|Wrong Number]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Chander Moto Bou]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Chorabali]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Television (2012 film)|Television]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Ek Cup Cha]]'' (2014)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-221089|title=Playback time|date=2012-02-04|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |script-title=bn:\u2018\u0986\u0987\u09af\u09bc\u09c1\u09ac \u09ac\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09c1 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09be \u09b8\u09ac\u09c1\u099c \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0997\u09be\u09a8 |url=https://www.dw.com/bn/\u0986\u0987\u09af\u09bc\u09c1\u09ac-\u09ac\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09c1-\u098f\u0995\u099f\u09be-\u09b8\u09ac\u09c1\u099c-\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be-\u0997\u09be\u09a8/a-45935069 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=2018-10-18 |language=bn |access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Love Runs Blind]]\n* [[Shei Tumi|\u099a\u09b2\u09cb \u09ac\u09a6\u09b2\u09c7 \u09af\u09be\u09af\u09bc (Let's Change)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n====Bibliography====\n* {{citebook |title=Where Am I Wearing? A Global Tour to the Countries, Factories and People That Make Our Clothes |first=Kelsey |last=Kimmerman |year=2009 |isbn=9781118277553|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |b=no |c=Category:Ayub Bachchu |d=Q4831762 |m=no |mw=no |n=no |q=Ayub Bachchu |s=no |species=no |v=no |voy=no |wikt=no}}\n* [http://www.ablrb.net Official Website]\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/6471404 Ayub Bachchu] discography on [[Discogs]]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4620075/ Ayub Bachchu] on [[IMDb]]\n* [https://www.last.fm/music/AYUB%2BBACHCHU Ayub Bachchu] on [[Last.fm]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bachchu, Ayub}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male musicians]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi rock singers]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male singers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi socialists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bangladeshi singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bangladeshi singers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi playback singers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi record producers]]\n[[Category:People from Chittagong]]\n[[Category:Government Muslim High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Bachsas Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Bengali musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Bangladeshi singer, musician, guitarist and record producer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name             = Ayub Bachchu\n| image            = LRB Ayub Bachchu (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Bachchu performing live in the ''[[Emami]]'' Fair and Handsome Award in October 2014.\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = bn\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1962|08|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Patiya Upazila|Patiya]], [[Chittagong]], [[East Pakistan]] (Now in Chittagong, Bangladesh)\n| nationality      = [[Bangladeshi]]\n| education        = [[Govt. Muslim High School]], Chittagong \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2018|10|18|1962|08|16|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh\n| death_cause      = [[Cardiac failure]]\n| resting_place    = Buried in Chaitanya Goli, Chittagong, Bangladesh \n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|record producer|businessman}}\n| father           = Ishaque Chowdhury\n| mother           = Nurjahan Begum\n| spouse           = {{ubl|{{marriage|Ferdous Ayub Chandana|31 January 1991|18 October 2018|his death}}}}\n| children         = 2; including Fairuz and Ahnaf\n| website          = {{URL|ablrb.net}}\n| module = \n {{Infobox musical artist\n | embed = yes\n | background = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n | origin           = Chittagong, Bangladesh \n | years_active     = 1977\u20132018\n | genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n | instrument       = {{hlist|[[Guitar]]|[[bass guitar|bass]]|[[vocals]]|[[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]}}\n | label            = {{hlist|CMV|AB Kitchen|Soundtek|Sargam|Sangeeta}}\n | associated_acts  = {{hlist | [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]] | [[Souls (band)|Souls]] | [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]] | [[James (musician)|James]] | [[Kumar Bishwajit]] | [[Asif Akbar]] | [[S.I. Tutul]] }}\n }} <!-- end of Infobox musical artist -->\n| signature        = Ayub Bachchu Robin signature.jpg\n}} <!-- end of Infobox person -->\n\n'''Ayub Bachchu''' ({{IPA-bn|ae\u032fub bat\u0283t\u0283u}}; 16 August 1962 &ndash; 18 October 2018) was a Bangladeshi [[rock music|rock]] guitarist, composer and singer-songwriter, who was the founder of the Bangladeshi rock band [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]]<ref>{{cite news |author=Saimum Saad |title=Ayub Bachchu sole owner of LRB, only heirs can run it: Copyright Office |url=https://bdnews24.com/entertainment/2019/04/16/ayub-bachchu-sole-owner-of-lrb-only-heirs-can-run-it-copyright-office |work=bdnews24.com |date=2019-04-16 |access-date=18 April 2019}}</ref> and earned success as the lead singer and the lead guitarist of the band.\n\nBorn in [[Patiya Upazila|Patiya]], Bachchu came to [[Chittagong]] with his family in the early 1970s. He formed his first band \"Ugly Boys\" in 1977, while studying in high school and joined in rock band Feelings (Now known as Nagar Baul) as the guitarist the same year. He played in the band from 1977 to 1980. In 1980, he joined [[Souls (band)|Souls]] where he played for ten years and appeared in four studio albums including ''Super Souls'' (1982), ''College Er Corridore'' (1985), ''Manush Matir Kachakachi'' (1987) and ''East and West'' (1988). In 1991, he left the band to form his own band LRB, where he was the vocalist and guitarist for 27 years, until his death in 2018. He released the first ever [[double album]]: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II'' in 1992, with the band. LRB's third studio album ''[[Shukh (album)|Shukh]]'', which featured \"[[Cholo Bodle Jai]]\", one of the greatest rock songs in Bangladesh. He also received well success as a solo artist. His first solo album ''[[Rokto Golap]]'' was released in September 1986. He got his breakthrough by releasing albums like ''[[Moyna (album)|Moyna]]'' (1988) and ''[[Koshto (album)|Koshto]]'' (1995) which received well success. He released only one [[instrumental rock]] album in his career: ''Sound of Silence'' (2007), which is the first ever instrumental album in Bangladesh.\n\nBachchu released several best selling-albums with LRB, and as a solo performer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu - New Music, Songs Playlist and Latest News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/591b4193-7876-4508-87f4-9ae67f4f3d46 |publisher=[[BBC Music]] |accessdate=2019-05-14 |first=\u0989\u0987\u09b2\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09ae |last=\u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09cd\u09ab\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u0987}}</ref> Bachchu is widely regarded as the greatest and most influential guitarist of [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu: An inspiration for the young generation |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/185153/Rock-inspiration-for-the-young |publisher=[[Prothom Alo]] |date=19 October 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> He has won six [[Meril Prothom Alo Awards]], one [[Channel i Music Awards|Citycell-Channel I Music Award]] with LRB and won the [[Bachsas Awards]] in the Best Male Vocal category in 2004. In 2017, he won the [[Tele Cine Awards|Tele Cine]] Lifetime Achievement Award.\n\nBachchu married his girlfriend Ferdous Ayub Chandana on January 31, 1991, with whom he had a daughter, Fairuz Saffra Ayub and a son, Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub. In October 2018, Bachchu died of [[cardiac failure]] in his own residence in Dhaka, six years after he was suffering of lung ailment. He gave his last performance in [[Rangpur City]] two days before his death. He was buried in Chaitanya Goli in Chittagong, beside his mother's grave.<ref name=\":05\" />\n\n==Early life==\n\nBachchu was born in Chittagong in [[Patiya Upazila|Patiya]] at Khorna union on 16 August 1962 to Mohammad Ishaque Chowdhury (father) and Nurjahan Begum (mother).<ref name=\":09\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu - Celebrities of Bangladesh |url=https://www.mediabangladesh.net/bcard/ayub-bachchu/ |publisher=Media Bangladesh |accessdate=2019-05-19}}</ref> The family moved to the Chittagong city after the [[Liberation War of Bangladesh]]. They resided in Jubilee Road. He had a brother and a sister. He was the eldest among them. His nickname was Robin. He got his first acoustic guitar from his father as a gift 1973, when he was in class four. He learned to play guitar from Jacob Dayas a [[Myanmar|Burmese]] man, who used to live in Chittagong. He borrowed an electric guitar from his friend,[[Kumar Bishwajit]], which was a [[Teisco|Teisco Guitar]]. Bishwajit gave him the guitar after he [Bachchu] showed more interest towards it. He was very attracted to the guitar playing techniques of [[Jimi Hendrix]] and [[Joe Satriani]]. He was admitted to [[Government Muslim High School]] in 1975. In 1979, he graduated from Muslim High School.<ref name=\":06\">{{cite news |last=Ul Ibad |first=Mahid |title=I always had one goal, and that was to become a musician, I had no other option |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/10/18/i-always-had-one-goal-and-that-was-to-become-a-musician-i-had-no-other-option-2 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=9 August 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> His parents did not support him on becoming a musician. But, after his family saw his passion for rock music, they agreed on letting him become a musician. While studying in high school, Bachchu formed a band named \"Golden Boys\", which was later renamed as \"Ugly Boys\". Kumar Bishwajit was the lead singer of the band and Bachchu was the guitarist. They used to do club shows and shows in weddings (Mostly in the Patiya Upazilla). The group disbanded after Bachchu joined [[Souls (band)|Souls]] in 1980.<ref name=\"Ayub Bachchu at a glance\">{{cite news |author=Mahid Ul Ibad |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/185118/Ayub-Bachchu-at-a-glance|title=Ayub Bachchu at a glance |publisher=[[Prothom Alo]] |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== 1977&ndash;1990: Feelings and Souls ===\n{{Further|James (musician)|Souls (band)}}\nWhile working with his own band Ugly Boys, Bachchu joined the [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Nagar Baul|Feelings]] (now known as Nagar Baul) in 1977. Feelings' frontman [[James (musician)|James]] stated that he saw Bachchu playing guitar at a tea stall. He was amazed by the playing style of Bachchu and he asked him to join the band. In the mid-1977, he joined the band as the lead guitarist and only stayed with the band for next two years until in 1980, he got a contract from Souls, as their lead guitarist Sajed ul Alam had left the band for the [[United States]]. Bachchu was playing with Feelings in a club in Chittagong, where Souls' keyboards player Naqib Khan was present. He was amazed by the playing of Bachchu and he talked to lead singer [[Tapan Chowdhury (singer)|Tapan Chowdhury]] about it. Both of them saw Bachchu playing in the club next day and they asked him to join Souls. He joined Souls in early-1980 and played with the band for next 10 years as the lead guitarist, songwriter and occasional singer. He had appeared on four studio albums of the band, including ''Super Souls'' (1982), ''College Er Corridore'' (1985) and ''Manush Matir Kachakachi'' (1987), which features the first song sung by him, \"Harano Bikeler Golpo\". His last album with Souls was ''East and West'' (1988). In the late-1990, Bachchu left Souls and went on to form his own band [[Love Runs Blind|Little River Band]], which later became famous as Love Runs Blind. He reunited with Souls in several reunion shows and has performed with members of the band like [[Tapan Chowdhury]], [[Kumar Bishwajit]] and Naqib Khan in several shows.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.dw.com/bn/\u09ad\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0-\u0995\u09be\u0981\u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7-\u098f\u09ac\u09bf-\u0989\u09a1\u09bc\u09be\u09b2-\u09a6\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8-\u0986\u0995\u09be\u09b6\u09c7/g-45939606| title=\u09ad\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09be\u0981\u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u2018\u098f\u09ac\u09bf\u2019 \u0989\u09a1\u09bc\u09be\u09b2 \u09a6\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u0986\u0995\u09be\u09b6\u09c7| publisher=Deutsche Welle| date=2018-10-18| accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu: Life of a Maestro |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/feature/people-feature/2018/10/18/ayub-bachchu-life-of-a-maestro |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=18 October 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Bachchu told ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'' that:\n\n{{quote|I left Souls because of two different tastes in sounds. They liked one kind of music, I liked another. I was into loud, rocking, powerful sounds, and the rest of the members wanted quiet, melodious sounds. You cannot just compromise day after day. We never really had any big arguments, but it occurred to me that it would be better if I just quit and do something different.<ref name=\"What Rocks AB's World?\">{{cite news |author=Sushmita S. Preetha |title=What Rocks AB's World? |url=https://archive.thedailystar.net/magazine/2012/11/02/cover.htm |work=Star Weeknd |publisher=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=2012-11-09 |access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref>}}\n\n=== 1991-2018: LRB ===\n{{Main|Love Runs Blind}}\n[[File:Ayub Bachchu.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Bachchu performing at the City of Winter Garden in 2008]]\n\nAfter Bachchu got out of [[Souls (band)|Souls]] in the late-1990, he came to Dhaka in 1991 and in January he married Ferdous Chandana, with whom he had a relationship since 1986. He formed a band named '''Yellow River Band''' in April 5, 1991 with [[S.I. Tutul]] on keyboards, Saidul Hasan Swapan on bass guitars and Habib Anwar Joy on drums.{{efn|Many have stated that Bachchu named his band Little Robin's Band (as his nickname was Robin) when forming in 1991 and changed the name in 1997 when Bachchu found out he was not little anymore. But, it is considered to be a rumor as Bachchu was already 29 years old when he was forming the band. Bachchu has stated that Yellow River Band was the band's first name and they were mistakenly called Little River Band in a club show in Dhaka. As Bachchu liked the name he kept the name for the band. But, they had to change it again in 1997 after finding out about the australian rock band with the same name.}} When they were performing in a club in the mid-1991, they were mistakenly called the '''Little River Band''', which Bachchu liked and officially named his band. But, after they heard about the [[Little River Band|Australian rock band of the same name]] they changed their name to '''Love Runs Blind''' in 1997. In April 1991, LRB did their first ever concert in the [[University of Dhaka]], a concert that was arranged by BAMBA, celebrating the downfall of autocratic leader [[Hussein Muhammad Ershad]]. In January 1992, they released the first ever [[double album]]: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II''. The band's third studio album ''[[Shukh (album)|Shukh]]'', was released in June 1993 and is considered one of the greatest rock albums of Bangladesh. It included \"[[Cholo Bodle Jai]]\", which regarded by some as Bachchu's greatest work. They released several albums in the 1990s and soon became one of the most popular rock acts of Bangladesh. In 1996, they performed in [[Bengaluru]], which was their first concert outside Bangladesh. LRB is the only Bangladeshi artist to perform in the [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/ayub-bachchu-passes-away-1648585| title=Rock legend Ayub Bachchu passes away| date=2018-10-18| work=The Daily Star| accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref>\n\nAfter Bachchu's death, the other members of LRB announced [[Balam (singer)|Balam Jahangir]] as their new lead singer. Bachchu's wife and daughter was not satisfied with the members of the band performing with a new singer under the name LRB. They asked the members to change the name. The band was disbanded for few days and the other members of the band along with Balam formed a new band named, \"Balam and the Legacy\".<ref name=\"Balam and the Legacy\">{{cite news |title=Love Runs Blind changes name to Balam and the Legacy |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/04/15/lrb-changes-name-to-balam-the-legacy |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=2019-04-15 |accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref> [[Bangladesh Copyright Office]] said that: \"Bachchu is the sole owner of LRB, only his heirs can run the band with the same name.\" On April 15, 2019, Bachchu's son Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub posted in his Facebook account that he was \"okay\" with the other members of the band keeping the name, and later Bachchu's wife and daughter also agreed on it.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu's family agrees to let the band keep the name LRB, copyright unclear |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2019/04/17/ab-family-agrees-to-let-band-keep-lrb-name-copyright-unclear |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=2019-04-17 |accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Solo career ===\n==== Early solo work: 1986-1988 ====\n{{Main|Rokto Golap|Moyna (album)}}\n\nWhile working with [[Souls (band)|Souls]], Bachchu had already recorded and released two album: ''[[Rokto Golap]]'' and ''[[Moyna (album)|Moyna]]'', both of which mostly contained [[pop rock]] songs. Some of the songs on those albums also contained [[Bangladeshi classical music|classical music]] fusion and featured instrument like [[tabla]]. ''Rokto Golap'', contain pop rock, classical and also [[Music of Bangladesh#Modern bangla music|adhunik bangla]] songs, while ''Moyna'' is an album that features pop rock and hard rock songs and helped him get his breakthrough. It has sold an estimated 60,000 copies in Bangladesh. Released in September 1986, ''Rokto Golap'' is his first solo album, released by Zahed Electronics, which contains the first [[hard rock]] song released by him, \"Anamika\". The album featured Ahsan Elahi (Fanty) of [[James (musician)|Feelings]] on drums and percussion. Manam Ahmed of [[Miles (band)|Miles]] on keyboards. Bachchu played both the [[bass guitar]] and [[electric guitar]] on the album. Ahsan Elahi (Fanty) and Manam Ahmed are also featured in his second album. The second album ''Moyna'' also features Emon and Mintu on keyboards and Khayem Pearu on bass guitars.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==== ''Koshto'': 1995 ====\n{{Main|Koshto (album)}}\nBachchu left Souls in the late-1990 and formed his own band [[Love Runs Blind]] in April 5, 1991. The band released the first ever [[double album]] in Bangladesh: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II'' in 1992. Bachchu didn't release a solo album for seven years. After the release of LRB's ''[[Ghumonto Shohore]]'' in 1995, he went on to record the album ''[[Koshto (album)|Koshto]]'' in the Audio Art Studio, where ''Ghumonto Shohore'' was recorded. The album came out in October 1995. The album is regarded by many as his best work. It included hit songs like \"Koshto Pete Valobashi\", \"Koshto Kake Bole\" and \"Jege Achi Eka\". The album was produced by Bachchu and co-produced by Azam Babu and musicians were [[S.I. Tutul]] of LRB on keyboards and Ahsan Elahi (Fanty) of Feelings on drums and percussion. By the release of the album, it was well received by fans. By 1996, the album had sold over 300,000 copies and is one of the best selling albums of Bangladesh.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n==== ''Shomoy'' and ''Eka'': 1998-1999 ====\n\nThough [[Bachchu]] left [[Souls (band)|Souls]] because of his love for \"rocking, powerful guitar music\", his solo career was mostly [[pop rock]], [[soft rock]] music. Since the beginning of his career, Bachchu had a fascination for [[blues music|blues]], [[jazz music|jazz]] and [[funk music|funk]]. He's love for those genres reflected on his band, [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]]'s music, but he wanted to do blues, jazz and funk in his solo career. By the early-1998, Bachchu founded his own studio [[AB Kitchen]], which later became a label. Bachchu had already released two [[double albums]] with his band LRB: ''LRB I'' and ''LRB II'' in 1992 and ''Amader'' and ''Bishmoy'' in 1998. He wanted to release double albums as a solo artist. The recording sessions for his fourth album ''Shomoy'' and fifth album ''Eka'' started in the mid-1998 in his own studio. Both albums were released in early-1999 by Soundtek Electronics. Both albums wasn't well received by fans like his previous album. About this two albums Bachchu said that:\n\n{{quote|Those albums were not received well at all. My regular audience thought it was too high-thought. They didn't want something so serious. After that, I didn't experiment much in my solo albums. What's the point if no one appreciates them.<ref name=\"What Rocks AB's World?\" />}}\n\n=== Other works ===\nBachchu performed live with Richard and Le Gang, [[Remo Fernandes]], Nandon Bugchi and [[Bickram Ghosh]] of India and [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]], [[Nagar Baul|Feelings]], [[Miles (band)|Miles]], [[Warfaze]]. He appeared as a judge on \"IIM Joka Rock Fest\" in India, [[Benson and hedges|Benson and Hedges Star Search]] I and II, and D-Rockstar I. Bachchu was one of the panel judges of [[Bangladeshi Idol]]. He led LRB at the South Asian Bands Festival 2013. He has worked as a music director for Azam Khan, Niloy Das, [[Khalid Hasan Milu]], [[Tapan Chowdhury (singer)|Tapan Chowdhury]], [[Rupam Islam]], Hasan Abidur Reza Jewel, Alam Ara Minu, Jholo and many others.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ayub Bachhu busy with World Cup song \n|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=217864:ayub-bachhu-busy-with-world-cup-song&catid=182:city-life&Itemid=220 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2014-06-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101082016/http://www.theindependentbd.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=217864%3Aayub-bachhu-busy-with-world-cup-song&catid=182%3Acity-life&Itemid=220 |archive-date=2015-01-01}}</ref> Bachchu was renowned for his musical scoring of television commercials. He wrote songs for [[Grameenphone]], provided the tune and music arrangement for the song \"Dol Lage Dol\" for the local television channels on the occasion of the [[FIFA World Cup 2014]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2013/07/01/ayub-bachchu-walks-out-from-bangladeshi-idol|title=Ayub Bachchu walks out from the reality show 'Bangladeshi Idol'|date=2013-07-01|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news/lrb-set-to-participate-in-south-asian-bands-festival-2013|title=LRB set to participate in South Asian Bands Festival 2013|date=2013-11-26|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Five new Ayub Bachchu songs launched by GP |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/five-new-ayub-bachchu-songs-launched-by-gp-12419 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2014-02-22}}</ref> Bachchu collaborated with [[Radio Foorti]] to bring new talents and fresh voices into the spotlight by giving them a platform to perform and shine. Bachchu was one of the leaders of Bangladesh Musical Bands Association (BAMBA). In [[Bangabandhu National Stadium]], in the \"T-20 World Cup 2014\" opening ceremony, Bachchu got in a controversy with [[Hamin Ahmed]] of Miles, which led him to cancel the membership of the association.<ref>{{cite news |last=Malik |first=Shadma |date=2014-07-20 |title=BAMBA to go big with 3-day concert this Eid |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/uncategorized/2014/07/19/bamba-to-go-big-with-3-day-concert-this-eid-2 |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune|accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n===Personal relationships===\n====Ferdous Chandana====\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Ayub Bachchu and his family.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Ayub Bachchu with his family. Clockwise from top: Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub, Fairuz Saffra Ayub, Ayub Bachchu and Ferdous Chandana]] -->\nBachchu met Ferdous Chandana in the early 1986, when he came to Dhaka to record his debut solo album ''[[Rokto Golap]]''. He said that, he fell in love with Chandana when he saw her picture stuck in his friend's mirror.<ref name=\"What Rocks AB's World?\" /> When Chandana's family found out about Bachchu they didn't let her meet him. He said that the [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]] song \"Ferari Mon\", from the band's ''self titled debut album'' told the story of how he wanted to meet Chandana, \"This mind of mine, doesn\u2019t care for any barrier. Hoping to find you, it comes back again and again.\" He left for Dhaka with only [[Bangladeshi taka|BDT]] \u09f3600 with him.<ref name=\":03\">{{cite news |title=When Bachchu came to Dhaka, he had only 600 taka in his pocket |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/music/when-he-came-to-dhaka-bachchu-had-600-taka-in-his-pocket-shafin-ahmed/articleshow/66301076.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=2018-10-21 |accessdate=2019-05-13 |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad}}</ref> He was struggling to live in Dhaka and pay his rents in the hotel. He got back to [[Chittagong]] after the recording ended for his debut album. When he left [[Souls (band)|Souls]] in late 1990, he came to Dhaka and proposed Chandana to marry him. Chandana's family didn't agree at first, but later both Bachchu's and Chandana's family agreed on letting them marry. He married Chandana on 31 January 1991. The couple had two children: daughter Fairuz Saffra Ayub (b. 1994) and son Ahnaf Tazwar Ayub (b. 1996).{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== AB Kitchen ===\nAB Kitchen is a full service audio recording studio and production company founded by Ayub Bachchu in 1998. Over 40 [[studio albums]], numerous AD Jingles, TV drama, films and film scores have been recorded in the studio. The first album produced by the label was Bachchu's ''[[Shomoy]]'' in 1999. From 2001, all the albums of LRB have been recorded and released by the label. It has also started three projects, including D-Rockstars (2005), R-Music (2006) and Sa 2 Sa (2007). All of these were televised respectively in [[G-Series (record label)|G-Series TV]], [[RTV (Bangladesh)|RTV]] and [[Channel I]].{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n== Musicianship ==\n=== Guitars ===\n{{quotebox|Ayub Bachchu had fallen in love for the first time when he was a teenager. Though it was not just for any tootsie from the neighborhood. It was for the smell of the burnished fret-board and the sound of the six strings that was the gateway to his own utopia. It took him to his paradise, where he kept exploring until the last moments of his life like an evergreen wanderer. Till the very day he died, Bachchu had no less than 60 guitars in his collection, which he took care of like a father does to his children. Over a week has now gone by after the magician's departure. His beloved offspring Tazwar and Fairuz still cannot hide their teary eyes. Come to wonder, aren't his guitars also weeping for their foregoer?<ref name=\":1\"/>\n|source= \u2014 ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]'', October 2018|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\nBachchu had cited [[Jimi Hendrix]] as the \"biggest influence on his guitar playing\". He has also cited [[Steve Vai]] and [[Joe Satriani]] as a big influence on his playing. In 2003, after [[S.I. Tutul]] had left [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]], Bachchu further didn't add a [[keyboardist]] in the lineup. He recruited Abdullah al Masud as the rhythm guitarist of the band. Also, Bachchu was becoming interested in guitarists like [[John Petrucci]], [[Jason Becker]], [[Rusty Cooley]] and [[Sacred Mother Tongue]] guitarist Andy James.<ref name=\":06\" /> Since then, LRB's music has gone much louder than the past and the band started releasing [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] songs.\n\nAt the time of his death, Bachchu had a collection of 65 guitars. He mostly played [[Ibanez Guitars|Ibanez]] guitars, particularly the [[Carvin]] guitar. He used [[Carvin Guitars|Carvin]] Kiesel guitars, [[Dean Guitars|Dean]] Rusty Cooley RC6 and Michael Angelo Batio. He also owned various signature guitars by some of his favorite guitarists, including a Steve Vai JEM Junior White, Jason Becker JB200C. In July 2017, he sold five of his guitars to young guitar players, with whom he wanted to start a competition of guitarists.{{efn|Sources indicate that Bachchu sold five of his guitars because he couldn\u2019t bear the maintenance costs for them anymore. The five guitars were [[Ernie Ball]] Music Man Axis, [[Carvin Guitars|Carvin]] Jason Becker, Ernie Ball Music Man [[John Petrucci]] and [[Charvel]].}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu to sell 5 of his guitars |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/153007/Bachchu-to-sell-guitars |work=[[Prothom Alo]] |access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref> He used a [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] JCM2000 amp onstage.\n\n=== Early influences ===\n{{Quotebox|Most of all I like [[Jimi Hendrix|Hendrix]]. He did not make the guitar playing very critical note after note. He played the guitar as per his feelings. I have been trying that.|source= \u2014 ''[[Dhaka Tribune]]'', October 2018|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\nBachchu's singing style has often been found similar to [[Music of Bangladesh#Modern bangla music|Adhunik bangla]] musicians. As he was a bandmate with [[Tapan Chowdhury (singer)|Tapan Chowdhury]] in [[Souls (band)|Souls]], he had an influence from Adhunik music.<ref name=\":07\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu was a complete musician, who could do any kind of music: Tapan Chowdhury |url=https://en.prothomalo.com/entertainment/news/185156/Bachchu-was-a-complete-musician-Tapan-Chowdhury |publisher=[[Prothom Alo]] |accessdate=2019-05-16}}</ref> Indian musician Prabuddha Banerjee said that: \"I found his voice extremely romantic and I always wondered if he could sing Bengali retro numbers. In fact, though he was a rock musician, his style of singing always captured the romanticism of adhunik bangla music.<ref name=\":02\" /> Bachchu's high pitched screaming in the LRB songs \"Gotokal Raate\" and \"Khoniker Jonno\", from the band's third album ''[[Shukh (album)|Shukh]]'', has been cited similar to the high pitched vocals of [[Ian Gillan]] of [[Deep Purple]]. He was also a big fan of [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]]. Bachchu was inspired by him to write and sing rock songs in [[Bengali language|Bengali]].\n\nBachchu's lyrics are inspired by [[the Eagles]], [[Deep Purple]], [[Pink Floyd]] and [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]. He has stated that the lyrics' of the Eagles songs \"[[Witchy Woman]]\" and \"[[Hotel California (song)|Hotel California]]\" are one of his most favorite lyrics. Also, [[the Beatles]] and [[Iron Maiden]] were among his lyrics inspiration.<ref name=\":06\" />\n\n== Death ==\nIn 2009, Bachchu underwent a successful heart valve surgery and became a regular patient at the [[Square Hospital, Dhaka|Square Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Legendary Bangladeshi Rockstar Ayub Bachchu dead at 56 |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/legendary-bangladeshi-singer-ayub-bachchu-passes-away-at-56-due-to-heart-failure-1913155.html |publisher=News18 |date=2018-10-18 |accessdate=2019-05-13}}</ref> Bachchu was admitted to the Square Hospital on November 27, 2012. He was admitted  in the [[Coronary Care Unit]] (CCU) under supervision of Dr. Mirza Nizamuddin of the hospital. Bachchu was suffering from lung ailment. Due to accretion of water in his lungs, he was experiencing respiratory problems. He recovered after receiving treatment.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu hospitalised |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=259156 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2012-11-29 |accessdate=2013-01-12}}</ref> On Thursday, 18 October 2018, he died of [[cardiac failure]] at his residence in [[Maghbazar]], [[Dhaka]] at 21:55 [[Bangladesh Standard Time|BST]] at the age of 56.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bangladeshi rock legend Ayub Bachchu has died |url=https://www.anandabazar.com/bangladesh-news/bangladeshi-rock-music-legend-ayub-bachchu-died-dgtl-1.883319 |publisher=Ananda Bazaar |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref> Dr. Mirza Nizamuddin of Square Hospital's Director of Medical Services said to the ''[[Dhaka Tribune]]'', \"Ayub Bachchu suffered heart failure at his home around 9:30 am, and left for Square Hospital with his driver by car. He died on his way to the hospital. He was found dead on arrival after he reached the hospital at 9:40 am. On-duty doctors announced his death at 9:55 am.<ref name=\": 08\">{{cite news |title=In Memoriam: The artists we lost in 2018 |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2018/12/29/in-memoriam-artistes-we-lost-in-2018 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |accessdate=2019-05-17}}</ref>\" He gave his last performance in [[Rangpur City|Rangpur]], Bangladesh, two days before his death.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rock star Ayub Bachchu passes away: President, PM express deep shock |url=http://unb.com.bd/category/Entertainment/legendary-singer-ayub-bacchu-dies/4502 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |agency=UNB News |publisher=[[United News of Bangladesh]] |date=18 October 2018}}</ref> He was declared dead at the [[Square Hospital, Dhaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/legendary-bangladeshi-singer-ayub-bachchu-passes-away-at-56-due-to-heart-failure-1913155.html|title=Legendary Bangladeshi Singer Ayub Bachchu Passes Away at 56 Due to Heart Failure|publisher=News18}}</ref> He was kept in [[Shaheed Minar, Dhaka|the Central Shaheed Minar]] up to four hours in October 19, where his contemporaries and fans paid tribute to him for the last time.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite news |title=A sea of mourners in the Central Shaheed Minar |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/fans-gather-shaheed-minar-pay-tributes-ayub-bachchu-1649086 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]] |date=20 October 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Popular artist Ayub Bachchu dies at 56 after heart failure |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/ayub-bachchu-popular-bangladeshi-singer-songwriter-and-guitarist-dies-at-56-after-heart-failure-5403281.html |publisher=First Post Entertainment |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref> His first Janaza was held in the National Eidgah Field in Dhaka.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu's Janaza in Dhaka on Friday |url=https://www.jagonews24.com/en/entertainment/news/42096 |publisher=Jago News24 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Remembering Ayub Bachchu through his music |url=http://icetoday.net/2018/10/remembering-ayub-bachchu-through-his-music/ |publisher=icetoday.net |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref> His body was taken to [[Chittagong City]] on 20 October 2018 in his maternal house in East Madarbari.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2018/10/20/ayub-bachchu-laid-to-rest-in-chattogram-amid-outpouring-of-love-tribute|title=Ayub Bachchu laid to rest in Chattogram amid outpouring of love, tribute|access-date=2018-10-21}}</ref> He was taken in the Jamaitul Falah Mosque for his 4th and last [[Janaza]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Last Janaza of Ayub Bachchu held in Jamaitul Falah Mosque in Chittagong |url=http://m.dainikshiksha.com/en/last-tributes-paid-to-ayub-bachchu-1st-janaza-held/152071/ |publisher=Dainik Shiksha |date=2018-10-19 |accessdate=2019-05-14}}</ref> He was buried in the graveyard of Chaitanya Goli, beside his mother's grave.<ref name=\":05\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu laid to rest next to his mother |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/2018/10/20/ayub-bachchu-laid-to-rest-next-to-his-mother |accessdate=October 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Rock legend Ayub Bachchu passes away | url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/ayub-bachchu-passes-away-1648585 | work=The Daily Star | date=2018-10-18 |accessdate=2018-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=India grieves over Ayub Bachchu's untimely demise |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/music/india-and-bangladesh-grieve-over-ayub-bachchus-untimely-demise/articleshow/66272928.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Tribute concert ===\n\nAfter the death of Bachchu, rock and [[metal music|metal]] artists of Bangladesh held a tribute concert at the Music and Dance Auditorium of [[Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy]] on December 2, 2018, arranged by BAMBA.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu: While a Nation Gently Weeps |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/showbiz/ayub-bachchu-sudden-death-while-nation-gently-weeps-1652206 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=27 October 2018 |accessdate=10 May 2019 |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad}}</ref> Some of the notable performances included, \"Keu Shukhi Noy\" performed by [[Shafin Ahmed]], \"Rupali Guitar\" performed by [[Bappa Mazumder]], \"Nil Bedona\" by Jamshed Chowdhury ([[Powersurge (band)|Powersurge]]). Emil (Shunno) and Sufi ([[Arbovirus (band)|Arbovirus]]) together performed the song \"Bangladesh\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Tribute to Ayub Bachchu by BAMBA |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/music/tribute-to-music-legend-ayub-bachchu-bamba-farewell-1668256 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|Daily Star]] |date=3 December 2018 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nArtists from both [[West Bengal]] and Bangladesh held a tribute concert for Bachchu at the Patuli Lokosanskriti Mela Ground in Kolkata on 24 December, titled \"In the Memorium of Ayub Bachchu, the Rocking of two Bangla\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Tribute Concert in Kolkata |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2018/11/14/ayub-bachchu-tribute-concert-in-kolkata-on-nov-24 |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=14 November 2018 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=In Memorium of Ayub Bachchu |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/feature/2018/11/25/two-bengals-pay-tribute-to-ayub-bachchu-in-kolkata |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=25 November 2018 |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref> The concert was organized by Cafe Kabira, a popular cafe in Kolkata. Bangladeshi musicians included, Maqsood Haque (Maqsood 'O Dhaka), Sina Hasan (Bangla Five), George Lincoln D'Costa ([[Artcell]]), Mehreen, Subrata Barua Rony (ex-[[Souls (band)|Souls]]), Imran Hussain ([[Rockstrata]]). Bachchu's teacher Jacob Dayas was also present at the concert. The show featured Indian artists like, Pradip Chattopadhyay Bula and Bapi ([[Moheener Ghoraguli]]), Anindya (Shohor), Avijit Burman and Soumitra Roy (Bhumi), Upal (Chandrabindu), [[Shilajit Majumder]], Gaurav Chattopadhyai (Lakkhichhara), Bramhakhapa, Deb Chowdhury and Sidhu (Cactus) performed at the concert.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n10 Bangladeshi bands from [[Canada]] including, Oboshor, Band4, Tulu and the Lightman, Sector 2.0, Reflection, Chandan and Friends, Shoor, Shikor, Jantrik, TWB and Manush held a tribute concert at the [[Blessed Cardinal Newman Catholic High School|Cardinal Newman High School]] in [[Toronto]] on December 15, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ayub Bachchu goes International |url=http://news.priyo.com/entertainment/2012/01/21/ayub-bachchu-goes-internationa-45695.html |work=Priyo |date=2012-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123095605/http://news.priyo.com/entertainment/2012/01/21/ayub-bachchu-goes-internationa-45695.html |archive-date=2012-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{quote box|quote=\"The trend in Bangladeshi music that Azam Khan initiated was taken to a new height by Ayub Bachchu. His death is an irreparable loss for Bangladeshi music.\"|source = \u2013 [[Fakir Alamgir]]<ref name=\":10\" />|width=27%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}\n\nBachchu is widely regarded as one of the greatest and most influential guitarist of Bangladesh. He ranked second on ''The Top Tens'' list of \"Top 10 Greatest Guitarist of Bangladesh\". [[Ibrahim Ahmed Kamal]] who ranked first in the list has said that, \"The ranking is not correct, it was created to abuse the Great Ayub Bachchu\". He is also credited for popularizing [[rock music]] in Bangladesh in the 1990s as the frontman of [[Love Runs Blind|LRB]] and as a solo artist, along with Nagar Baul, [[Miles (band)|Miles]] and [[Ark (Bangladeshi band)|Ark]].<ref name=\":07\" /> He is also considered to be one of the \"big three rockstars of Bangladesh\" along with [[Azam Khan (singer)|Azam Khan]] and [[James (musician)|James]].{{sfn|Kimmerman|2009|p=26}} He is also considered to be the first electric guitarist in Bangladesh to use [[Distortion|distortion]] in songs. About that he said to Ekattor TV: \"I was being forced to leave [[Souls (band)|Souls]], because I wanted to play distorted guitar\".\n\nGuitarist who were influenced by him includes, Ibrahim Ahmed Kamal ([[Warfaze]]), [[Iqbal Asif Jewel]] ([[Miles (band)|Miles]], Legend, Warfaze), Ershad Zaman ([[Artcell]]), George Lincoln D' Costa (Artcell), Kazi Faisal Mahmud (Metal Maze, Artcell), Oni Hasan (Vibe, Warfaze), Emon Chowdhury ([[Chirkut]]), Samir Hafiz ([[Powersurge (band)|Powersurge]], [[Severe Dementia]], [[Raef al Hasan Rafa|AvoidRafa]]).\n\nEx-Minister of Cultural Affairs, [[Asaduzzaman Noor]] said, \"the fact that people from all walk of life were affected by the departure of Ayub Bachchu is testament to his greatness as an artist. I was fortunate enough to have personally known him since his starting days. He was an immensely passionate person.\" [[Hamin Ahmed]] of [[Miles (band)|Miles]] said, \"when Ayub Bachchu started his career, the guitar wasn't as prominent as an instrument. He made sure that it was the heart and soul of his music, and the entire country followed. That alone is enough to explain his legacy.\" [[Bappa Mazumder]] of [[Dalchhut]] said, \"The great man not only taught us about music, but taught us how to be a great human. I always admired how much he loved his mother, and requested other people to take care of their parents.\" Indian singer-songwriter [[Sahana Bajpaie]] said to ''[[Daily Sun (Bangladesh)|Daily Sun]]'': \"I was 12 when I first realised there is a Bengali musician who plays the guitar like Jimi Hendrix. He was one of the pioneers of Bengali rock music. My teenage was inspired by his music. He became a family friend when I was in Bangladesh. His simplicity was outstanding. His contributions to music will be remembered by generations to come.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{cite news |title=India music world mourns over the untimely demise of legendary Bangla rock singer Ayub Bachchu |url=https://www.daily-sun.com/post/344059/2018/10/18/India-music-world-mourns-for-Ayub-Bachchu%E2%80%99s-premature-death |work=[[Daily Sun (Bangladesh)|Daily Sun]] |date=2018-10-18 |accessdate=2019-05-12 |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad}}</ref>\n\nIn 19 December 2018 [[Asif Akbar]] has released a song for Ayub Bachchu, with the title \"A Tribute to the Great Legend Ayub Bachchu\" from Dhruba Music Station.<ref name=\"A Tribute\">{{cite news |title=Asif Akbar releases new song for Ayub Bachchu |url=http://www.observerbd.com/details.php?id=173857 |work=The Daily Observer |date=19 December 2018 |access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rupali Guitar (01).jpg|thumb|The Rupali Guitar in [[Chittagong|Probortok Circle, Chittagong]]]]\n\nOn 20 October 2018, the mayor of [[Chittagong City Corporation]], [[A J M Nasir Uddin]] proposed that an \"important road in the port city Chittagong be named after him and a seminar hall in Muslim Hall be named after him.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=An important road in the port city chittagong would be named after Ayub Bachchu: CCC Mayor |url=https://m.daily-bangladesh.com/english/A-port-city-road-to-be-named-after-Ayub-Bachchu-CCC-Mayor/12426 |work=The Daily Bangladesh |date=2018-10-20 |accessdate=2019-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mahid |last=Ul Ibad |title=Chittagong City Corporation to name road after Ayub Bachchu |url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/showtime/2018/10/20/chittagong-road-to-be-named-after-ayub-bachchu |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=2018-10-20 |accessdate=2019-05-04}}</ref> Chattogram City Corporation Mayor AJM Nasir Uddin unveiled the sculpture of the guitar at the Probortok intersection in Chattogram. The sculpture of the 18-feet tall guitar is made of steel and has six strings.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ashfaque |last=Nipun |title=THE RUPALI GUITAR strikes a chord |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/arts-entertainment/news/the-rupali-guitar-strikes-chord-1801960 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=19 September 2019 |accessdate=12 October 2019 |}}</ref>\n\n=== Achievements ===\n16th '''[[Tele Cine Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2017 || Ayub Bachchu || Lifetime Achievement Award<ref>{{cite news |author=Mahid Ul Ibad |title=Six Bangladeshi artists win the Tele Cine Awards |url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/17103/bangladeshi-film-artistes-win-awards-in-kolkata |work=New Age |accessdate=15 March 2019 |date=2017-06-05}}</ref>|| {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n32nd '''[[Bachsas Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2004 || Ayub Bachchu || Best Male Vocal<ref name=\"32nd BACHSAS\">{{cite news |author1=Afsar Ahmed |title=32nd BACHSAS Awards: A glitzy night Recognition of outstanding media talents |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2004/06/28/d406281402119.htm |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]] |date=28 June 2004}}</ref> || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n'''[[Meril Prothom Alo Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 1998 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1999 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2000 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|- \n| 2001 || ''Mon Chaile Mon Pabe {{small|(You'll Get My Heart if You Want it)}}'' || Album of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2005 || Love Runs Blind || Best Band of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Sporsho {{small|(Touch)}}'' || Album of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2009 || \"Bolini Tomai {{small|(Didn't Tell You)}}\" || Best Male Vocal of the Year || {{nominated}}\n{{end}}\n\n'''[[Channel i Music Awards|Citycell-Channel I Music Awards]]'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Sporsho {{small|(Touch)}}'' || Album of the Year || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{See also|Love Runs Blind discography}}\n\n=== Solo albums ===\n* ''[[Rokto Golap]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Moyna (album)|Moyna]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Koshto (album)|Koshto]]'' (1995)\n* ''Shomoy'' (1999)\n* ''Eka'' (1999)\n* ''Prem Tumi Ki'' (2000)\n* ''Duti Mon'' (2002)\n* ''Kafela'' (2002)\n* ''Prem Premer Moto'' (2003)\n* ''Pother Gaan'' (2004)\n* ''Vatir Gaane Matir Tane'' (2006)\n* ''Jibon'' (2006)\n* ''Sound of Silence'' (2007)\n* ''Rim Jhim Brishti'' (2008)\n* ''Bolini Kokhono'' (2009)\n* ''Jiboner Golpo'' (2015)\n\n=== Souls ===\n{{Main|Souls (band)#discography}}\n* ''Super Souls'' (1982)\n* ''College Er Corridore'' (1985)\n* ''Manush Matir Kachakachi'' (1987)\n* ''East and West'' (1988)\n\n=== Film scores ===\nBelow is the list of films where Bachchu produced the original soundtrack.\n* ''Luttoraj'' (1996)\n* ''Sagorika'' (1998)\n* ''Lal Badshah'' (1999)\n* ''[[Ammajan]]'' (1999)\n* ''Gunda Number 1'' (2000)\n* ''[[Bachelor (2004 film)|Bachelor]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Wrong Number (2004 film)|Wrong Number]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Chander Moto Bou]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Chorabali]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Television (2012 film)|Television]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Ek Cup Cha]]'' (2014)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-221089|title=Playback time|date=2012-02-04|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |script-title=bn:\u2018\u0986\u0987\u09af\u09bc\u09c1\u09ac \u09ac\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09c1 \u098f\u0995\u099f\u09be \u09b8\u09ac\u09c1\u099c \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0997\u09be\u09a8 |url=https://www.dw.com/bn/\u0986\u0987\u09af\u09bc\u09c1\u09ac-\u09ac\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09c1-\u098f\u0995\u099f\u09be-\u09b8\u09ac\u09c1\u099c-\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be-\u0997\u09be\u09a8/a-45935069 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=2018-10-18 |language=bn |access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Love Runs Blind]]\n* [[Shei Tumi|\u099a\u09b2\u09cb \u09ac\u09a6\u09b2\u09c7 \u09af\u09be\u09af\u09bc (Let's Change)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n====Bibliography====\n* {{citebook |title=Where Am I Wearing? A Global Tour to the Countries, Factories and People That Make Our Clothes |first=Kelsey |last=Kimmerman |year=2009 |isbn=9781118277553|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |b=no |c=Category:Ayub Bachchu |d=Q4831762 |m=no |mw=no |n=no |q=Ayub Bachchu |s=no |species=no |v=no |voy=no |wikt=no}}\n* [http://www.ablrb.net Official Website]\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/6471404 Ayub Bachchu] discography on [[Discogs]]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4620075/ Ayub Bachchu] on [[IMDb]]\n* [https://www.last.fm/music/AYUB%2BBACHCHU Ayub Bachchu] on [[Last.fm]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bachchu, Ayub}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male musicians]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi rock singers]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male singers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi socialists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bangladeshi singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bangladeshi singers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi playback singers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi record producers]]\n[[Category:People from Chittagong]]\n[[Category:Government Muslim High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Bachsas Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Bengali musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Boogey Humphrey", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAchievements)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayub_Bachchu"}
{"title_page": "List of Coronation Street characters (2006)", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Coronation Street'' characters (2006)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2016}}\nThe following is a list of minor characters that first appeared in the [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Coronation Street]]'' in 2006, by order of first appearance.\n\n==Aadi Alahan==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Aadi Alahan|\n|years=2006, 2009\u2013\n|first=13 January 2006\n|born=13 January 2006\n|portrayer= Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed (2006)<br/>Zennon Ditchett (2009\u2013)\n|classification= [[List of Coronation Street characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n|home = 7 Coronation Street\n|occupation = Student\n|father = [[Dev Alahan]]\n| mother = [[Sunita Alahan]]\n| sisters = [[#Asha Alahan|Asha Alahan]]\n| halfsisters = [[Amber Kalirai]]<br>Shareen\n| relatives= [[Grishma Parekh]]<br/>[[Upma Parekh]]\n}}\n'''Aadi Alahan''' played by triplets Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed in 2006<ref name=\"Corrie twins are really triplets\">{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/tv-exclusive-corrie-twins-are-reallytriplets-576572|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|title=TV EXCLUSIVE: CORRIE TWINS ARE REALLY..TRIPLETS|date=2 February 2006|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> and Zennon Ditchett since 2009, is one of the twins born to [[Sunita Alahan|Sunita]] ([[Shobna Gulati]]) and [[Dev Alahan]] ([[Jimmi Harkishin]]) on 13 January 2006. He leaves with his mother and sister [[#Asha Alahan|Asha]] (Tanisha Gorey) soon after he is born. In December 2009, Aadi returns to the Street with Sunita and Asha.\n\nAadi moves into Dev's flat in March 2010, after Dev and Sunita reconcile. Aadi and Asha think that it would be funny if Aadi goes onto the balcony of Flat 6, Victoria Court. Sunita tries to get him inside but the door jams. Dev tries and breaks the door handle. After many attempts to open the balcony door, they fail but [[Graeme Proctor]] ([[Craig Gazey]]) is riding by and rescues Aadi just as Sunita is going to call 999.\n\nIn August 2010, Aadi is pushed by [[Simon Barlow]] ([[Alex Bain (actor)|Alex Bain]]) and bangs his head as they play a game, while [[Sophie Webster]] ([[Brooke Vincent]]) and her girlfriend [[Sian Powers]] ([[Sacha Parkinson]]) are babysitting. He is later rushed to hospital after he loses consciousness. When the doctors find another bruise on Aadi (as a result of Dev pulling him off the road when a car nearly ran him over), social services are contacted. They suspect Aadi's injuries are not accidental and take Aadi and Asha into care but they are allowed to go home after Simon admits that he hurt Aadi.\n\nIn September 2011, it becomes clear to Dev that Aadi is a talented golfer. He persuades Sunita to allow him to nurture Aadi's talent although Sunita is unsure as Dev's golf is already becoming very expensive. Sunita finally agrees on the condition that, if Dev is happy to spend money on Aadi and his golf, he needs to be willing to splurge an equal amount on Asha.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Asha Alahan==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Asha Alahan\n|years=2006, 2009\u2013\n|first=13 January 2006\n|born= 13 January 2006\n|classification= [[List of Coronation Street characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n|portrayer= Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed (2006)<br/>Tanisha Gorey (2009\u2013)\n|home = 7 Coronation Street\n|occupation = Student\n|father = [[Dev Alahan]]\n| mother = [[Sunita Alahan]]\n| brothers = [[#Aadi Alahan|Aadi Alahan]]\n| halfsisters = [[Amber Kalirai]]<br>Shareen\n| relatives=[[Grishma Parekh]]<br/>[[Upma Parekh]]\n}}\n'''Asha Alahan''' played by triplets Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed in 2006<ref name=\"Corrie twins are really triplets\"/> and Tanisha Gorey since 2009, is one of the twins born to [[Sunita Alahan|Sunita]] ([[Shobna Gulati]]) and [[Dev Alahan]] ([[Jimmi Harkishin]]) in January 2006. She leaves with Sunita and her twin brother [[#Aadi Alahan|Aadi Alahan]] (Zennon Ditchett) soon after she is born. Asha returns to the Street in December 2009 with Sunita and Aadi. Upon Asha's return, Sunita thinks that she may have measles, after having spots and a temperature. [[List of minor Coronation Street characters (2004)#Dr Patel|Dr Patel]] (Josephine Lloyd-Welcome), from the medical centre visits her home and, much to the relief of a worried Dev and Sunita, she is not suffering from measles, just a virus.\n\nIn September 2010, Asha is taken into temporary care, along with Aadi, when social services believe that Dev and Sunita may be abusing Aadi. She is soon returned to Dev and Sunita when it becomes clear that Dev and Sunita are innocent.\n\nIn July 2012, Dev and Sunita separate after Sunita has an affair with [[Karl Munro]] ([[John Michie]]) and chooses to be with him. Aadi and Asha meet Karl and he promises both Aadi and Asha that he won't get in the way of seeing Dev. Aadi and Asha later see Dev attacking Karl when Dev confronts him and Sunita.\n\nIn September 2019, Asha begins bleach her skin in an attempt to lighten her skin tone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/coronation-street/a29309824/coronation-street-spoilers-asha-alahan-seeks-help/|title=Coronation Street's Asha Alahan sees a doctor next week|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=2019-09-30|website=[[Digital Spy]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> Dev discovers that she used his credit card to buy illegal skin lightening cream, and insists on taking her to a doctor. She has also been self-harming, finding out by her father asking to see her arm.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Becky McDonald==\n{{Main|Becky McDonald}}\n\n==Jo==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Jo|\nfirst=6 February 2006|\nlast=12 February 2006|\n| classification  = [[List of past Coronation Street characters#J|Former; guest]]\n| portrayer= Emma Pike\n}}\n'''Jo''' is a character whom [[David Platt (Coronation Street)|David Platt]] ([[Jack P. Shepherd]]) gets chatting to when she moves into the flat above the bookies. She then offers David a part-time job with flexible hours and good money, which he accepts. David tells his mother [[Gail McIntyre|Gail]] ([[Helen Worth]]) that he is walking Jo's dog for her. Meanwhile, David tells [[Craig Harris (Coronation Street)|Craig Harris]] ([[Richard Fleeshman]]) that dog walking is only part of his job for Jo. He shows Craig the cannabis farm which Jo has installed in her flat and pays him to look after.\n\nThe police later raid Jo's flat and discover the drugs. David is arrested but is later released when he insists that he knew nothing about the drugs. Jo disappears and is never seen again.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Michelle Connor==\n{{Main|Michelle Connor}}\n\n==DS Phil Campbell==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n| name = DS Phil Campbell\n| first = 9 June 2006\n| last = 28 April 2008\n| years = 2006\u20132008\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation = [[Police Officer]]\n| portrayer  = Gary Cargill\n| born =\n}}\n'''Detective Sergeant Phil Campbell''' is a police officer. Campbell is first seen investigating a hit-and-run accident in which an elderly man was killed. He arrests [[Steve McDonald (Coronation Street)|Steve McDonald]] ([[Simon Gregson]]) for causing death by dangerous driving and Steve implicates his girlfriend [[Ronnie Clayton (Coronation Street)|Ronnie Clayton]] ([[Emma Stansfield]]) who is the actual culprit and is subsequently arrested. The following month, Campbell questions [[Danny Baldwin]] ([[Bradley Walsh]]) on suspicion of fraud after it is revealed he had forged a will in order to get his father [[Mike Baldwin (Coronation Street)|Mike]] ([[Johnny Briggs (actor)|Johnny Briggs]]), who suffered from Alzheimers disease, to leave him his factory. In January 2007, Campbell arrests [[Tracy Barlow]] ([[Kate Ford]]) and charges her with assaulting [[Charlie Stubbs (Coronation Street)|Charlie Stubbs]] ([[Bill Ward (actor)|Bill Ward]]). After Charlie dies of his injuries, Campbell charges Tracy with murder. Campbell questions Tracy's neighbours [[Claire Peacock]] ([[Julia Haworth]]) and [[Gail McIntyre|Gail Platt]] ([[Helen Worth]]) both of whom claim Charlie was subjecting Tracy to domestic violence and abuse. Campbell also questions Charlie's friend [[Jason Grimshaw]] ([[Ryan Thomas]]) who tells them that Tracy staged a deliberate row in order to get the police involved. [[David Platt (Coronation Street)|David Platt]] ([[Jack P. Shepherd]]) later visits the police station and tells Campbell that he witnessed Tracy kill Charlie in self-defence after he had attacked her with a knife. David also tells Campbell that Charlie had attempted to abduct him in his van and had also attempted to drown him in his bathtub. Campbell later speaks to [[Liam Connor]] ([[Rob James-Collier]]) who witnessed the abduction attempt and [[Maria Connor|Maria Sutherland]] ([[Samia Ghadie]]) who witnessed the attempted drowning and they both back David's story up. Campbell was last seen investigating the arson attack at [[Leanne Battersby]]'s ([[Jane Danson]]) restaurant \"Valandros\" committed by chef [[Paul Clayton (Coronation Street)|Paul Clayton]] ([[Tom Hudson (English actor)|Tom Hudson]]). After Paul reports himself and Leanne to the police, Campbell arrests Leanne and questions her but her boyfriend [[Dan Mason]] ([[Matthew Crompton]]) gives her an alibi.\n\nIn October 2004, Cargill played a police officer called DC Paul Campbell, who arrested [[Dev Alahan|Dev]] ([[Jimmi Harkishin]]) and [[Sunita Alahan]] ([[Shobna Gulati]]) on their wedding day on suspicion of being illegal immigrants and falsely marrying to gain a visa. It is not known whether this was the same character under a different name. \n{{Clear}}\n\n==Brian Tully==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Brian Tully|\nfirst=5 June 2006|\nlast=18 June 2006|\n|classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; guest]]\n|portrayer=[[Tim Healy (actor)|Tim Healy]]|\n|wife=[[Maureen Tully]] (1975\u20132005)|\n|daughters=Angela Tully\n|stepsons =[[Sean Tully]]\n}}\n'''Brian Tully''' thinks that [[Sean Tully]] ([[Antony Cotton]]) is his son but left when he realized that he isn't. In 2006, Sean begins visiting his father until he learns the truth.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Maureen Tully==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Maureen Tully|\nfirst=26 June 2006|\nlast=28 June 2006|\nportrayer=[[Susan Brown (English actress)|Susan Brown]]|\nhusband=[[Brian Tully]] (1975\u20132005)|\nsons=[[Sean Tully]]|\ndaughters=Angela Tully|\nsisters=Angie|\ngrandsons=[[Dylan Wilson]]|\nclassification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; guest]]\n}}\n'''Maureen Tully''' is [[Sean Tully]]'s ([[Antony Cotton]]) mother. She lies to her son saying that [[Brian Tully]] ([[Tim Healy (actor)|Tim Healy]]) is his real father, Sean's real father is unknown, but she then tells him it was a plumber named Paul Jones that she had met at a dance.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Freddie Peacock==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Freddie Peacock\n|introducer=[[Steve November|Steve Frost]]\n|first=17 July 2006\n|last=14 January 2011\n|years=2006\u20132011\n|classification=[[List of past Coronation Street characters#C|Former; recurring]]\n|born=17 July 2006\n|home=France\n|father=[[Ashley Peacock]]\n|mother=[[Claire Peacock]]\n|brothers= [[Joshua Peacock]] (adoptive)\n|grandfathers =[[Fred Elliott]]\n|grandmothers = [[Yvonne Casey]]<br>[[Kathleen Gutteridge]]<br>[[Beryl Peacock]] (adoptive)\n|relatives = [[Beryl Peacock]]\n|portrayer=Jack & Jake Rogers (2006)<br>Dylan & Hayden Whitbread (2006\u20132009)<br>Lewis & Niall Beresford (2009\u20132011)\n| alias = Thomas Peacock\n|\n}}\n\n'''Frederick Thomas \"Freddie\" Peacock''' (also '''Thomas Duncan Peacock''') is the son of [[Ashley Peacock|Ashley]] ([[Steven Arnold]]) and [[Claire Peacock]] ([[Julia Haworth]]). On Christmas Day 2005, Claire tells Ashley that she is two months pregnant, and months later, Freddie is born on 17 July 2006. Claire suffers from [[post natal depression]] after Freddie is born, refusing to believe that Freddie is her child. On one occasion, she pushes his pram into the path of an oncoming vehicle and tries to return him to the hospital. She is sectioned until she is well enough to come home.\n\nIn October 2006, Claire announces that she would like to change his name from Thomas to Freddie, after his paternal grandfather [[Fred Elliott]] ([[John Savident]]) who died the week before. In December 2006, he is christened Frederick Thomas with [[Eileen Grimshaw]] ([[Sue Cleaver]]) as godmother and [[Roy Cropper]] ([[David Neilson]]) as his godfather.\n\nIn May 2007, a fire starts in Freddie's bedroom. Claire is rescued from the burning building but Freddie is not found until later that day, wrapped up in a local park. It is revealed that the fire was started deliberately by use of an accelerant. Originally, this storyline was to last several months but was rewritten to avoid upsetting the family of [[Madeleine McCann]], who disappeared two weeks previously. In September 2007, the identity of Freddie's abductor is revealed to be Claire's former friend, [[Casey Carswell]] ([[Zoe Henry]]). Casey abducts Freddie and takes him to the balcony of her flat where she threatens to jump with him. Freddie is rescued unharmed and Casey is arrested.\n\nWhen a tram crashes on to the Street on 6 December 2010, Ashley is killed when the roof of 'The Joinery' Bar collapses and he is crushed by the debris. Freddie and Joshua are subsequently left without a father. In January 2011, Claire attacks [[Tracy Barlow]] ([[Kate Ford]]) after she makes insulting remarks about Ashley and after [[Becky McDonald]] ([[Katherine Kelly (actress)|Katherine Kelly]]) is arrested for assaulting Tracy and leaving her for dead, she confesses to the police. Her friends persuade her to leave the country to avoid a prison sentence and take her sons with her. Freddie, Claire and Joshua leave for France on 14 January 2011.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Mr. Griffin==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Mr. Griffin\n|portrayer=Roger Morlidge\n|introducer=[[Steve Frost]] (2006)<br> Kim Crowther (2009) <br> [[Kate Oates]] (2016)\n|years = 2006\u20132007, 2009, 2016\n|first = 18 June 2006\n|last = \n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n|occupation=Headmaster\n}}\n'''Mr. Griffin''' is the Headmaster at Weatherfield High and commonly appears in storylines concerning [[David Platt (Coronation Street)|David Platt]] ([[Jack P. Shepherd]]) when he attends the school, and more recently [[Chesney Brown]] ([[Sam Aston]]). Mr. Griffin made his most recent appearance when Chesney's sister [[Fiz Brown]] ([[Jennie McAlpine]]) was about to punch [[Kenzie Judd]] (Jack Cooper) for bullying him. Mr. Griffin makes another appearance in September 2016 at a meeting to deal with [[List of Coronation Street characters (2016)#Lauren|Lauren]] ([[Shannon Flynn]])  for bullying [[Bethany Platt]] ([[Lucy Fallon]]) .<ref name=\"DavidgetsrevengeonbullyLauren\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-08-30/coronation-street-david-gets-revenge-on-bully-lauren---by-hacking-at-her-hair-with-the-shears|title=Coronation Street: David gets revenge on bully Lauren - by hacking at her hair with the shears!|last=MacCarthy|first=Kate|date=30 August 2016|work=[[Radio Times]]|publisher=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Cameron McIntyre==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Cameron McIntyre\n|portrayer=Ryan Cook\n|duration=2006\n|first = 24 July 2006\n|last = 7 August 2006\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n|occupation=Student\n}}\n'''Cameron McIntyre''' is a school friend of [[Chesney Brown]] ([[Sam Aston]]) and [[Sophie Webster]] ([[Brooke Vincent]]), often causing trouble.\n\nWhen he first appears, Sophie doesn't really like him. Later that day, the trio prank-call all the contacts on Sophie's mother's [[Sally Webster|Sally]]'s ([[Sally Dynevor]]) phone, and Sophie begins to develop a crush on him. On Chesney's 12th birthday party, Sophie is quietly upset that Cameron can't attend. However, to Sophie's relief, he turns up later on with a card for Chesney, and they go out again. Later on, Sophie, Chesney and Cameron hang out at Sophie's house to watch Chesney's step-dad's horror film. The film is found by Sally who orders the trio outside to play, annoying Chesney's mother [[Cilla Battersby-Brown|Cilla]] ([[Wendi Peters]]). In the ginnel later that week, Sophie and Chesney meet up with Cameron again and soon find out he has cigarettes in hand. Chesney refuses to smoke, but Sophie takes a cigarette but unfortunately, Sally smells tobacco and sends Chesney away as he hides the cigarettes. Cameron and Chesney briefly fall out, but become friends again and go to watch films with Sophie. The trio are caught again by Sally and Chesney is sent packing. When Sally discovers \u00a35 is missing from her money, she assumes Chesney stole it. Sophie is the one who took the money to buy cigarettes for her and Cameron, and when Sophie tells Cameron that she is going to tell her mother what happened, he makes an excuse to go home to avoid getting into trouble and runs away from the street, leaving Sophie devastated.\n\nCameron is no relation to [[Joe McIntyre (Coronation Street)|Joe]] ([[Reece Dinsdale]]) and [[Tina McIntyre]] ([[Michelle Keegan]]).\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Liam Connor==\n{{Main|Liam Connor}}\n\n==Ryan Connor==\n{{Main|Ryan Connor}}\n\n==Paul Connor==\n{{Main|Paul Connor (Coronation Street)}}\n\n==Carla Connor==\n{{Main|Carla Connor}}\n\n==Slug==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Coronation Street\n| name = Slug\n| portrayer = [[Marshall Lancaster]]\n| introducer = [[Steve November|Steve Frost]]\n| first = 18 December 2006\n| last = 7 September 2009\n| years = 2006\u20132007, 2009\n| born = 1977\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation = Drug dealer\n}}\n'''Slug''' (real name '''Neil Ackroyd''') is an old friend of [[Becky Granger]]'s ([[Katherine Kelly (actress)|Katherine Kelly]]), who first appears in December 2006. He is a drug dealer and user who takes advantage of Becky. In June 2009 Slug returns, apparently a reformed man. It is later revealed that he is working for DC Hooch, a police officer who is an enemy of Becky's and wants her in prison. Slug plants drugs on Becky and she is subsequently arrested. Becky's fianc\u00e9 [[Steve McDonald (Coronation Street)|Steve McDonald]] ([[Simon Gregson]]) and his colleague and friend [[Lloyd Mullaney]] ([[Craig Charles]]) find out about Slug's involvement and track him down. They bundle him into a car, drive him back to the street and question him. When they bring him to Hooch, Hooch decides to drop the charges, scared Slug will tell the police about him.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sonny Dhillon==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n| name = Sonny Dhillon\n| first = 22 December 2006\n| last = 11 March 2007\n| portrayer  = [[Pal Aron]]\n| romances = [[Michelle Connor]] (2006-2007)\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n}}\n'''Sundeep \"Sonny\" Dhillon''' is  played by [[Pal Aron]]. Sonny is [[Michelle Connor]]'s ([[Kym Marsh]]) millionaire boyfriend. It comes to light that Sonny has relationship history with [[Sean Tully]] ([[Antony Cotton]]), in that they had previously been dating, with Sonny admitting to being [[bisexual]]. On the Streetcars lads' night out [[Steve McDonald (Coronation Street)|Steve McDonald]] ([[Simon Gregson]]) spots Sean and Sonny kissing. In late February 2007, Sonny proposes to Michelle. While she is in The Rovers celebrating, a jealous Steve tells her that Sonny is gay, however, she does not believe him. When Michelle's brother [[Liam Connor]] ([[Rob James-Collier]]) hears Steve's allegation, he confronts him, with Steve sticking by what he saw. An unsure Liam questions Sean at work with Sean claiming nothing is going on. The same day, Liam and his brother [[Paul Connor (Coronation Street)|Paul]] ([[Sean Gallagher (actor)|Sean Gallagher]]) confront Sean a second time, forcing him to tell the truth. They then frogmarch Sean to the pub to tell Michelle the truth. Sean does so, with Michelle bursting into tears, shocked at what she is hearing. An oblivious Sonny arrives at Michelle's that night, ready to take her out. A crying Michelle tells Sonny she knows about him and Sean, before giving him back her engagement ring. Sonny then leaves in shame.\n\nWhen Michelle's son [[Ryan Connor]] ([[Ben Thompson (actor)|Ben Thompson]]) discovers the gay affair, he steals Sonny's car and takes it for a [[Joyride (crime)|joyride]]. The police find out but Sonny doesn't press charges. After Michelle discovers the affair, Sonny goes to Sean but Sean rejected him. Sonny walks out of number 11 and hasn't been seen since.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Holly Grimshaw==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n| name = Holly Grimshaw \n| first = 25 December 2006\n| last = 25 April 2007\n| years = 2006&ndash;2007\n|introducer = [[Steve Frost]]\n|classification = [[List of past Coronation Street characters#G|Former; recurring]]\n| portrayer  = Amelia Caudwell<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macclesfield-live.co.uk/news/local-news/swapping-craig-road-for-corrie-2535100|title=Swapping Craig Road for Corrie|date=2007-03-28|work=Macclesfield Express}}</ref>\n| born = August 2006\n| mother = Emma\n| father = [[Charlie Stubbs (Coronation Street)|Charlie Stubbs]]\n| alias = Chloe\n}}\n\n'''Holly Grimshaw''' (real name '''Chloe''') first appears on Christmas Day 2006 when her mother Emma ([[Stephanie Waring]]) dumps her on [[Jason Grimshaw]] ([[Ryan Thomas]]) claiming that he is her father, following a one-night stand. Jason's mother [[Eileen Grimshaw|Eileen]] ([[Sue Cleaver]]) bonds with her new granddaughter, who they name Holly because of the day she arrived. Jason bonds with her too and enjoys being a father and a family with his fianc\u00e9e [[Sarah Platt]] ([[Tina O'Brien]]) and her daughter,  [[Bethany Platt|Bethany]].\n\nWhen [[Charlie Stubbs (Coronation Street)|Charlie Stubbs]] ([[Bill Ward (actor)|Bill Ward]]) is murdered in January 2007, Jason is upset as Charlie was one of his closest friends. However, [[Tracy Barlow]] ([[Kate Ford]])'s trial is in the newspaper. Holly's mother, Emma, reads about it and realises that Charlie is Holly's father, not Jason. She returns for her daughter but Eileen initially refuses to give her back. She threatens to go for legal custody but is persuaded to return her on 25 April 2007 {{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coronation Street characters}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Coronation Street characters|2006]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2006|*, Coronation Street]]\n[[Category:2006 in British television|Coronation Street]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Coronation Street'' characters (2006)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2016}}\nThe following is a list of minor characters that first appeared in the [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Coronation Street]]'' in 2006, by order of first appearance.\n\n==Aadi Alahan==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Aadi Alahan|\n|years=2006, 2009\u2013\n|first=13 January 2006\n|born=13 January 2006\n|portrayer= Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed (2006)<br/>Zennon Ditchett (2009\u2013)\n|classification= [[List of Coronation Street characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n|home = 7 Coronation Street\n|occupation = Student\n|father = [[Dev Alahan]]\n| mother = [[Sunita Alahan]]\n| sisters = [[#Asha Alahan|Asha Alahan]]\n| halfsisters = [[Amber Kalirai]]<br>Shareen\n| relatives= [[Grishma Parekh]]<br/>[[Upma Parekh]]\n}}\n'''Aadi Alahan''' played by triplets Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed in 2006<ref name=\"Corrie twins are really triplets\">{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/tv-exclusive-corrie-twins-are-reallytriplets-576572|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|title=TV EXCLUSIVE: CORRIE TWINS ARE REALLY..TRIPLETS|date=2 February 2006|accessdate=6 February 2017}}</ref> and Zennon Ditchett since 2009, is one of the twins born to [[Sunita Alahan|Sunita]] ([[Shobna Gulati]]) and [[Dev Alahan]] ([[Jimmi Harkishin]]) on 13 January 2006. He leaves with his mother and sister [[#Asha Alahan|Asha]] (Tanisha Gorey) soon after he is born. In December 2009, Aadi returns to the Street with Sunita and Asha.\n\nAadi moves into Dev's flat in March 2010, after Dev and Sunita reconcile. Aadi and Asha think that it would be funny if Aadi goes onto the balcony of Flat 6, Victoria Court. Sunita tries to get him inside but the door jams. Dev tries and breaks the door handle. After many attempts to open the balcony door, they fail but [[Graeme Proctor]] ([[Craig Gazey]]) is riding by and rescues Aadi just as Sunita is going to call 999.\n\nIn August 2010, Aadi is pushed by [[Simon Barlow]] ([[Alex Bain (actor)|Alex Bain]]) and bangs his head as they play a game, while [[Sophie Webster]] ([[Brooke Vincent]]) and her girlfriend [[Sian Powers]] ([[Sacha Parkinson]]) are babysitting. He is later rushed to hospital after he loses consciousness. When the doctors find another bruise on Aadi (as a result of Dev pulling him off the road when a car nearly ran him over), social services are contacted. They suspect Aadi's injuries are not accidental and take Aadi and Asha into care but they are allowed to go home after Simon admits that he hurt Aadi.\n\nIn September 2011, it becomes clear to Dev that Aadi is a talented golfer. He persuades Sunita to allow him to nurture Aadi's talent although Sunita is unsure as Dev's golf is already becoming very expensive. Sunita finally agrees on the condition that, if Dev is happy to spend money on Aadi and his golf, he needs to be willing to splurge an equal amount on Asha.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Asha Alahan==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Asha Alahan\n|years=2006, 2009\u2013\n|first=13 January 2006\n|born= 13 January 2006\n|classification= [[List of Coronation Street characters#Regular characters|Present; regular]]\n|portrayer= Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed (2006)<br/>Tanisha Gorey (2009\u2013)\n|home = 7 Coronation Street\n|occupation = Student\n|father = [[Dev Alahan]]\n| mother = [[Sunita Alahan]]\n| brothers = [[#Aadi Alahan|Aadi Alahan]]\n| halfsisters = [[Amber Kalirai]]<br>Shareen\n| relatives=[[Grishma Parekh]]<br/>[[Upma Parekh]]\n}}\n'''Asha Alahan''' played by triplets Hannah, Harris & Ria Ahmed in 2006<ref name=\"Corrie twins are really triplets\"/> and Tanisha Gorey since 2009, is one of the twins born to [[Sunita Alahan|Sunita]] ([[Shobna Gulati]]) and [[Dev Alahan]] ([[Jimmi Harkishin]]) in January 2006. She leaves with Sunita and her twin brother [[#Aadi Alahan|Aadi Alahan]] (Zennon Ditchett) soon after she is born. Asha returns to the Street in December 2009 with Sunita and Aadi. Upon Asha's return, Sunita thinks that she may have measles, after having spots and a temperature. [[List of minor Coronation Street characters (2004)#Dr Patel|Dr Patel]] (Josephine Lloyd-Welcome), from the medical centre visits her home and, much to the relief of a worried Dev and Sunita, she is not suffering from measles, just a virus.\n\nIn September 2010, Asha is taken into temporary care, along with Aadi, when social services believe that Dev and Sunita may be abusing Aadi. She is soon returned to Dev and Sunita when it becomes clear that Dev and Sunita are innocent.\n\nIn July 2012, Dev and Sunita separate after Sunita has an affair with [[Karl Munro]] ([[John Michie]]) and chooses to be with him. Aadi and Asha meet Karl and he promises both Aadi and Asha that he won't get in the way of seeing Dev. Aadi and Asha later see Dev attacking Karl when Dev confronts him and Sunita.\n\nIn September 2019, Asha begins bleach her skin in an attempt to lighten her skin tone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/coronation-street/a29309824/coronation-street-spoilers-asha-alahan-seeks-help/|title=Coronation Street's Asha Alahan sees a doctor next week|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=2019-09-30|website=[[Digital Spy]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> Dev discovers that she used his credit card to buy illegal skin lightening cream, and insists on taking her to a doctor. She has also been self-harming, finding out by her father asking to see her arm.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Becky McDonald==\n{{Main|Becky McDonald}}\n\n==Jo==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Jo|\nfirst=6 February 2006|\nlast=12 February 2006|\n| classification  = [[List of past Coronation Street characters#J|Former; guest]]\n| portrayer= Emma Pike\n}}\n'''Jo''' is a character whom [[David Platt (Coronation Street)|David Platt]] ([[Jack P. Shepherd]]) gets chatting to when she moves into the flat above the bookies. She then offers David a part-time job with flexible hours and good money, which he accepts. David tells his mother [[Gail McIntyre|Gail]] ([[Helen Worth]]) that he is walking Jo's dog for her. Meanwhile, David tells [[Craig Harris (Coronation Street)|Craig Harris]] ([[Richard Fleeshman]]) that dog walking is only part of his job for Jo. He shows Craig the cannabis farm which Jo has installed in her flat and pays him to look after.\n\nThe police later raid Jo's flat and discover the drugs. David is arrested but is later released when he insists that he knew nothing about the drugs. Jo disappears and is never seen again.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Michelle Connor==\n{{Main|Michelle Connor}}\n\n==DS Phil Campbell==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n| name = DS Phil Campbell\n| first = 9 June 2006\n| last = 28 April 2008\n| years = 2006\u20132008\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation = [[Police Officer]]\n| portrayer  = Gary Cargill\n| born =\n}}\n'''Detective Sergeant Phil Campbell''' is a police officer. Campbell is first seen investigating a hit-and-run accident in which an elderly man was killed. He arrests [[Steve McDonald (Coronation Street)|Steve McDonald]] ([[Simon Gregson]]) for causing death by dangerous driving and Steve implicates his girlfriend [[Ronnie Clayton (Coronation Street)|Ronnie Clayton]] ([[Emma Stansfield]]) who is the actual culprit and is subsequently arrested. The following month, Campbell questions [[Danny Baldwin]] ([[Bradley Walsh]]) on suspicion of fraud after it is revealed he had forged a will in order to get his father [[Mike Baldwin (Coronation Street)|Mike]] ([[Johnny Briggs (actor)|Johnny Briggs]]), who suffered from Alzheimers disease, to leave him his factory. In January 2007, Campbell arrests [[Tracy Barlow]] ([[Kate Ford]]) and charges her with assaulting [[Charlie Stubbs (Coronation Street)|Charlie Stubbs]] ([[Bill Ward (actor)|Bill Ward]]). After Charlie dies of his injuries, Campbell charges Tracy with murder. Campbell questions Tracy's neighbours [[Claire Peacock]] ([[Julia Haworth]]) and [[Gail McIntyre|Gail Platt]] ([[Helen Worth]]) both of whom claim Charlie was subjecting Tracy to domestic violence and abuse. Campbell also questions Charlie's friend [[Jason Grimshaw]] ([[Ryan Thomas]]) who tells them that Tracy staged a deliberate row in order to get the police involved. [[David Platt (Coronation Street)|David Platt]] ([[Jack P. Shepherd]]) later visits the police station and tells Campbell that he witnessed Tracy kill Charlie in self-defence after he had attacked her with a knife. David also tells Campbell that Charlie had attempted to abduct him in his van and had also attempted to drown him in his bathtub. Campbell later speaks to [[Liam Connor]] ([[Rob James-Collier]]) who witnessed the abduction attempt and [[Maria Connor|Maria Sutherland]] ([[Samia Ghadie]]) who witnessed the attempted drowning and they both back David's story up. Campbell was last seen investigating the arson attack at [[Leanne Battersby]]'s ([[Jane Danson]]) restaurant \"Valandros\" committed by chef [[Paul Clayton (Coronation Street)|Paul Clayton]] ([[Tom Hudson (English actor)|Tom Hudson]]). After Paul reports himself and Leanne to the police, Campbell arrests Leanne and questions her but her boyfriend [[Dan Mason]] ([[Matthew Crompton]]) gives her an alibi.\n\nIn October 2004, Cargill played a police officer called DC Paul Campbell, who arrested [[Dev Alahan|Dev]] ([[Jimmi Harkishin]]) and [[Sunita Alahan]] ([[Shobna Gulati]]) on their wedding day on suspicion of being illegal immigrants and falsely marrying to gain a visa. It is not known whether this was the same character under a different name. \n{{Clear}}\n\n==Brian Tully==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Brian Tully|\nfirst=5 June 2006|\nlast=18 June 2006|\n|classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; guest]]\n|portrayer=[[Tim Healy (actor)|Tim Healy]]|\n|wife=[[Maureen Tully]] (1975\u20132005)|\n|daughters=Angela Tully\n|stepsons =[[Sean Tully]]\n}}\n'''Brian Tully''' thinks that [[Sean Tully]] ([[Antony Cotton]]) is his son but left when he realized that he isn't. In 2006, Sean begins visiting his father until he learns the truth.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Maureen Tully==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Maureen Tully|\nfirst=26 June 2006|\nlast=28 June 2006|\nportrayer=[[Susan Brown (English actress)|Susan Brown]]|\nhusband=[[Brian Tully]] (1975\u20132005)|\nsons=[[Sean Tully]]|\ndaughters=Angela Tully|\nsisters=Angie|\ngrandsons=[[Dylan Wilson]]|\nclassification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n}}\n'''Maureen Tully''' is [[Sean Tully]]'s ([[Antony Cotton]]) mother. She lies to her son saying that [[Brian Tully]] ([[Tim Healy (actor)|Tim Healy]]) is his real father, Sean's real father is unknown, but she then tells him it was a plumber named Paul Jones that she had met at a dance.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Freddie Peacock==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Freddie Peacock\n|introducer=[[Steve November|Steve Frost]]\n|first=17 July 2006\n|last=14 January 2011\n|years=2006\u20132011\n|classification=[[List of past Coronation Street characters#C|Former; recurring]]\n|born=17 July 2006\n|home=France\n|father=[[Ashley Peacock]]\n|mother=[[Claire Peacock]]\n|brothers= [[Joshua Peacock]] (adoptive)\n|grandfathers =[[Fred Elliott]]\n|grandmothers = [[Yvonne Casey]]<br>[[Kathleen Gutteridge]]<br>[[Beryl Peacock]] (adoptive)\n|relatives = [[Beryl Peacock]]\n|portrayer=Jack & Jake Rogers (2006)<br>Dylan & Hayden Whitbread (2006\u20132009)<br>Lewis & Niall Beresford (2009\u20132011)\n| alias = Thomas Peacock\n|\n}}\n\n'''Frederick Thomas \"Freddie\" Peacock''' (also '''Thomas Duncan Peacock''') is the son of [[Ashley Peacock|Ashley]] ([[Steven Arnold]]) and [[Claire Peacock]] ([[Julia Haworth]]). On Christmas Day 2005, Claire tells Ashley that she is two months pregnant, and months later, Freddie is born on 17 July 2006. Claire suffers from [[post natal depression]] after Freddie is born, refusing to believe that Freddie is her child. On one occasion, she pushes his pram into the path of an oncoming vehicle and tries to return him to the hospital. She is sectioned until she is well enough to come home.\n\nIn October 2006, Claire announces that she would like to change his name from Thomas to Freddie, after his paternal grandfather [[Fred Elliott]] ([[John Savident]]) who died the week before. In December 2006, he is christened Frederick Thomas with [[Eileen Grimshaw]] ([[Sue Cleaver]]) as godmother and [[Roy Cropper]] ([[David Neilson]]) as his godfather.\n\nIn May 2007, a fire starts in Freddie's bedroom. Claire is rescued from the burning building but Freddie is not found until later that day, wrapped up in a local park. It is revealed that the fire was started deliberately by use of an accelerant. Originally, this storyline was to last several months but was rewritten to avoid upsetting the family of [[Madeleine McCann]], who disappeared two weeks previously. In September 2007, the identity of Freddie's abductor is revealed to be Claire's former friend, [[Casey Carswell]] ([[Zoe Henry]]). Casey abducts Freddie and takes him to the balcony of her flat where she threatens to jump with him. Freddie is rescued unharmed and Casey is arrested.\n\nWhen a tram crashes on to the Street on 6 December 2010, Ashley is killed when the roof of 'The Joinery' Bar collapses and he is crushed by the debris. Freddie and Joshua are subsequently left without a father. In January 2011, Claire attacks [[Tracy Barlow]] ([[Kate Ford]]) after she makes insulting remarks about Ashley and after [[Becky McDonald]] ([[Katherine Kelly (actress)|Katherine Kelly]]) is arrested for assaulting Tracy and leaving her for dead, she confesses to the police. Her friends persuade her to leave the country to avoid a prison sentence and take her sons with her. Freddie, Claire and Joshua leave for France on 14 January 2011.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Mr. Griffin==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Mr. Griffin\n|portrayer=Roger Morlidge\n|introducer=[[Steve Frost]] (2006)<br> Kim Crowther (2009) <br> [[Kate Oates]] (2016)\n|years = 2006\u20132007, 2009, 2016\n|first = 18 June 2006\n|last = \n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n|occupation=Headmaster\n}}\n'''Mr. Griffin''' is the Headmaster at Weatherfield High and commonly appears in storylines concerning [[David Platt (Coronation Street)|David Platt]] ([[Jack P. Shepherd]]) when he attends the school, and more recently [[Chesney Brown]] ([[Sam Aston]]). Mr. Griffin made his most recent appearance when Chesney's sister [[Fiz Brown]] ([[Jennie McAlpine]]) was about to punch [[Kenzie Judd]] (Jack Cooper) for bullying him. Mr. Griffin makes another appearance in September 2016 at a meeting to deal with [[List of Coronation Street characters (2016)#Lauren|Lauren]] ([[Shannon Flynn]])  for bullying [[Bethany Platt]] ([[Lucy Fallon]]) .<ref name=\"DavidgetsrevengeonbullyLauren\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-08-30/coronation-street-david-gets-revenge-on-bully-lauren---by-hacking-at-her-hair-with-the-shears|title=Coronation Street: David gets revenge on bully Lauren - by hacking at her hair with the shears!|last=MacCarthy|first=Kate|date=30 August 2016|work=[[Radio Times]]|publisher=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Cameron McIntyre==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n|name=Cameron McIntyre\n|portrayer=Ryan Cook\n|duration=2006\n|first = 24 July 2006\n|last = 7 August 2006\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n|occupation=Student\n}}\n'''Cameron McIntyre''' is a school friend of [[Chesney Brown]] ([[Sam Aston]]) and [[Sophie Webster]] ([[Brooke Vincent]]), often causing trouble.\n\nWhen he first appears, Sophie doesn't really like him. Later that day, the trio prank-call all the contacts on Sophie's mother's [[Sally Webster|Sally]]'s ([[Sally Dynevor]]) phone, and Sophie begins to develop a crush on him. On Chesney's 12th birthday party, Sophie is quietly upset that Cameron can't attend. However, to Sophie's relief, he turns up later on with a card for Chesney, and they go out again. Later on, Sophie, Chesney and Cameron hang out at Sophie's house to watch Chesney's step-dad's horror film. The film is found by Sally who orders the trio outside to play, annoying Chesney's mother [[Cilla Battersby-Brown|Cilla]] ([[Wendi Peters]]). In the ginnel later that week, Sophie and Chesney meet up with Cameron again and soon find out he has cigarettes in hand. Chesney refuses to smoke, but Sophie takes a cigarette but unfortunately, Sally smells tobacco and sends Chesney away as he hides the cigarettes. Cameron and Chesney briefly fall out, but become friends again and go to watch films with Sophie. The trio are caught again by Sally and Chesney is sent packing. When Sally discovers \u00a35 is missing from her money, she assumes Chesney stole it. Sophie is the one who took the money to buy cigarettes for her and Cameron, and when Sophie tells Cameron that she is going to tell her mother what happened, he makes an excuse to go home to avoid getting into trouble and runs away from the street, leaving Sophie devastated.\n\nCameron is no relation to [[Joe McIntyre (Coronation Street)|Joe]] ([[Reece Dinsdale]]) and [[Tina McIntyre]] ([[Michelle Keegan]]).\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Liam Connor==\n{{Main|Liam Connor}}\n\n==Ryan Connor==\n{{Main|Ryan Connor}}\n\n==Paul Connor==\n{{Main|Paul Connor (Coronation Street)}}\n\n==Carla Connor==\n{{Main|Carla Connor}}\n\n==Slug==\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = Coronation Street\n| name = Slug\n| portrayer = [[Marshall Lancaster]]\n| introducer = [[Steve November|Steve Frost]]\n| first = 18 December 2006\n| last = 7 September 2009\n| years = 2006\u20132007, 2009\n| born = 1977\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n| occupation = Drug dealer\n}}\n'''Slug''' (real name '''Neil Ackroyd''') is an old friend of [[Becky Granger]]'s ([[Katherine Kelly (actress)|Katherine Kelly]]), who first appears in December 2006. He is a drug dealer and user who takes advantage of Becky. In June 2009 Slug returns, apparently a reformed man. It is later revealed that he is working for DC Hooch, a police officer who is an enemy of Becky's and wants her in prison. Slug plants drugs on Becky and she is subsequently arrested. Becky's fianc\u00e9 [[Steve McDonald (Coronation Street)|Steve McDonald]] ([[Simon Gregson]]) and his colleague and friend [[Lloyd Mullaney]] ([[Craig Charles]]) find out about Slug's involvement and track him down. They bundle him into a car, drive him back to the street and question him. When they bring him to Hooch, Hooch decides to drop the charges, scared Slug will tell the police about him.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Sonny Dhillon==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n| name = Sonny Dhillon\n| first = 22 December 2006\n| last = 11 March 2007\n| portrayer  = [[Pal Aron]]\n| romances = [[Michelle Connor]] (2006-2007)\n| classification  = [[List of Coronation Street characters#past characters|Former; recurring]]\n}}\n'''Sundeep \"Sonny\" Dhillon''' is  played by [[Pal Aron]]. Sonny is [[Michelle Connor]]'s ([[Kym Marsh]]) millionaire boyfriend. It comes to light that Sonny has relationship history with [[Sean Tully]] ([[Antony Cotton]]), in that they had previously been dating, with Sonny admitting to being [[bisexual]]. On the Streetcars lads' night out [[Steve McDonald (Coronation Street)|Steve McDonald]] ([[Simon Gregson]]) spots Sean and Sonny kissing. In late February 2007, Sonny proposes to Michelle. While she is in The Rovers celebrating, a jealous Steve tells her that Sonny is gay, however, she does not believe him. When Michelle's brother [[Liam Connor]] ([[Rob James-Collier]]) hears Steve's allegation, he confronts him, with Steve sticking by what he saw. An unsure Liam questions Sean at work with Sean claiming nothing is going on. The same day, Liam and his brother [[Paul Connor (Coronation Street)|Paul]] ([[Sean Gallagher (actor)|Sean Gallagher]]) confront Sean a second time, forcing him to tell the truth. They then frogmarch Sean to the pub to tell Michelle the truth. Sean does so, with Michelle bursting into tears, shocked at what she is hearing. An oblivious Sonny arrives at Michelle's that night, ready to take her out. A crying Michelle tells Sonny she knows about him and Sean, before giving him back her engagement ring. Sonny then leaves in shame.\n\nWhen Michelle's son [[Ryan Connor]] ([[Ben Thompson (actor)|Ben Thompson]]) discovers the gay affair, he steals Sonny's car and takes it for a [[Joyride (crime)|joyride]]. The police find out but Sonny doesn't press charges. After Michelle discovers the affair, Sonny goes to Sean but Sean rejected him. Sonny walks out of number 11 and hasn't been seen since.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Holly Grimshaw==\n{{Infobox soap character\n|series=[[Coronation Street]]\n| name = Holly Grimshaw \n| first = 25 December 2006\n| last = 25 April 2007\n| years = 2006&ndash;2007\n|introducer = [[Steve Frost]]\n|classification = [[List of past Coronation Street characters#G|Former; recurring]]\n| portrayer  = Amelia Caudwell<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macclesfield-live.co.uk/news/local-news/swapping-craig-road-for-corrie-2535100|title=Swapping Craig Road for Corrie|date=2007-03-28|work=Macclesfield Express}}</ref>\n| born = August 2006\n| mother = Emma\n| father = [[Charlie Stubbs (Coronation Street)|Charlie Stubbs]]\n| alias = Chloe\n}}\n\n'''Holly Grimshaw''' (real name '''Chloe''') first appears on Christmas Day 2006 when her mother Emma ([[Stephanie Waring]]) dumps her on [[Jason Grimshaw]] ([[Ryan Thomas]]) claiming that he is her father, following a one-night stand. Jason's mother [[Eileen Grimshaw|Eileen]] ([[Sue Cleaver]]) bonds with her new granddaughter, who they name Holly because of the day she arrived. Jason bonds with her too and enjoys being a father and a family with his fianc\u00e9e [[Sarah Platt]] ([[Tina O'Brien]]) and her daughter,  [[Bethany Platt|Bethany]].\n\nWhen [[Charlie Stubbs (Coronation Street)|Charlie Stubbs]] ([[Bill Ward (actor)|Bill Ward]]) is murdered in January 2007, Jason is upset as Charlie was one of his closest friends. However, [[Tracy Barlow]] ([[Kate Ford]])'s trial is in the newspaper. Holly's mother, Emma, reads about it and realises that Charlie is Holly's father, not Jason. She returns for her daughter but Eileen initially refuses to give her back. She threatens to go for legal custody but is persuaded to return her on 25 April 2007 {{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coronation Street characters}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Coronation Street characters|2006]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2006|*, Coronation Street]]\n[[Category:2006 in British television|Coronation Street]]\n", "name_user": "Conquistador2k6", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMaureen Tully", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Coronation_Street_characters_(2006)"}
